text:
It's a one of a kind experience.  A sandbox for the kiddies, very large outdoor area with casual picnic and regular tables.  Issues: Not enough table umbrellas on a hot day, no dogs allowed (really?), and it's on the beach, but has bushes so tall you can't really see the sand.  For sunsets, for sure, yes.

Get in line.  Counter ordering, not full-service, is what causes the long line to be formed.  Allow 30 mins to get thru it.  The menu has a mix of fast foods, sandwiches, salads, and on Sunday - BBQ (I think 11a-3p).

I got an order of the Shrimp Tacos ($9.95) -- grilled tequila-lime shrimp, shredded cabbage, tomato, avocado, cilantro cream sauce, handmade corn tortillas, chips, pico de gallo.  The chips were the best thing on the plate.  The shrimp was just okay (costco?), but mainly the problem was it swimming in the cream sauce.  No bueno.  (2.5 stars)

My gf ordered the Beach Club Sandwich ($7.50), and had to send it back...so darn greasy.  She got a salad instead, and it was the wrong one and way too simple at that.  Not worth getting back to the counter and waiting again, so she ate it like a good sport.  Again, no service so you are forced to do it yourself.

If you have small kids and need a break from it all, this is your place.  Overall, I wouldn't come here for the food, or the live band (ma & pa band doing 1970's covers).

text: Priority is given to take out orders so kitchen gets backed up and dine in patrons are given poor service. I would order to go- we saw many people come and go with bags of food while we waited. Maybe order ahead and then sit down- either way your food will probably be cold. We were told kitchen was backed up with to go orders but when our food finally arrived it was cold. Maybe they should ditch the sit down service and do what they do best- Maybe even get a drive thru like Taco Bell!

text: Not even sure how to rate this. Best sushi around with the stupidest policy ever... If you show up in person they take your number and then call you when your space in line comes up. Totally get it. Worked good last night for us. Tonight I am 3 miles down the road and called and asked the mgr (who refused to give me his name, really???) if I could put my name in so they could call me when a spot was ready. I didn't want to be ahead of anyone just didn't want to drive 3 miles to put my name in (when I was told the wait was 2 hours). Why would you ask someone to drive down so they can tell you "we will call you when we have you space available... In two hours". Completely stupid. I'm glad they are successfully and full of themselves but making exceptions for folks that don't want to waste time is stupid. Especially when they won't  take Reservations.

text:
This place was insanely good. It was quite possibly one of the best bites of food I've ever had in my entire life. I went here in June and I am still thinking about the food and I think I can still remember most of what I ate.

1 - the zensai had three elements: seafood, beef, and vegetables. Each representing the ocean, plains, and mountains respectively. The seafood (shrimp, abalone, and octopus) was amazing, each having distinct flavor and texture and was so interesting paired with the gelatinous chicken soup. The pickled vegetables were the highlight of this course. They were extremely flavorful and refreshing. 

2 - the owan was hands down the most delicate and flavorful soup I have ever had in my entire life. I legit still vividly remember the taste after months. The soup was a simple katsuobushi dashi that tasted very much like bonito but complex. I think the sesame oil that they finished it with came through with a pleasant nuttiness that didn't overpower the soup but made it more full bodied. The black cod was buttery and tender, still having it's fish characteristics as well. The shiitake mushroom was so umami rich and flavorful, you could taste the tare it was in but it didn't bleed it's flavors to the other parts of the dish in such a way that it overpowered. It just kinda woke you up in a good way. The egg was fun, almost like noodles. The bamboo shoot had a nice crunch that was a good contrast from the rest of the soup and the tomato and sprout introduced a much needed acidity and freshness and brought the whole course together. 

3 - the mukouzuke was also good. We had king mackerel, amberjack, and uni. These were really good cuts of fish and the house made ponzu was really good. I forget which one, but one of these fish were lightly smoked and the other was wrapped in kombu and both these techniques showed through as the kombu made the texture of the fish firmer and the lightly smoked one had a nice aroma to it. The highlight of this dish was the difference in the uni. I've had lots of uni and I am a big advocate for eating local purple urchin that have ravaged our coast. They served uni from hokkaido and santa barbara (I believe both were red urchin). The little hokkaido uni were so much sweeter and now I understand the difference and why people pay a premium for this. I still think eating local uni is more sustainable though!

4 - Ah the yakimono is the reason why this review was a 4 star. When I ordered the wagyu, I was expecting to taste wagyu beef. Instead the slices of meat tasted like chinese sausage. The marinade and cooking process just did not do the beef justice. I wish it was better because I think this dish single handedly made the experience slightly disappointing.

5 - For the shiizakana, I got the freshwater eel. It was a but better than the eel I can get in store but still quite good. I think getting this and the wagyu was a mistake, as their flavor profiles were similar. I should have gotten something that contrasted. The monkfish liver was very interesting and good though!

6 - The shokuji was a nice breath of fresh air after all those sweet meaty dishes. I think the ama ebi was extremely good. Best sweet shrimp I've ever had. It tasted very fresh. The scallop nigiri was also very good! I haven't had scallops served this way and it was pleasant. Finally, the quail egg and yam hit home. It tasted exactly like natto and egg mixed in rice but with a little bit more complexity and freshness. It was inspiring to say the least.

7 - To finish it all off, the kanmi. Honestly, coming into the restaurant, my friends and I were thinking "oh it's a 6 course meal plus dessert" just cuz that's kinda how our restaurant experiences were like. But man, we were seriously wrong. The mochi was ridiculously good. The first one with red bean and strawberry was eye-opening. The red bean texture was great and the mochi had just the right amount of sweetness and the texture was nice and chewy. The second one with mint was really good and the mint leaf garnish just tied the two mochi together so well. I never thought I'd have the best mochi in my life at this restaurant. If I could criticize anything, it would be that the plate choice was interesting because the color and shape of the plate kinda clashed with the triangular shape and orange color of the mochi. 

Besides the food, the service was fantastic. I really enjoyed the side conversations we had with the servers. The tea was very good. And they also gave our table enough space to have our own conversations without feeling like we were being hawked over. 

The decor of the place is nice and feels very elegant, but welcoming. 

Overall, can't wait to go again some day! 

I don't have any pictures because my phone camera is broken. You can see the pics in other people's photos though!

text: FINALLY tried Mizza and wasn't disappointed. Loved (almost) everything we ordered, great atmosphere, excellent service, and the perfect setting for a lovely bday Sunday. The burrata & heirloom tomatoes app was scrumptious, the salmon pasta, very flavorful and the salmon perfectly cooked, I liked the toppings of the veggie pizza but wasn't a super fan of the crust (doesn't mean I won't come back and try another pizza on their menu ) and the cannoli was good although that dessert in general isn't my fave (it was my bf's bday so had to get what he wanted ). The flourless chocolate cake and limoncello cake are what I'll try next time. Had a great time and will be back. Gave it 4 stars just cuz I wasn't that excited about the pizza and that's something they're supposed to so well. Would recommend the restaurant though!

text:
Bottom line: quick, very tasty food at rock-bottom prices.

What I'm reviewing here is the deli.  When you walk into this place, you might not even realize there's a deli.  In fact, I'd gone to the market several times over the years without really paying attention to the deli, partly because it used to be that the deli was only open for a few hours around lunchtime.  But a few months ago, walking by, I saw a sign saying the deli was now staying open until midnight.  I live nearby, so I thought I'd give it a try.

And man, I'm glad I did!  This place is a real diamond in the rough.  I've gone there about half a dozen times now, and I've yet to be disappointed.  It's way better than you'd expect from a little deli window in the back of a mini-mart.

Their menu is considerably more extensive than the typical hole-in-the-wall deli; it's more like what you'd see at a no-frills restaurant.  "Deli" is actually kind of a misnomer, since most of the stuff on the menu is Mexican food.  And they've got it all: not just burritos and tacos, but stuff like enchiladas and even tamales that you wouldn't expect to find at a place like this.  On top of that they have some basic American-style fare like salads, burgers, and sandwiches (none of which I've tried yet), plus, interestingly, a few Middle Eastern options: falafel, shawarma, and kibbe.

So far I've tried the tacos, burritos, taquitos, and tamales, plus the shawarma.  Everything has been top notch.  The burritos are big enough that I can get two meals out of one.  (The chile verde is especially tasty.)  I worked my way up to the tamales, because, come on, tamales are an ace item.  But they delivered yet again.  All the Mexican items have really flavorful sauces.  Service is always friendly and quick, and you can ask them to add this or hold that and get your order just so.  

The thing that seals the deal, though, is the prices.  The food is about as inexpensive as you can get around here.  Pretty much everything on the menu is $5.99.  They also have a little "VIP card" that you can get stamped when you buy stuff, and after you buy 5 you get the 6th free.

I'm the type of guy for whom good food tastes better when I know it's cheap.  This, combined with the fact that Presidio is only 5 blocks from my apartment, has made it my go-to place when I come home tired and want some warm food but have nothing to cook.  I foresee myself coming back here again and again.

(Edit: Yes, the prices have now gone up.  Everything went up by one dollar.  Everything is still a dang good deal at that price.)

text:
Sama Sama opened on Tuesday and it looked like good words have gotten out and they were quite busy during lunch.  They still haven't hang up a sign yet, but you can see they stamp their name proudly on the paper table liners.  I am not a connoisseur of Indonesian food and can't comment on the authenticity, but the mix of fraqrant ingredients, especially the house made sambals were excellent.  Everything is served in appetizer size, so with a couple of friends, you can try one of everything on the menu without breaking the bank.

chicken sate-two small skewers of chicken and scallion with a sweet and savory glaze were more heavily seasoned than the typical Thai chicken sate.     

shrimp chips-a very common Asian snack.  I always like to watch the dry chips unfold, puff up, and turn opaque in the hot oil.  Sama Sama served the chips with a sweet peanut dipping sauce and a spicy limey coconut sambal.   

duck confit fried rice-it looked very much like kimchi fried rice, but with different seasoning, not tangy and less spicy.  Its Asian comfort food and my only complaints are it needed a little more salt and a lot more duck meat.

corn fritter-I liked this version more than Tap Thai's.  There were minimal binders, just lots of sweet corns.  The spicy tomato sambal provided a refreshing contrast with the fried corns.  

tempeh taco-glazed with a sweet soy based sauce, garnished with micro cilantro, and sandwiched in between a crispy wonton wrapper.  These fusion bite size tacos were satisfying as well.           

There seemed to be some major confusion as to which table ordered what and the wait for food was long as you watch plate after plate of delicious food pass you by.  I suggest they take a lesson from a la carte dim sum restaurants, print an extra copy of receipt to set on the table and as the servers deliver the plate, they scratch off dishes from the receipt.

text:
Eating at Alcazar Tapas Bar is like being invited into Alvaro's home for dinner. Alvaro is the restaurant's owner who attentively waits on his guests as well, offering fantastic suggestions and clearly demonstrating his love for food. He is an outstanding host.

My husband selected this restaurant for our 2 year wedding anniversary and what a perfect choice it was! It is a quaint, intimate restaurant with flavorful food that has you appreciating every bite. 

Our choices consisted of the following: 
Tapa al la Dana - Excellent starter, but better for a larger group instead of two people.
Sweet Potato Fries - Done perfectly. I've had my share of these and Alvaro hit the mark. 
Gambas Alcazar - A simple yet tasty shrimp dish. It's good, but didn't blow me out of the water. The Gambas Chipotle is more flavorful I'd imagine.
Ahi Tuna sashima - Divine and I'm afraid of raw fish!
Filet con Crema - AMAZING. Hit the spot. 

We sealed the deal with some fresh honey, lemon ginger hot tea. It was incredible combined with an apple dessert that had the perfect level of sweetness. 

We will definitely be coming back here on our visits to Santa Barbara.

text: We were walking down State Street for the first time and saw a bunch of people eating delicious-looking charcuterie and drinking wine, so we decided we had to try it out--so glad we did. The food was incredibly flavorful (bonus points for presentation). Their menu seems to shift seasonally (what we saw on Yelp posted 2 months ago wasn't all the same, although they definitely seem to have their standards like the Yoga Pants Salad - which we didn't have but looked delicious). We ordered the Aubergine Rilettes (eggplant tapenade served with a bunch of pickled veggies, whole grain mustard, and bread - could've used even more bread), the Confit Tomatoes (YUM - a jar of confit tomatoes served with more warmed bread), and the Beech Ceviche (fantastic - I'd never had beech mushrooms before and I didn't miss the seafood one bit). Plus a large cookie for dessert! My husband had the Sunshine Spritz which we think had aperol and some sort of vanilla in it (not totally sure - a little sweeter than he expected, could've been what wine they used) and I had a strawberry shrub (refreshing and tart). Being 6 months pregnant I couldn't imbibe, but look forward to coming back to try some of their natural wines the next time we're in town. Really enjoyed sitting along state street on a warm day - and the servers/hostess were all extremely nice and accommodating.

text:
As many people know already, I'm somewhat of a coffee snob. I had been wanting to try and support H&G since they recently opened during COVID. It is hidden within the passages of Paseo Nuevo, sharing the same space with ParadICE (Hint: Enter the outdoor mall off State Street across from the Salt Caves) .

I finally swung in here to socially distance meet up with a close friend. We both were sold on trying their Maple Sea Salt Latte with oat milk. I mean...'Tis the season! Both were made perfectly smooth, warm (not over or under steamed) and with beautiful foam art to top it off. It was also not overly sweet but jussssst right, while still maintaining the taste and aroma of espresso. Goldilocks approved!

I also wanted to fill my empty stomach with something solid before digesting coffee. I went with the "Queen Bee" toast which had peanut butter, banana slices, chia seeds and honey.  For me personally, any place that has menu options like "Beez Nutz" and "Queen Bee" has my vote! The toast had a crunchy crust but soft interior. I'm a big fan of PB&Js so this one won my heart over.

Head over here and support H&G. They serve delicious Caje Roastery coffee and have extremely friend employees.

text:
Today was my first visit to Three Pickles Sandwich Deli located in the City of Goleta, CA.  My first impression was that is was seated in a very nice area; nestled deep in a large parking lot surrounded by several businesses.  Another thing that captured my attention was the colorful umbrellas which denoted outside seating; a plus on a beautiful day. 

The sandwich menu was nothing out of the normal and the wait time time to order was a little long. 

I came to understand the name of the deli once I realized they offered three types of pickles: kosher, dill and pepper chilies . 

Today I ordered a whole sandwich: roasted turkey on a sub roll, chips and a fountain drink.  My total was $12.00.  My meal was sufficient and actually I only consumed half of what I ordered

If you prefer salads or soups, no worries...the deli offers a variety: menu attached in photos.  It is my understanding the deli has other locations such as downtown Santa Barbara.  The Deli offers catering, online and phone in orders!!  

I enjoyed my first experience and the only thing that kept me from giving it a 5 star was the location of the restroom which is located in the building adjacent to the deli.

text:
Don't get me wrong- the food is excellent - well, as much as I could allow myself to eat..  I went there for my first time this afternoon on my lunch break from work.  I ordered the Tijuana and a side of fries to bring back to work and share.  I paid with my card, and shortly after the man behind the register handled my card and the register, he took a towel and wiped a counter clean.  After that I watched as he took his unwashed hands and dug into a big salad bowl with his HANDS and grabbed the lettuce w/ dressing and put a handful on a plate to go out.  I almost vomited on the spot.  He wasn't the only one who did it.  Another girl behind the counter also handled money and multiple plates and placed her hands on the dirty counter and then grabbed a handful of salad to put on a plate, shaking her hand to make sure all the lettuce got off.  This happened multiple times.  I must have made a face behind the glass because when I received my food, the guy used tongs to put salad on my plate.  Needless to say, I was VERY cautious about eating my food, and halfway through it, was so grossed out I threw it away.  Just saying - you should probably follow basic kitchen cleanliness guidelines if everyone can see through a big glass window into your kitchen. 

I'd like to try the food again but I'm not sure I actually will.  Its disappointing as I have heard many great things.

text:
My friends and I were celebrating and so we decided to head on over to Shaker Mill on a Saturday evening. The menu is a QR code that you scan and they provide hand sanitizer at the front

I ordered the Mango Lassi and it was probably my favorite drink of the night. Super refreshing and light but on the smaller side.

My friends ordered the Hemingway? and the oceanside. I tried them and personally they weren't to my liking. It honestly just tasted like alcohol and seltzer to me

We ordered the Miami Vice too and it was HUGE. The waiter warned us it was meant for two but I thought I'd be okay drinking it on my own. well, I was wrong! I was able to finish it but man...it was strong. They didn't actually mix the pina colada and strawberry daiquiri super well so I mixed it myself and it tasted pretty good after! 

they use paper straws which was actually a bit difficult in the Miami Vice but it was fine in the other drinks. the price was standard but they don't have happy hour. cubaneo is in the same area/building so if you're looking for a bite, you can order from them

text:
Delicious soup/salad combo!  Excellent oven roasted chicken sandwich!

I had zero expectations of this little spot.  It's unassuming - you walk up to the counter and order and wait for your food to come out.  And when it does - wow - it knocked my socks off!  There's a nice, outdoor patio to enjoy your food.

Next to the register is a display case with beautiful, sweet treats.  I didn't try any, but they sure looked tempting!

I will definitely be back!  A decent price point, as well!

text:
Are here while I stayed there this past week. Not my first time staying here, but I can say the service at the Bistro has taken a tumble. It was slow pretty much all times I at there during the week to a point I almost actually got up and left at one point because 15 minutes went by before anyone even came to ask me what I wanted to drink. We had a lunch group of 4 and though the food came out decent timed, our waitress never once came to check on us or the food, and when we wanted to leave we asked a random guy walking by to get our checks because our waitress was MIA.

This is a place that should have high standards. The food is great, if you have nothing to do but wait on the crummy service.

text:
This place was great! The sushi was even better the second time coming here! The reason why this isn't getting 5 stars is because the fish was a bit bland and not too fresh the first time. However, the hamachi sashimi was perfect the second time!

The hostess was funny, and she told us funny stories back from when she was in vietnam, but she was perhaps, too imposing. When we asked to order another roll, she didn't bother bringing the menu. She just recommended a roll, and we went with it.

I'll be coming back sometime before the school year ends :)

text:
We picked a slightly breezy weekday to come and visit a winery, so we pretty much had the place to ourselves.  We came in and were greeted, and we were given some information about some of their tasting options.  We chose to sample 5 wines for 10 dollars.  The pace can be really fast, we slowed it down and were talking to the girl who gave us really honest answers about some of the places that we should try in Santa Barbara.  She also gave us suggestions on some bakeries and coffee shops to visit as well.
Overall the wine tasting was great, but the service really put this place over the top for me.

text: We went to the bar/cafe last night and got to enjoy the new wine on tap program they just implemented.  Incredible!  You can get full and half carafes of wine and as they explained, since the wineries don't have the cost of bottling/labels/etc, the savings is passed along.  Plus, with less waste, its more enviornmentally friendly.  We had a Melville Pinot Noir and the Margerum red blend.  We also shared the greek flatbread...delicious!

text:
Thomas Paine once noted:

"A thing moderately good is not so good as it ought to be. Moderation in temper is always a virtue; but moderation in principle is always a vice."


Moderation is a principal that does not play when talking about Lilly's tacos. I've pretty much had everything on the menu tacos, tacos, tacos from all parts of the cow, and really smelling and tasting cilantro, a spice that while simple to provide is usually not and if so, not fresh. Not at Lilly's: they know how to bring it.
And for the day after, really a great hangover cure...

Arriba!
Arriba!

text: My bf's sister lived a few buildings down from here, so we grabbed breakfast before heading out to paragliding. I ended up giving in to trying their Hummus Lemon Pepper Bagel since it was like the only one I could eat (allergies). I was hesitant because it didn't sound too appetizing, but it surprisingly was pretty good. They got cold brew on tap here too and the bagel "sandwiches" are filling! Solid breakfast spot if you're on the go, otherwise they have outdoor seating only.

text: A tiny bit of drive to get to but so worth it. Outdoor and indoor seating are offered and it's best to have a reso. We visited on a Wednesday without a reso but we still got offered such a great seat! An outdoor high top right next to the window and the bar. When the weather is perfect it makes the experience beautiful as it is so close to the ocean/dog beach. My salmon eggs Benedict were very fresh, delicious, and filling. My only critique being a suggestion on slicing the onions a lot thinner as they became a little overwhelming for my taste. My fiance ordered the Boathouse Omellete which had both lobster and shrimp stuffed inside of it. Although I didn't try it, it looked amazing and the chunks of lobster were huge. Overall, great food, great view, great service. We will return!

text: My two friends and I decided to eat Chick-fil-A after studying. When we arrive, everything seems normal.. UNTIL a cashier starts freaking out about something near the drink area (which is on their side). The cashier asks some guy with glasses, who is also a worker there, "what is that".. and guess what it was? A DAMN COCKROACH. So the cashier is telling the guy to kill it. The guy acts dumb as says "what are you talking about? I don't see anything.", gives her the death stare and pretend like all is great. Let me even mention how he used one of the food trays to kill/catch the cockroach. He failed because the cockroach kept on walking on the counter then up the wall. YOU BET THAT I DID NOT ORDER AFTER THAT. I am so glad I didn't though, and I feel bad for the guy who just ordered his food when all of that happened :(. My friends and I stepped to the side, because we were trying to decide on where else to go. Then you see the manager, sort of yelling at the cashier who pointed out the cockroach... I salute the cashier who freaked out about that, because it's a fucking restaurant. Wth.

text: We came right before they closed and they were so nice to still take us! The vibes are amazing and most of the tables have personal fire pits which is great in the evenings when it's chilly. We got a bottle of the Prosecco, an Irish mule, and an espresso martini. All of the drinks were great! The espresso martini was truly perfect. For meals we split the burrata/peach/prosciutto board, Fettuccine Bolognese, and the spicy shrimp starter. We also ordered the five cheese pizza to go and it was so good- it has hints of truffle oil and we loved it! We really enjoyed everything we ordered and loved the ambiance. Can't recommend stopping by enough!!

text:
I love the huge patio here, both times I've dined here we've opted to eat outside. Once because we had our dog with us (the patio is dog friendly) and once because it was just too nice outside to be sitting inside. They have a lot of tables around the fountain so you can watch the turtles while you eat! Bonus!

The service was great here, we never had to wait long for anything. Not only was our server checking in on us, so were other staff members. Their chips and salsa were so tasty we ended up getting refills of it, I could have easily made a meal of it! 

I got the fish tacos and since I couldn't decided on grilled or fried they were able to do one of each. Both were tasty, though the fried ones were slightly better (I mean, what isn't good fried). 

Viva is tucked away off of the main drag in a little courtyard so even if you opt to eat outside you aren't right on the street which is nice. Great option for lunch or dinner!

text:
My rating is for the taste of the food since that's what I care most about for a place in IV. Not going for fine dining or anything but the aesthetics of the place is appealing. 

This place improved much since it first opened though it still has areas of improvement which in sure they'll fix with more reviews. 

Service is great as usual but the owners probably need to hire one or two more workers for busy hours. 

I got the torikatsu plate and though the portion was big, it was made more suited toward vegetarians since the ratio of the chicken katsu to everything else is too small. In terms of the taste, the macaroni salad is not overwhelming or too creamy like other places. The Hawaiian slaw is only complete if you add one of their sauces which I highly recommend. Otherwise it's nothing too special even though it has its own unique flavor. The rice has furikake (sesame and seaweed) in it so that's a plus. The katsu and the accompanying sauce is the best part in my opinion since the katsu remained crispy and the sauce has a tang to it that makes it a fusion.

text:
A week before our wedding this past September our rehearsal dinner location fell through. We had 6 days to find a restaurant that would fit 30 people for a Friday night and reached out to Pizza Mizza. Sean immediately got back to us he and Kourtney put together the perfect dinner for us and we couldn't be more grateful for how it turned out.

We were set up on the patio and pizza and salads were brought out promptly. All our guests raved about the food and atmosphere. The waitstaff was very attentive and were quick to bring out more food and refill beverages. We couldn't be happier with the turnout and my parents were happy to have the leftovers for the next few days. So happy with both the food and the customer service.

energetic atmosphere, then The Sandbar is the place to go. Though I only came for food, as most restaurants close early in Santa Barbara, I was astounded by everything. text: It's hard to express my disappointment with my experience. My wife and I where unable to celebrate  our 20th anniversary together because of the pandemic. So I decided to surprise  her for her birthday with a trip to Santa Barbara where we could celebrate both occasions. What better place to be than on the beach at sunset at a restaurant that had great reviews. We new that there would be a wait and thats fine. What I want prepare for was pathetic excuses and terrible service! Saying your sorry every time you walk by to serve another table or seat new patrons doesn't mean Sh!t.  2 1/2 hours and flavorless food makes me wish I would have stayed in our hotel and eaten Spaghett'os and fish sticks. Thanks for nothing! I would write more but I have to go and console my crying wife!

text:
Kimchi, where do I begin?
First, 
quality of the ingredients is impeccable. The kimchi is quite traditional, with a brine flavor being indicative of home made fresh ingredients. The Daikon is superb with perfect consistent slicing. The Soon Dubu type soup has the spice I was looking for.
Second,
Having been an employee at a Korean BBQ and tried a various large chains (to judge the pecking order) I can tell you this menu is strong. Scottish Sushi Grade Salmon for the base meal price? No premium prices menu? This has a pescatarian option built into the menu. Although vegetarians who get dragged along with friends, you still will be eating primarily side dishes. The vegetable plate is generous with its full mushrooms, sweet onions, and zucchini.
Third and Lastly,
The service (the make or break for most newly aquatinted AYCE KBBQ diners) was strong but still needs refinement. Ask pointers if lost! People often over cook items or need to learn when to cut the meat (post not pre-cooked).
Synopsis: 
five star quality at a four star price point. Junior Varsity service team that will assuredly aim to please. Menu poised to answer all customer issues traditionally associated with KBBQ (too much selection, menu A/B options, no seafood).

text: So disappointed in this hotel as we were looking forward to a nice little getaway from home after being in lockdown for 6 months.  The hotel grounds are absolutely beautiful but the attitude of the staff leaves much to be desired. They are not helpful or friendly and never answer their phone at the front desk.  Prior to check in we requested extra towels, and a few toiletries, none of which were provided.   More than a few times we were chided for paying cash at the  onsite restaurant Bistro.  While paying for breakfast and leaving cash we were told that they are "not a bank and do not give change" while were taken back by this we just let our server know that no change was needed.  On the same day later on in the evening while paying for our dinner to go, another person said that cash was not accepted at the hotel due to covid.  We insisted and were giving a bit of attitude over it.  And to top it off our bed was horrible-lumpy and we had to walk down to the front desk to request a mattress be replaced.  When checking on the status of the bed, we encountered a young man who was quite irritated and could not give us status as to whether the bed was being replaced.  He said "I can't really give you details but I know its being taken are of".   Talk about 5 star service!  The only person who we felt actually cared was Ramon the housekeeping manager. He took the time to follow up with us and make sure the mattress was replaced.   Ramon is the one person who actually made us feel welcomed and cared about. The final insult was when they charged us an additional $400.00 in fees without informing us or sending us the final bill.  Upon asking for my folio 2 day later I found out they had charged my credit card the $400.00 in "phantom extra fees".  The money was refunded after they checked my account but nevertheless it did not feel right.  I wonder how often this occurs at this hotel.  If you are looking to be pampered and get away from all the noise go somewhere else because at this hotel the majority of the employees don't want to be bothered by you and your requests.

text: Amazing experience. Becka was our server. This was our first experience in a restaurant setting since the quarantine. text:
I have been to Alcazar twice and the first time it was great and the 2nd time just OK.
The first time we were greeted and waited on by what we believed to be either a manager or owner, and the experience was nice.  It brought us back - that and the delicious food.  Yes, agreed portions are appetizer size and prices are for entrees so that is the only drawback.  Dcor is relative to your taste; I happen to like the red walls, slightly dark, lounge-like feel, and the projection screen is a cool quirky touch.
2nd time there our server was indifferent and disconnected, so we basically just enjoyed our food, our company, and left.  Will give them another try - 3rd time will either be a charm or a strike out.  It is nice though to have someplace different in an area with a plethora of Mexican/Latin eateries.

text:
This is one of the best lunch deals on downtown State Street, price-wise.
A 12" pizza, baked right in front of you, for $7. That'll get you one of several basic pizzas, and I quite like the margherita. 

Additional toppings are $1 each. 

I also tried one of the specialty pizzas and still preferred the basics. The guys at the ovens have a good guage on how long to bake the standards, but the more toppings there are, the more likely the crust won't come out perfect and the toppings can be watery. And it's seriously a difference of 5-15 seconds that determines whether you've got a nice crust, or one that's soft in the center, or burnt. I happen to like mine with a little char.

The pizza size is ample for one person, too much for me actually. Next time I'd share it with a friend and get dessert. The pistachio gelato is great, it had a pleasant roasted pistachio flavor, not overly sweet.

The interior reminds me of a food court that surrounds a shopping mall ice skating rink - a place for kids and friends to hang out and lots of top 40 music playing. Turns out the only time I've heard those songs are in memes, so I got confused when I'd recognize the tunes, but there would be no goats yelling. 

If you're short on time, this is a great downtown option. In and out in minutes if you get it to go, and the price can't be beat. They're supposed to be open late on the party nights too.

text: Chili's is usually good overall. I was disappointed with my experience this time. A friend and I decided to go grab dinner here and we were seated pretty quickly but a very friendly hostess. But that's where the fun ends. Upon being seated we waited like ten to fifteen minutes to put our drink order in. They came out in like half the time. And then we waited like another ten minutes or so to put our food order in. After that we said to ourselves that the food would come out in a reasonable amount of time but it did not. Our waiter would pass by and always say "food will be right out guys" but the food would not come out. I wanna put the time we waited for our food at about 20+ minutes just for it to be alright. I got a burger based on the waiters recommendation and nah it wasn't anything special it was alright. My friend got his usual witch is 3 different types of wings and said it was like always. Overall this chili's doesn't live up to the rep of other chili's, maybe I caught them on an off night? Overall nahhh I ain't coming back to this one

text:
I love me some Ike's. 

Having frequented their Northern California locations in years past I was ecstatic to hear they opened a location in Santa Barbara. With that said, Ike's has easily become a frequent destination for lunch. I have taken a few coworkers and they love it. The variety and the quality of the sandwiches is something to awe at. There is literally something here for everyone, guaranteed. 

Being an avid Dodgers fan I hold no restraint in choosing the Matt Cain or Madison Bumgarner sandwiches every time. They are must try's. Very flavorful and structured perfectly. A Dutch crunch roll is highly recommended. 

Additionally, not being a soda fan, I love their fountain sodas with their choice of using craft soda beverages rather than the typically large scale brands. Black Cherry is my favorite. 

Highly recommend anyone to check Ike's out. It is unlike any other Sandwich shop.

text:
Very cute place and great atmosphere. The food was tasty and seemed like the menu was well thought out. We had the onion rings and Pasilla Chile's as appetizers and as a vegetarian, I ordered the Brie cheese and apple fritter small plate. I usually don't like salads but this was very good. My other family members enjoyed their steaks (and the potatoes were filled with flavor!) The service felt a little rushed but I appreciate how on top of it she was.

One thing I would suggest is to add a specialty entree for a vegetarian. If my family comes for a steak dinner, I don't want just a pizza as a main entree choice (although I enjoyed my small plate). I'm sure other options were great I just wanted a specialty pot pie or something out of the ordinary since the other food was so good!!

text:
Talk about comfort food at its finest!

Mama's happens to be located in one of the most forgettable strip malls in town. For years, I'd drive right past it without putting a second thought into actually stopping. Boy, was I glad I stopped, though.

The interior is pretty bland and still reminds me a bit of the old Pizza Hut that once occupied the space. One does not come to a place like this to critique the interior, though, so that gets a pass.

The staff here are all very sweet and cordial, always smiling and helpful. This is primarily a take-out place, though they will serve you if you opt to dine at the location. I've found that the wait time is pretty short, which is a plus if I'm in a hurry. The sandwiches and soups I've ordered have all been prepared very well, full of flavor and color. I recommend ordering a cup of their chicken pozole soup, paired with bread, on a cold day - yum!

I love that I found this hidden little gem, and await my next visit!

text: Went here for dinner with a party of 6-the waitress was super personable and made sure we were all satisfied! I ordered the hummus plate, which was way better than expected. The hummus was home made and served with veggies and soft pretzels (which were amazing). Our party also ordered burgers, beers, onion strings and a sausage (which was a bit on the salty side, but otherwise tasty)... Would definitely recommend to anyone in the area! The outdoor seating has heaters for when the sun goes down, and big TVs over the bar for watching sports.

text: Loquita is a must do if you're in the funk district in SB. On a Tuesday night it was packed and we were grateful we had a reservation. The albondigas (lamb meatballs) were magical. The paella, while not my favorite of all time,  was solid. Who knew that fried calamari was what most paella were missing?! If you still have room after the food and cocktails, the pan chocolate with home-made sourdough ice cream was a nice way to end.

Delicious pastries. Perfect for a mid-afternoon tea or coffee break while walking State street. They have outside seating with shade.

We will be back for breakfast or dinner. 

Parking is close to restaurant.

text:
This is a copy of an email I sent to the General Manager of this hotel last week after my stay.  To date it has not been replied to:

Good morning Mr. Ide,

Rather than write a review on Yelp, I wanted to first give you the courtesy of reaching out directly to you to express my and my wife's extreme displeasure with our recent stay at your hotel in Santa Barbara.  The Four Seasons Biltomre always held a special place in our hearts as it goes back to the very beginning of our relationship over 15 years ago and continued through three children all the way up until last week.  Unfortunately, I can't say that we'll be visiting again.  Allow me to explain:

We booked a three night stay from Tuesday to Friday in hopes of a much needed break from our kids and a highly stressful business we run.  Upon arrival, it was clear that times had changed at the hotel, but we aren't typically the types to complain about minor things such as the lack of being offered a bottle of water at the front desk.  It happens.  That said, we became increasingly frustrated, and eventually livid, with the lack of service and follow through from your establishment.  The primary culprit- the pool area.  

Now we recognize that midweek in February is not exactly the high point of the season, but that doesn't excuse a hotel like the Four Seasons from not having an attendant during pool hours, not having towels available at all, nobody to help set up chairs, no drink or food service, and most egregious, no attention paid to the pile up of dirty towels or trash that extended well into the evenings.   Sitting in the hot tub on Wednesday morning, we were beside ourselves waiting to see what would happen.  We noticed a phone saying that we could dial in-room service to get food at the pool.  We called that number and told them there were no towels.  Their reply, "That's the spa's responsibility".  I am not exaggerating when I say that I would have expected better service at a Holiday Inn.  Below I've attached a couple of photos for reference.  

Beyond frustrated, we toweled off and walked to the lobby of the hotel, where a clearly rattled employee excused herself after hearing our complaints to go "find a manager".  After having been gone for a good 3 or 4 minutes, she returned only to say that the manager was unavailable and that the Food and Beverage Manager is responsible for pool service.  She also told us that the F&B Manager would be in touch in the afternoon to clear the air.  As a courtesy, we were offered passes to the beach club across the street but nothing else.

The kicker to the story is this. Over the next 2 days and up to today, we've never heard a peep from the F&B Manager nor anyone from the hotel.  

For what it's worth, just one month earlier, we decided to spend one night at the Four Seasons Westlake Village just to relax a bit.  During that mini-trip, construction was happening at the hotel.  We asked to have our room changed to another wing of the hotel, and within 5 minutes of asking, the front desk girl who checked us in had personally come to our room with a bellhop in tow, moved us across the way with a room upgrade to a suite, and threw in a $100 in-room dining credit for us to enjoy breakfast the following day.  And on top of that, she continued checking in with us throughout the stay and even a day or two later just to make sure we felt taken care of.  I'd argue that such a level of service is what we are used to getting from a Four Seasons.  And in that particular case, the offense was much less egregious than what I described here, yet the follow through was night and day.  Needless to say, we plan to return to Westalke Village.  I can't say the same with Santa Barbara.  

We may not be the type of clientele who is spending $2,500 a night for some fancy suite.  True, we only booked a pretty basic room.  However, if you have the nerve to charge $600+ a night for your hotel, you really need to be able to deliver, and all evidence seems to be to the contrary.  I certainly hope there's a reason for this lapse in service.  However, I'm worried that it's a defined strategy to cut corners and if that's the case, I don't envy your position as a 5 star hotel manager in a part of the world with many options.  

I write this to you not with my hand out for a make-good of any kind.  The truth is that I probably wouldn't take you up on it anyhow.  I just want you to know about the experience we had in hopes that you are able to right the ship before it sinks.

Thank you,

text:
Excellent, just had a feast at Los Agaves and it never disappoints.

The burritos are delicious, baja fish tacos fresh, crispy and just right, chile relleno is perfect, not too heavy not too light and just the right amount of flavor, their chips are fresh and not too oily, salsa's are A+.

Don't miss Los Agaves, the service is wonderful (10/10) and the place is a gem. I'm not going for the full 5-stars yet because it has not blown my mind but just solid all around.

PS - idiot reviewer who reviewed this place poorly and started with the line "I don't like Mexican" - what planet are you from that you 1) ate here and 2) wrote a review criticizing this place? Unreal.

PPS - The horchata is 10/10 exceptional, wow.

text: Waste. Of. Time. Literally.  We went there on a Saturday morning, got there around 8:20am so not exactly during the busy period.  We waited for a while to get a menu before getting one ourselves.  Then after we ordered, we waited more than half an hour for the food.  Come on, folks, it's just eggs and pancakes!  After receiving the bill, I waited some more for someone to take my payment before finally going up to the register myself (of course I had to wait some more for someone to help me).  What should have been an informal breakfast took more than 75 minutes (I know because I ended up having to pay for parking after the grace period).  The food here was your standard diner fare, and definitely NOT worth the hassle, at least not until they get more staff.

text:
Looking for a tasty dinner, we made our way over to The Pasta Shoppe. We wanted to sit at one of the tables by the railing, but we were told that was communal seating and we wouldn't be served there (unless we ordered something to go). Instead, we had to wait for a spot to open up at the bar. The wait wasn't too, too long, but later on, we saw them handing menus to people at the communal tables and serving them dishes. That was annoying, but we were already seated, so what to do?

We ordered the prosciutto pizza and gigli pasta. Both were excellent, and we finished everything.

It was a lucky choice and completely our lovely evening.

text: Arrangements were made a day in advance to be able to use room for dinner. Upon arrival, which we were told we could come early, the room was occupied. We had two separate families just united at UCSB graduation to spend an evening together. They told us we were to get a table that should seat less than what numbers we had. A booth next to table was offered which accommodated the numbers but then separated the families which this dinner was to unite. Moments later the occupants of the room departed in which we thought they'd offer, but never happened and on top of that wasn't used again that night. Besides that, the food was excellent and the waiters most accommodating especially when a meal was forgotten. Loved the menu choices and would definitely return.

Very, very mediocre to say the least. Typical restaurant that depends on tourist traffic to fill their Tables. Vegetables were still frozen and fish was really bland. Hostess and waitress pleasant but just going thru the motions.... Barely! 

If you like Applebee's and Denny's , this is the place for you. If you like better fish and service, go to Lure.  The best thing this place has is it's location. That's probably how they can get away with being a bad restaurant and stay in business.   Happy eating.

text:
How can you write a review about In-n-Out?  If you've been there, you either like it or you don't.  If you haven't been there. . .well, you're missing out!

The reason I'm reviewing this specific location is due to the cleanliness of the tables.  For some reason, fast food restaurants in Santa Barbara always have dirty tables (except for In-n-Out, apparently).  You'll see a kid come out from behind the counter, with a rag, pick up trash/trays, and go back behind the counter WITHOUT EVER USING THE RAG.  WTF? I don't know what it is.  Poor eyesight?  Stoned employees?

That's never a problem here, though.  Two (greasy) thumbs up!

text:
A must try in Santa Barbara! I've had soondubu many places, but this one is my favorite. I've had the bulgogi, spicy pork, soondunu, tteokmanduguk, and the tteobokki and I would recommend all of them. 

It's a small mom and pop kind of store with various Asian goods run by a husband and wife. They're always super friendly. The husband runs the front and the wife runs the kitchen. The food reminds me very much of when I would go to my korean friends' houses with that kind of home cooking.

Definitely food that warms the soul and fills you up, and for a good price too!

text:
When you first walk into this restaurant you are immediately struck by the decor, which is lovely and was a very unexpected surprise when we walked in.  You would never guess how charming it is on the inside just from looking at the outside.

My hopes were already set high.  We got a great little table, and the place had a really good vibe.

Unfortunately, the service was supremely awful.  After our order was taken and delivered, we were completely ignored by all wait staff.  My order was wrong, I clearly stated NO DAIRY on my tacos and wouldn't you know it, plenty of cheese on there.  The young girl working was busy talking with friends and family at another table the entire time.  I couldn't mention my order was wrong, ask for more water, more chips, nothing, it was like we weren't there.  When we finished our meal, we were still ignored by the young lady as she chatted with her friends and had to go up to the counter to pay for our meal.  Here's a tip for you, young lady- if you want a tip, you gotta earn it, it shouldn't be given "just because".

text:
FIVE STARS for food. Minus 9/11 to 2008, I have been coming to Kyoto since 1996 on a regular basis. 

ONE STAR for letting loser drunk college kids with no manners whatever take the joint over at dinner with the sake bomb BS. 

My boyfriend had problems when he was there with his 3rd grade son a couple weeks ago. Last night, these total losers minus ONE pretty girl who came over to tell me she was a Berkeley student (these kids looked mid-20s not college age and perhaps they're upset because they're 25 doing sake bombs after classes that their peers took, what, 5 years ago?)

The owners and their nice son, Alex, are absolutely useless when this happens. Ineffectual and subservient, wishing it all to go away but that's now how things generally work. 

When I pointed out they were screaming and ruining everyone's dinner, one kid had the GALL to quote YELP to me: "Have you seen the Yelp reviews? Everyone knows it's loud and that they sake bombs are the draw [not his word, they were all low IQ, white kids trying to be cool and ghetto and pathetic/unattractive the lot of them]." 

Well, I had not noticed this. Then again, I don't always read all the other reviews, particularly on an old place I've been going this long. 

Outrageous. My boyfriend stood up to fight one of the dorks in the matching turquoise shirts and my boyfriend is 200, 6 feet, muscular and from Texas. These were not wimpy boys but they weren't built like Mack trucks either. More: my boyfriend doesn't care how he looks when he fights. He never starts a fight but if he is attacked, he doesn't think about perfect boxing form. He thinks: how is this person going to get laid out on the floor in what Ving Rhames called in Pulp Fiction, "agonizing f****** pain." 

It didn't come to blows but those loser kids will wake up today with a headache and a long life of trying to make a living and educate themselves and I am happy to report I'm 41 and have to worry about neither. 

P.S.

text:
Outdoor, covid-safe seating? Check.

Extensive menu with more than enough vegetarian (and vegan!) options? Check.

We were drawn to OPPI'Z Bistro because of their plentiful vegetarian options and covid-safe outdoor dining experience and left so content and full that we ended up taking a longer route back to our car to "walk it off".

We shared the ravioli and pizza pere e zola and both were absolutely delicious. You can immediately tell the ravioli is made in house and made fresh to order. The pear slices are julienned to perfection, and has the perfect mix of mozzareela, stracciatella cheese, and gorgonzola. Ask for a side of balsamic to drizzle on the pizza - you won't regret it!

We were happy with the prices we paid for the portions we received, and loved dining al fresco. Yes, it's stressful as people walk by without masks, but for the most part, everyone around us was behaving in a safe manner (including the wait staff). I definitely recommend OPPI'Z for any fans of delicious pasta and pizza, and for all vegetarians (and vegans!).

The ONLY thing I'd recommend is they invest in some heat lamps :)

text:
I love Los Agaves, but apparently so does everyone else in SB. I've never been there when there isn't a line out the door. But that's a good thing, and tells you a lot about the restaurant. Even while waiting in line, the staff is quick to get a menu in your hand so you can figure out what you want before getting to the counter. And they always work hard to accommodate your party; at least that's been my experience.

I love that you still get free chips and salsa, and the salsa selection is amazing! I usually order the Beer Battered Baja Tacos (I'll get 1 shrimp, 1 halibut). Never disappoints. I also love the Mole Enchiladas (because it's hard to find good mole in town).

What I love most about Los Agaves is that it doesn't try to be something it's not. It's just good Mexican food. Period. Be prepared to wait a bit, but be patient because it's worth the wait.

text: Fun place. Lots of energy. Creative menu of small, medium and large plates. Portions were very large--two of us shared the crispy Brussel sprouts, lamb tartare and hamachi collar and that was more than enough. All was delicious. Only criticism is that many of the dishes are sweet--they contain fruit or a marmalade or a pickled veggie. I tend to like more savory food and save sweets for dessert. But we enjoyed the food, cocktails and wine. Would recommend.

text: Compared to other good Thai restaurants around town this place is very casual but the food stays true and tasty for a reasonable price.  I usually always get the green curry or pad thai noodles and they're my favorite renditions of those dishes in town.  The chicken satay with peanut sauce and cucumber salad are always spot on and you can't beat the genuine friendly attitude of the staff.  They have a great tasty drink selection and a variety of flavors for a somewhat small menu.  They're also fairly small in space so be prepared to invest some time if the night is busy.

text:
A solid personal hot pot place that won't force you to make a trip down to LA to satisfy your craving. 
A good price point for the area. 

Taste is similar to other personal hot pot joints I've tried. I'm always a beef fan, so I like to go with the beef hot pot, medium spicy.
They have 3 types of dipping sauces (chili oil, chili paste, garlic soy sauce) for you, I always like to mix all 3. Hopefully they offer more variety in the future! 

Servers are friendly and working hard. Also only lunch time is when they have a free tea with your meal! Eventually they will have their own teas, but for now they have some canned chinese classics like Jia Duo Bao, which is one of my favs~

As the only personal hot pot place here with the right taste, that alone deserves 5 stars. Blessed that they even decided to open one in this area!!

text: In the era of COVID-19, Rincon Beach Bar nailed the restaurant industry pivot! Offering dine-in, take out or catering, RBB covers the gamut of dining options flawlessly. Stepping onto their garden patio was a breath of fresh air. The tables were generously spaced more than 6 feet apart. All ordering and payment is "touch-less," executed from the convenience of your personal device. The staff is warm and attentive; and the food is delicious! We opted for the Nashville Hot Chicken on Biscuits, Browned Butternut Squash Ravioli, Kids Four Cheese Mac N Cheese, Passion Fruit Margarita, Churros and Made West Hazy IPA on draft. Everything was a hit with our family! In fact, my 1-year old daughter clapped after each and every macaroni bite -- which is her favorite way of 'saying' -- "compliments to the Chef!" We'll definitely be back and look forward to trying their meal delivery menu as well.

text:
I wish I was "in the know" about the secret menu - I totally would have had my fries wild or animal or whatever makes them covered in cheese!! Maybe next time. I don't eat burgers so why was I there?  We stopped in before heading back to the airport and lunch was "driver's choice"- seems fair... 

I was not disappointed however as I had quite the tasty grilled cheese with fresh tomato, crispy lettuce and whatever the spread is made from. The fries were yummy too especially the crispy bits. It was very crowded but a fun atmosphere. We were even able to snag a table outside which made for some prime people watching. I am glad we stopped and experienced a CA staple.

text:
I am in love! I love walking around State Street and finding amazing resturants like this one!

The seafood was on point! You have to try their cajun shrimp, dunguness crab with the drunken special, brussel sprouts, and calamari! You wont be disappointed!

I honestly dont know what I loved more the friendly staff, perfect ambience, prime location, or the phenomenal seafood!

P.S dont be afraid to get messy!

text: It is the best Chinese chuan food in Santa Barbara. We ordered chicken, pork, beef and roast duck. They all have pretty satisfying quality. The spicy is average level, not super. Roast duck is ok because the duck is a little bit dry and the skin is not hot. It is too expensive to order this Beijing dish in a Sichuan restaurant. The koushui chicken is supposed to be a cold dish, but it was hot. Other than the aforementioned points, the food is good. We order the pork belly which is very similar to what I had in China. Beef with sour soup is also very tasty and very spicy. They have parking lot outside.

text: It's a great location and the food was expensive but good, but we waited over an hour to be seated for two. We walked in and the hostess was on the phone and didn't acknowledge us. We waited for probably ten minutes for the seating hostess to help us but she never looked up. Another server finally saw us standing there, she put us on the list and promised to text us when a table was ready but then forgot about us until we checked in again over 50 minutes later. After waiting some more they found seats for us at the bar. Service was decent after we were seated, but definitely disappointing first experience. Not sure we'll go back.

text:
We tried Galanga b/c I had already been to Zen Yai a few times.  Galanga doesn't have the ambiance that Zen Yai has, but it was good for a quick dinner with friends. 

We ordered:
~ Papaya Salad -- too much fish sauce and too salty.  Did not like that the peanuts were whole peanuts and not crushed. 

~ Eggplant chicken -- very good, large serving, filling for three people.  Large pieces of eggplant and lots of chicken. it was a tad too sweet.  

~ Pad Thai -- eh, this was ok... barely any sprouts, this was the least tasty dish which is sad b/c most people order pad thai. 

~ Green curry -- this was also ok, sort of watery, but good pieces of chicken. 

Service was a little skippy in that it was a little fast and felt rushed, but overall, it was acceptable.  

The total was about $20 per person.  Not a bad choice on State Street.

text:
The hubby and I went here during COVID. All seating is outside. You order from the counter and they bring your food out to you. Staff was quick and friendly. 

We ordered the giant pretzel and spicy tequila lime shrimp fettuccine. 

Giant Pretzel: 4.5/5 the giant pretzel is served warm which is my favorite kind of pretzel. It is big enough for 1-3 people to share. Served with stone ground mustard which was too vinegary tasting. The warm cheese sauce that it's paired with was a lot better. Would definitely recommend. 

Spicy tequila lime shrimp fettuccine: 4.5/5. Would be 5/5 if the portion was a little bigger. But overall the dish tasted really good. Would come back to order it again.

This is a wonderful spot.  Very warm and inviting with eclectic, fun furnishings.
We sat in front and then explored the patio after eating.  It could use some
"warming up"...perhaps more plants or some tiny lights in the huge fig tree out there.
Small lights on the tables?  The food was perfect and reasonably priced.  One could
easily make a dinner out of two or three of their small plates.  We had the lamb
chops and the tamale corn cakes with three sauces.  Both delicious.  There is
ample parking at the public lot so that too is convenient. Will definitely visit again.

text:
It has been one of my best memories when I living in Santa Barbara. 
Walking on the State street in a lazy Sunday afternoon and enjoy two scoops of McConnell's ice cream with the crispy waffle cone. 
They have more than 15 flavors, including some seasonal flavors. 

Here are my top favorites!!
Santa Barbara Strawberry
Earl Grey
Turkish coffee
Brazilian coffee

text:
Their cakes are tasty but they are pretty overprice(~$10 per piece, normal size), probably it's just cheaper back in Norcal where the cake slices are around $5 dollars. the staff who helped us also was not familiar with the cake selections(when we asked about the fillings in the cakes) so it took us a while to get our cakes ordered.

We got strawberry layer cake and marzipan danish layer cake. The strawberries are fresh and goes well with tasty cream cake; the marzipan cake is okay, simply just layers of sponge cake, cream and raspberry jam. The almond paste top layer however is overly sweetened.

I like the interior ambiance it is really European, cozy and cute.

text: I loved pretty much everything about this place. The food was awesome- sometimes fusion style food can be hit or miss, but I really enjoyed the mix of flavors. The chipotle sauce chicken pasta was yummmy, and the pizzas were great. The decor is pretty cool as well, and I liked the specialty cocktails. The only thing I would lament about was the slow service- our waitress was generally unavailable (but friendly when she was) and the hostess picked up a lot of the slack. Perhaps it was just a busy night for her. All and all, I loved the place and I am definitely going back :)

text: Shawn was our driver and from the get go had poor customer service. He was short and condescending. At one point he even called our group of 8 not classy. He also clapped at us like dogs to tell us it was time to go (I don't even clap at my dog). Sandwiches were sub par. And there was so much information! It was hard to relax and take in the scenery or enjoy your friends because Everytime you started to enjoy yourself he pulled the group to explain one thing or another. The first winery was all about talking about wine process and how to drink which is fine, but then here Shawn comes and pulls us out not even giving us time to purchase or sample any other wines like the owner said we could after his demonstration. I've been on several wine tours with different companies in different wine regions. This by far was the most rude and rushed tour guide I've met. I mean even when I kindly pointed out that he offended my group by his classy comment and clapping at us, he didn't once apologize. He even told one of my friend to "read" when she asked him to point out which side the roast beef sandwiches were on. I paid good money for this tour and to be treated in such a way was unprofessional and in bad taste. I would not recommend this place.

text: Ordered the lobster special with clam chowder and ceasar salad. The clam chowder is awesome!! Big chunks of clam, potatos, and celery- but the clams out weighed the other ingredients- unlike most clam chowders. It was almost comparable to fishermens warf in sf. The salad was meh... I hate when restaurants give me the hard stubs and lettus was old! Other then that the lobster was pretty good. I ordered the lb and a half one.... The body and tail end was great, but when it ce time to eat the claws, I felt the meat was too mushy. Our weightstress was nice, but nothing special. It was a nice lobster lunch by the ocean, but not something that is a must have if ur visiting sb for the first time

text: The place itself is beautiful and the food is great. The prices are spot on. BUT, the service is HORRIBLE. It seems as though management has lost touch with their employees. My first impression was "there are 2 bars... one near the kitchen for the staff to sit at after hours and drink beers in their blue jeans and Pascussi t-shirts, and the other bar is for guests." The cook was eating in the open behind the staffs' bar. There is no music in the background, so all you can hear are the employees at the "other bar" talking above the guests who are trying to enjoy a quiet romantic Italian dinner. My bartender, Sophia, wasn't wearing anything professional... from her jeans to a mid drift checkered shirt tied up around her chest to reveal an underlying tank top. She tried to sell me the most expensive glass of wine they have. Once I ordered a medium priced glass of the BV Pinot Noir and the Mozzarella di Bufalo appetizer, I lost her attention. She was busy (what I can only assume is texting) on her cell phone under the register monitor plugged in for charging. I waited 17 minutes for my one appetizer. After asking her to check on it, she brought it out and blamed the delay on the "new cook."  Never asking how my food was and if I wanted anything else... she asked if I was ready for the check.  The best part is- while Sophia & the bar lounging employees were distracted, a homeless guy came in and grabbed a handful of mints out of the bar bowl. He then pretended to work there wiping the bar down with his black sweatshirt sleeve and offered me a menu. None of the employees noticed and the homeless guy walked out with about $5 worth of mints. Oh and last but not least, Sophia wiped the outside of a beer glass down with a dirty bar rag after she poured it, and then served it to a customer. Can you say GROSS?!

text:
YUM!! 

This place is at the end of stearns wharf on the pier and surrounded by ocean. It's small with limited seating.

Servers are friendly and engaging, very prompt. They have one guy (the cook) who is super badass handling the grill, stoves, fryer all at once! Pretty sure he's like superman or something. Can handle like 4 dishes going on at once and didn't burn a single thing. Impressive.

Husband and I ordered:

Fried shrimp and calamari - subbed fries instead of onion rings. This was delicious!! Calamari and shrimp were fresh. Came with side of slaw which was good and crispy fries. Cocktail sauce was also good. Huge portion.

Cup of chowder: flavor was amazing!! Nice and thick, creamy soup with plenty of clams.

lobster pasta: ughh this garlic butter white wine sauce with linguini and chucks of lobster totally hit the spot. It was a TAD bland so I added some salt but it was delicious.

Fresh seafood and awesome views with great customer service. Can't go wrong!

text:
Mrs and I went there for lunch yesterday.  I had the Torta and she had the Tortilla Soup.  Both dishes were very good.  We also had margaritas (pretty bad, pre-made) and a side of chips and salsa.  The chips and salsa came at the same time as the entrees so I wouldn't recommend.

Very nice patio area but eating out of cardboard boxes with plastic forks is a turn off.  Ordering at the cash register was awkward as well.  It is probably wonderful for dinner.

text:
This place is TINY! Very limited seating, but the views are hard to beat. Expect a wait. Always.

Ordered:
x garlic baked clams (6 Littleneck Clams topped with garlic, breadcrumbs and parmesan cheese) - This was good until I started tasting coconut... I don't like sweet things in my food so this was a bit of a turnoff. However, my group really enjoyed it.
x steamed mussels (white wine garlic broth) - Obv had to order these as I ALWAYS order steamed clams or mussels everywhere I go. These did not disappoint. 
x crab cakes -  decent crab cakes. Certainly not anything to rave about.
x abalone served w/ rice - The abalone was good, but the rice is came with was SOOO bland. I think this dish would've tasted better sashimi style.

Everything was good, but it wasn't mind-blowing. I'd definitely come again for drinks and a little snack. It's at the end of the wharf so it's less people walking around blocking the views :) 4 stars for the view and 3 stars for the food.

text: I went to Sachi last night, on a cool winter night, looking for some asian comfort food.  I ordered a beer and a bowl of the spicy miso ramen with charshu.  The beer came in a couple of minutes and I had one sip, then the ramen arrived.  Impressive fast service, but I'd have liked to enjoy the cool beer for a few minutes at least before the ramen showed up.  Anyhow, I slid the beer aside and tasted the ramen.  The noodles were nuclear hot, while the mushrooms were refrigerator cold.  I then sampled the soft-yoke boiled egg, and the outside was lukewarm while the yolk was refrigerator cold.  I was somewhat disappointed by the cold items in my hot ramen.  I set it aside for a few minutes, drank the beer, then resumed with the ramen, since the temperatures of the various ingredients had time to warm or cool to a common temperature.  Needless to say, not too impressed.

text:
Food: Good. Not great, but good. We ordered several pieces of nigiri. The fish to rice ratio was off (too much rice). The shishito peppers were too spicy, and we like spicy food, but it was almost distracting from the flavor. The cauliflower tempura was a little gimmicky, but very good and filling. Toro and uni are must orders. 

Service was fine. We asked to be seated at a larger table and was denied because we were only a party of two, which is fine, but 5 minutes later sat a party of 2 and a party of 1 at the larger tables. Other than that, our server was fine. 

Overall, ask to be seated on the roof. The view of the marina and the ocean is beautiful. Decent choice for lunch. Would probably recommend Arigato nearby, but this wasn't a terrible consolation.

text:
I go to Zaytoon for two things: the falafel, and the amazing outdoor dining experience. The firepits, fountain, and ambiance lighting make for an incredible evening. The falafel is excellently prepared, not greasy, and very tasty. When I was last there I tried the lamb which was delicious, but seemed way overpriced for the portions. The hummus was also a bit lemony for my taste. If you're looking for a nice place to bring a group, kill a few bottles of wine and enjoy an exquisitely prepared meal, this is the place to do it. Just be prepared to pay the high price that goes with it. 

A word of caution: Be careful, it's very easy to drive past this place. A  little off the main drag, and the sign is incredibly easy to miss.

text:
First off it's called Brophy's Brothers.  If that doesn't shout a damn good time then I don't know what does.  Let's get to the skinny of this.  This is a seafood restaurant on the harbor so dammit make sure you eat seafood.  This is what we had.

Clam Chowder - Nice chunks of clam but watery.  I don't think I need to say more.  Splash Cafe (see my reviews) hands down.  Funny thing is, I ran into a local woman outside that was trying to school us on the food and we were told that the Clam Chowder was the best she had ever had.  Let's put it this way I can think of 5 places without even blinking an eye better than this place.

Oysters On The Half Shell - Fresh, Cold and Tasty.  Horseradish was not very good but other than that you rarely can mess this up with restaurants on the shore.

Grilled Salmon Salad - Portions were hearty.  I'm talking nice bright colored vegetables, cherry tomatoes, olives etc...  I swear it looked like grandma just picked it out of the garden.

Calamari - Ok this is where the money was.  Damn thing was so good and you know what, it was the best I've ever had.  Calamari was tender and juicy and the batter was incredible.  It was not that crappy batter they use on onion rings nor was it the thick coating that others use.  This was perfectly coated yet thin and flaky.  It crumbled in your mouth and was perfectly seasoned.  I would go back for this alone.  They also had in the same section of fried goodies, clams, scallops, shrimps and fish.  I'm just hoping they use the same batter and this is for sure a repeat stop on my next road trip.

This place really deserves a 5 but it was hard for me to decide because if the local was telling me the clam chowder was the best she had ever had and claimed to have eaten the whole menu then damn it should be pretty good.  The rest of the meal was a 5 but I then think to myself what others things on the menu could be like the clam chowder.  Looking around I saw some things that looked ok.  I guess I didn't really have a complete meal but their fish selection really looked good.

Maybe on my next trip I'll have to try other things on the menu and I can revise my review to a 5.

text: Very excited to finally have a local brewing supply store in Santa Barbara! For years, I've been making a daily trip out of driving an hour-plus down south or north to pickup ingredients for my next brew. I missed their grand-opening, but was able to stop-in on their 3rd week open (good news doesn't usually travel slowly in the brewing community). Not only was it ridiculously easy to locate their shop, it has a great layout and lots of quality ingredients to choose from. BYOB has a good assortment of brewing equipment in stock as well as kegging equipment. They also fill CO2 tanks which is great, as a lot of places in town have stopped filling them. The owners and shop staff are all brewers and very knowledgeable, whether you're piecing together an experimental brew or building an exact recipe, BYOB is sure to have what you need!

text:
Congratulations, you have an ocean view in Santa Barbara. Listen, the wine is good here, but it's honestly not worth the trip if you're looking for a friendly staff to pour your wine. While we were here using our AXXESS card, it was crowded, but not unreasonable. The staff ran out of glasses and started serving $60 bottles of wine out of plastic cups. And to make things better, I overheard one of the staff ask one of the owners to help polish glasses so they could serve out of REAL wine glasses, and the owner said, "Listen...I'm not here to work. *eye roll* I'm just visiting with some friends. This isn't my problem." ....the dude was behind the bar taking up room...and his friends were occupying half the bar on the other side...like actually? Treat your staff better and don't be such a prick! 

Bottom line: small pours, attitudinal owners, and kind of a hot mess.

Alternatives you won't regret: Kunin Winery, Area 5.1, and DV8 Wine Cellars. 

The only thing this place has going for it....it's on the ocean. But so is the rest of Santa Barbara...never coming back here again.

text:
Really used to like this place, but the last couple times I've gone the experience has been really disappointing. They're blowing the basics of cooking the ingredients. A few weeks ago, the noodles in the pad thai were so overcooked that they were essentially mush when they hit my mouth. It's a tad unsettling when I can chew food using only my tongue. Last night, the noodles on P C U noodles were, on the flip side, completely undercooked. They were hard. Not even close to al dente. The chicken, as other reviews here have pointed out, was also extremely overcooked and dry. It was not pleasant whatsoever to eat. I'm a big guy, and the food was so unacceptable quality wise that I left a third of it on my plate because I'd rather go a tad hungry than finish it.

To management: PLEASE go back to basics and QA the food before it comes out, and figure out a better way to cook the chicken so it isn't bone dry. At this point, I won't be coming back anytime soon, if ever again. Empty Bowl is currently far ahead of you.

text: I looked endlessly for a great place to enjoy breakfast my one and only morning in the Santa Barbara area. I came across Summerland Beach Cafe, and it looked cute enough and had good enough reviews that I decided to venture out of SB and down the coast a bit to enjoy breakfast here instead. I was disappointed. The omelette I ordered was just not impressive, mostly because the green peppers and onions were not cooked at all inside of it. I guess if I wanted raw veggies, I would've ordered a salad...The waitress offered to have the cook fix me up a side of sauted veggies after the fact, but I declined. It wasn't worth it. Mediocre food at best. The service was good and the waitress also offered me a reward card to redeem for a free meal in the future, but that doesn't really do me any good. The likelihood of me being back in the area and/or returning here is not great.

text:
Went there for takeout and observed no social spacing in outdoor dining area. People were back to back. I was led past all the tables inside to get my order. Behind the bar a dozen employees were clustered together with no apparent logistical reason.

Why cant you pay at the hostess desk at the entrance? Meanwhile Toma down the street does it right with lots of spacing between tables.

If SB does a full shutdown due to to issues, the good actor restaurants can partially thank this place.
