text:
Came here for dinner tonight and our experience was nothing short of AMAZING! 

Service: Max was our waiter and he was truly phenomenal! He knew the menu so well and every one of his recommendations was 10/10. Every course we had was perfectly timed out as well. 

Food: Would recommend 3-4 dishes for two people. We had the tuna crudo, nectarine cucumber salad, grilled prawns, and fried chicken.  Every item was so delicious but the standout for us was the crudo 

Drinks: I had a glass of Cabernet, and my boyfriend had their signature rye whiskey cocktail - both were delicious and went perfectly with our food. At the end of the meal we decided to share an espresso martini - this one was unique, not like others we've had before but still very delicious and we loved it nonetheless! 

Would HIGHLY recommend dining at The Lark when visiting Santa Barbara. We definitely can't wait to come back!

text:
So get this shit. I have been here a few times for margarita mondays and Ive usually had a good time besides the margs being absolute rubbish. But hey for 2 bucks what do you expect. 

Anywho, I'm at this place and I'm having a grand ol' time spending my good  money on margs and a chicken quesadilla which was ok.

Later in the evening I'm sitting at a table with friends and this waitress brings by a plate of food, and we let her know it isn't ours. She takes it away looking for the right table and after a minute comes back, abruptly sets the plate on our table, and scampers away...

So we sit.... And look... first at the plate of delicious looking tamales and beans and rice... and then at each other. 

We wait... a good few minutes. Wondering what the hell we are to with this food that has been so unceremoniously put before us. After a little bit we all did what I think any good human being who is aware of how precious food is would do. We enjoyed the f**k out of it. 

But wait! Here's the best part... after we each get a couple stabs, this other completely different waitress that hasn't helped us the whole night comes over and says something to the effect of "Oh, that plate was for this table over here..." pointing to a table completely void of any humans. And so I'm like "Ok, well we told the fine girl who was in charge of delivering it to the proper destination that it was in no way our plate, she left, came back and plopped it right down on this here table without any utterance whatsoever" (not verbatim but you get the point)

To this she replies: "Oh, ok. So like you have to pay for it now then..."

To which I replied: "Absomotherf**ckinglutley Not" (again not verbatim but certainly  what I would have liked to have said) 

Anyway let's get on with the point of this scathing review. Long story short she went to get the manager, who I was excited to have a word with, thinking that, clearly this fine chap would certainly see things from the customers point of view (as is any good establishments first priority).

Sadly, He did not. It was pretty pathetic. I outlined to him the exact situation which I have gone into such detail with all you yelpers, and after having done so he looked at me incredulously and says "So, you're not going to pay for the plate?..."


OK. I've had it. Screw you manager guy. Screw you El Paseo. How dare you try  to "unassumingly" place a plate in front of a customer you know good and well didnt order that plate. No... another party who was most likely fed up with your shitty service ordered it and walked out on you. Your solution? Try to pin it on another patron in a very sneaky and ingenuous way. This is Santa Barbara and that kind of shit should not be happening in a town with world class restaurants and especially in an establishment that has such roots in this towns culture. Seriously  shame on you El Paseo for disgracing SB.

Anyway I'm done.

This customer stated she left her phone on the table, when the waiter couldn't find it she proceeded to accuse him of stealing it. The manger politely stood up for the waiter and told the lady if he says he didn't see it, he didn't see it. Come to find out her husband had it the whole time. Thank you Mr. Manager for protecting your staff while still being professional with undeserving customers

text: Came here for brunch with a friend after seeing all the good reviews for it. Its a quaint little restaurant, with a nice homey feel to it. People recommended making a reservation, but I guess since we arrived at nine in the morning it wasn't very crowded. My friend and I decided to share three dishes, with each other because it would be cheaper that way, since the restaurant is very pricey for college students. And boy were we satisfied, the three platters we shared definitely filled us up beyond capacity. We started out with the apple beignets, which were decent, but nothing special. I wouldn't order it the next time. However, what made me give Tupelo's the 5 stars was there Vanilla French Toast on a berry sauce, with fresh whipped cream and the crab cakes. The vanilla french toast had to be the best french toast I've ever eaten. They had a nice crisp to them, and I was surprised on how potent the actual vanilla flavor came out. The mixed berry sauce it laid on top of complimented it beautifully. There were actual berry pulp, I believe it was rasberry and blackberry, in the sauce and the fresh whipped cream was a nice side as well. The crab cakes were amazing as well, and big enough to share. It comes with two large crab cakes, topped with eggs benedict, avocado hash, and potatoes on the side. What I liked about the crab cakes was that there was no bread filler. It was all crab meat with a nice crust on the outside. The eggs benedict were cooked to perfection, and the potatoes were also amazing. I honestly love avocado, so the avocado definitely made the dish all that better for me.

text: Where can I start? My plate of fish tacos were amazing. Normally I'm a picky eater and don't like tomatoes but these tacos. Omg. It had tomatoes and black beans and cabbage and avocado and a special sauce was very tasty altogether. Then my berry mojito was good too. My sister enjoyed her Babcock red wine and empanadas. Her son enjoyed his fish n chips. After we were all done eating he kept eating his fries. Looked so cute doing it. Okay back to the family, they all enjoyed there scallop and risotto dish. We were lucky to have one of the heaters next to us because there was only 3 available for the entire patio. Maybe they can add more because it was a chilly night.

I hate to only give it a three stars because the waiter, Joey, was awesome and the food was really delicious. Decor is a bit tacky, so I was a little nervous.

I'm also regretting not buying a bag of the coffee from El Salvador!!!  I can't stop thinking about how amazing that cup of drop was!!! text: Had lunch here last weekend with a friend who was visiting from out of town. She and I started off by ordering tangerine mimosas, only to be told that they were out of tangerine. Not that big of a deal, but still...I ordered the crab quesadilla and after a very long wait, it came out stone cold. The shredded cheese was not melted at all and the crab was cold as if it came straight from the fridge. Tortilla was barely toasted.  I sent it back.  My friend had the crab melt sandwich and the crab in that was fishy but the fries were good.  Hubby had the chicken fettuccine alfredo and he liked it a lot.  We all waited way too long for our food. And then trying to flag someone down to get the check took forever, and it took too long for them to process the credit card as well. The ambiance is really nice, great people watching along the State Street promenade, but the food and service don't make it worth it. Right down to the wobbly table at which we were seated. Servers watched us struggling to stabilize the table and did nothing to help.  Prices do not match the experience. Skip it.

text:
Love love love this place!!!!! My favorite beer in the area, and the atmosphere is quirky in a great way. The IPAs are delicious, the severance is probably my favorite. My husband lives the Ogre. 

But, let's talk about the spectre. Soooooooo good that I crave it! I was never a big fan of Irish stouts, not that I don't enjoy them, just that I don't seek them out. Well, now I do! Try the spectre on nitro! 

I also love the red here! 

One of the best features here is that you can get 4oz glasses, crowlers (40 oz to go) and growlers. The 4 oz glasses are nice if you are in the mood to try a few different things without having to commit to a taster.

They bring in food trucks and there's a fairly large space, although because it's concrete building with concrete floors, it can get pretty loud at peak times. 

It's also dog friendly, and they support the local dog adoption agency.

text:
Best way to describe it was how  I saw someone else write it on this site. This is NOT your typical Hyatt.

When my wife and I looked for a resort-like Santa Barbara vacation, I had no idea that this was the former Radisson and scattered other brands over the last 20 years. Had I known that, I wouldn't have booked it because I knew it was a ratty older building and not "resort-like".

I'm not trying to be mean but at $260 per night and the name "Hyatt", I expected a cleaner, more modern facility with amenities that didn't make me feel like I was at Motel 6.

However....I WAS at Motel 6 because the first room they put us in had a clear cut view to Motel 6 which was right across the street. Opening the window and seeing motel-goers drinking a six pack in their boxers in front of their room doors wasn't really that scenic look we were hoping for.

And the room was so small, so old and reeked of smoke.

When we contacted the front desk about it, one girl behind the desk was very rude. However, another girl named "Gaby" and the manager, "Cameron", DID go beyond the call of service to try to make us happy. In fact, they are the only reasons that I am giving this review Two Stars.

After taking us into a few buildings and touring a few other room options, they finally placed us in a much better size room with an ocean view and didn't charge us the upgrade price. And that was much appreciated.

However, apart from that view of the ocean, we really didn't like the hotel. If I paid $100 for the Comfort Inn, I would have been fine with it. But it was the Hyatt. And I paid much more.

One of the valet guys told me that it's a protected property because of it's historical factor and as such they have strict restrictions on new construction.  I get that. But what a shame Hyatt put their name to it because it doesn't match their standards.

text:
OVER PRICED! The food are just not that good at all! 

We ordered the Cajun Crawfish popcorn for appetizer.  It was one step above fast-food, it lacked seasoning but it was a good portion size.  For entree we got Crawfish Etouffee and Cajun Lamb Chops.  The etouffee had the spice kick to it but the flavor was lacking, since it doesn't fuse the flavors of the peppers and onions in well. The lamb was good, the sauce was good but the white cap mushroom flavor took a lot away from the sauce. It distracted the taste buds, for the price they of the dish they could have used a higher quality mushroom. 

On the positive side, the Bread pudding desert was good, it was a bit too sweet but good (1 star).  The staff is friendly and the service is superb, and it does have excellent atmosphere (a little loud but not bad) (1 star).

We've gone to Range in SF (http://www.yelp.com/biz/range-san-francisco?rpp=40&sort_by=date_desc) and Fresca in SF (http://www.yelp.com/biz/fresca-san-francisco-2#query:Fresca) and our meal which was not as good as theirs fell in between those two places for dinner for two.  Overall for the price we expect better quality food with more flavor.

text:
Sadly, all the other yelpers with the same complaints here are vilified.  Everything is crazyily overpriced...but I can get past that if the price is very up front.  It is not.  There are signs such as "mac & cheese special" for 5.99....after tax, 3$ charge or a quarter slice of bacon ground up and 2 slice jalapeno....plus some crazy "extra nighttime charge" that is not advertised anywhere visible (surprise surprise) takes a tiny little hotdog tray full of mac and cheese to over 10$.  Thats cool and all, but I like others felt ripped off or stung, but I am guessing that must be the intention... They get 1 star as the only thing they never managed to mess up or over charge me for was a mug of 805 beer.  Waiting times for freshness? Not a problem.  Waiting time for unfresh cack? Strike 3 you're out of there.

Edit : Response - 
Thanks for the reply, Rocco; Im glad it is not your intention to rip people off, and appreciate you telling me this.  However, as far as I know, there's still no obviously indication to customers that orders after a certain time/  early evening are subject to a 'nighttime' surcharge.  I feel that this is very dishonest, and that is without touching on the $3 charge for, I repeat, 2 slices of jalapeno, and half to a quarter slice of ground up bacon.

text:
Arigato is the best sushi in town!
I have been a connoisseur since I was very little because as soon as he could, my father would sweep me away from the house and take me out for sushi.  So I have been to some of the best sushi places all over.
Anyhow, having been to Arigato over and over again, here is what I recommend ordering:
Start with miso soup and a large sake
Then have garlic and soy flavored hot edimame (order only these things first as the orders come out whenever they are ready and are not paced according to courses)
Then order the fiesta roll (this has warm halibut tempura and many other amazing ingredients)
After you are finished, enjoy your sake and order the sashimi jalepeno yellowtail....oh my goodness this is like butter!)
If you want another roll the pro roll is great and the spicy tuna. (I personally don't like to stuff myself and I like to eat less, eat slower and savor more of the food and the experience.)
For dessert the tempura fried greed tea ice cream is refreshing and a pleasure.  The ice cream is of the best quality and the tempura batter is not too heavy but on the contrary light and fluffy complimenting the ice cream just enough.
All in all there is a reason that Arigato is at the top of my list of favorite restaurants!

text: Disappointed in the service.  Place was about half full on a Friday evening when we arrived.  The empty tables were all dirty so we figured it would be just a couple of minutes to clean one up so that we could be seated.  We sat there for probably 15 minutes and felt completely ignored.  No tables were cleaned and the staff didn't seem to interested in getting us seated.  We finally gave up and walked down to Padero Beach Grill where we were quickly served.  We were fired up for some good pizza but never got the opportunity.  They may have great food for all I know but they should work on improving their customer service.

text:
Summary if you don't want to read a longer than usual review - over-complicated dishes, badly prepared, over-priced served clumsily in a well designed environment. 
Go to The Lark or Loquita for a better meal and all round more impressive experience.

4 of us were keen to try the new place in town that is apparently going for a Michelin star.
Have eaten at plenty of starred restaurants in many cities and these guys are delusional if that's true.

The redeeming features: The dcor and furnishings were great, designed with impeccable taste and in line with places in London, New York, etc.
The wine we had was superb but, oddly, the cheapest on the extremely high end list. $60 was the starting point on the main list (unnecessarily high?) but a bottle of Rioja hiding on the 'wine by the glass' menu at $52 was a relative bargain.

Unfortunately, the negatives are a longer list.
The first thing that struck us was that the waiters were 100% male, and (on the night that we were there) 100% white.
We were kept 20 mins past our booking time and then sat at an enormous table for 6-8 in what seemed like a secondary room off the garden. We then asked for a table where we could sit close enough to be able talk to each other and they moved us to the main room to a table that had been empty the whole time. Not a great start. 

The menu is simply pretentious nonsense in my opinion. Overly complicated dishes that are poorly executed. The short rib ossobuco with polenta was bland and inedible. The fusilli was a mush of overcooked pasta. We didn't get far with either and they said they'd knock them off the check. The hangar steak (at $42)  was the only hit and the lobster spaghetti was a child size size portion served in a massive bowl. 

To be fair, they tried hard to make amends for the main courses by offering us a complimentary dessert. We ordered 2 between 4 but inexplicably they brought 4. When the check came they had left the two meals on there that they'd offered to comp, excluded the desserts that we hadn't ordered and added a fictitious bottle of Badoit. By this point we were just confused as to their approach as it seemed to make things worse rather than better. We were keen to just get out at that point and won't be returning. 

Two general observations. 
First, their genuine concern that we didn't enjoy our meals shows that they care but I'm afraid that they come across as having absolutely no idea what they are doing. It's like eating in a restaurant that's run by someone who's obviously not a restaurateur. 
Second, there are other restaurants in SB owned by grown up restaurateurs that do it consistently right, where every visit is a pleasure. They happen to be owned by the same group and are a much better choice for a special night out. You'll also struggle to spend the $100 a head there that Somerset will cost you. 

An honest (but reluctant) warning to readers from someone who is happy to give anywhere new a chance....

text:
On my first trip here last fall, I was somewhat disappointed because the woman in line in front of me was given a number of samples. She got to try a lot of different cacao percents. I've never really explored chocolate that much, and was hoping to be offered a small bit either while the other lady was trying some, or once it was my turn. This never happened. Anyways, I made my selection of chocolates (about 4 or so), which were placed in a clear cellophane bag. I left, ate the chocolates in my car, and thought 'meh'. Overall, I was not impressed. 

Anyways, I decided to give this shop a second chance this past Monday when I had the day off work. The woman behind the counter was so friendly and kind to me. She helped recommend different types of chocolates to me, explained what the funny-looking Mexican grinder things on the walls were, and told me it would be cheaper to just ship a box of chocolates to my sister myself rather than pay $10 for the store to do it. Thank you for the honest tip! Anyways, I was so delighted to have this woman help me. She even wrapped up my chocolates in a little box and with pretty ribbon on top. She asked Maya (in the back) a few questions as well. I suspect that Maya is the unfriendly woman who helped me last fall...just a hunch. How funny when an employee of the shop is much nicer than the owner, hm?

Anyways, the chocolates are awesome. I am really enjoying them and taking my time with letting the flavor develop in my mouth. I just hope to have the nice lady help me the next time I visit the store! -1 star for the first time I visited

text:
Another beautiful day off in paradise, and winding down here at Uncorked. Tasty wines through their Wine Station system, paired with a wide variety of foods.

And bring your big appetite, you won't go away hungry. Tonight's favorites: Pacific Paradise Oysters (it is Monday Oyster Night after all), Tri-Tip Steak Bites, and Fred B's Avocado Toast. 

Thanks Alexis and Michael for a delicious time.

Located on Haley Street, next to Rose Cafe and Twenty Four Blackbirds Chocolates, and just over Highway 101 from the Funk Zone.

text:
My bf and I had reservations here for a Saturday evening to celebrate our one year anniversary.  

There was valet parking and ample street parking.

We arrived 15 minutes early and waited at the bar while our table on the patio was being prepared. Our table was ready within 5 minutes... complete with a flower arrangement that my bf has ordered from Montecito Flowers and coordinated with Oliver's to have ready for our arrival.  The patio was beautiful, comfortable, and relaxing with music playing from speakers, string lighting and heaters.  They also had blankets available to keep you warm. 

The menu included a wide variety of vegan options that all looked delicious and creative.  We opted for Crab Cakes, Brussel Sprouts, Truffle Potatoes, Wild Mushroom Tostada, and Impossible Burger.  For desert, we had the Blueberry Crumble.  Everything came out in a timely manner and was delicious!  The Crab Cakes were lite and tasty.  The tostada was also lite and flavorful esp since I love mushrooms.  The burger was huge. My bf who is not a vegetarian said it tasted like a real burger.  

Service was exceptional!  Everyone was professional, courteous, attentive, and personable.

The two restrooms were unisex, single user restrooms.   They were clean and spacious. 

Prices were reasonable.

We loved Oliver's.  We will definitely be back to try more menu items.  

Solid 5 for a vegan restaurant!

text: One of the best places to eat in Santa Barbara!! The menu is creative and the food is fresh and delicious. Everything I have ordered has been great.  I normally order the Cali melt- so yummy! The Crushcafe also has the BEST chai latte in town. I have friends that love it, who don't even normally like chai drinks. It is mild, sweet, and creamy... Just perfect. The ginger plum iced tea is also a wonderful drink they serve. It is not as strong and bitter as other iced teas I've had. It tastes light, floral, and fruity!  It is also great mixed with lemonade. It is probably obvious, but I am passionate about how much I absolutely love this place! I have yet to be the slightest bit unhappy with the service, food, or atmosphere. Parking can be tricky, but there is usually street parking within a block or two. Overall, I highly recommend trying out Crushcafe.

text: Terrible.  I can't remember the last time I walked out of a restaurant but today I did.  We arrived at 10:45 am and were told that breakfast was over and we could have a continental breakfast only.  Ok.  We sat, we were given no menus and no one greeted us for 10 min.  We asked for coffee, another 10 min.  We asked for menus and never got them.  Someone from the kitchen came out and told us that they could "make us toast and maybe whatever fruit was left".  At that point, we said "No thanks" and left.  My husband and I spent the whole time talking about how if we were the owner, having invested millions in the decor and location, we would feel furious/heartbroken that staff seemed incapable of handling two customers that arrived just past breakfast service.  Next time.....just out a closed sign on the door would let us know you weren't interested in our business and be a lot better than pretending that you were.

text: If it weren't for the amazing help I receive every day at Starbucks, this location would have one star. I cannot believe how rude these employees are. Especially those in the deli. They cannot make a sandwich with out sighing, or giving you total attitude and making you feel as though you've interrupted their day. ESPECIALLY the short woman with the caked on eyeshadow. I have had her respond to me "what do you want!?" on multiple occasions. One of the managers had the audacity to tell me "don't buy watermelons this time of year if you're expecting decent fruit!" When I asked for a refund on a disgustingly over ripe watermelon I purchased. Again, with the exception of the outstanding customer service from Starbucks, this store needs a serious revamp. I can't believe they can even stay open with how poorly they treat their customers.

text:
WooooooOOooOoOwwwww.. I am in heaven....hands down, best chicken sandwich ever!!! Most places mess up on their chicken sandwiches because they put all the unnecessary sauces on it and the batter to the fried chicken isn't crispy, or no flavor or too much batter, and the chicken is dry. This chicken is juicy, tender, perfect batter where it's the perfect light airy crunch! No sauce sauce is on it, not needed. Fried bacon on top of the fried chicken and the jalapeo jam sauce (very light) with the brioche bun, is all the flavor it needs!! Bacon is nice and thick. It's not being engulfed with sauce hiding all the imperfection, because it's perfect! The buns is so light and fluffy with the perfect sweetness. 

The challah French toast- perfect sweetness with the honey and the grapefruit is spectacular!!! It's juicy and crunchy. The bread is soooo soft and fluffy. 

Both items were perfectly balanced being able to taste and feel every single flavor and texture. Who created this!? Who are the chefs!? Props!! My new fave spot when I visit Santa Barbara!! 

Staff was very nice and I could see they were all working very hard.

text: First time at Helena Ave Bakery this morning. It has a trendy ambiance and kind staff. I had the huevos rancheros - I was skeptical because it was served on bread, rather than tortillas. Still, it was tasty and the salsa was outstanding. I followed it with a morning bun (be sure to ask for it warmed), because breakfast desert should be a thing. Only downside: small portions for the price point, but would still recommend.

text:
This place is super low-key. I used to drive by this place all the time wondering what the hell it was, and then I thought that maybe it was a dive bar or something.  After coming here with my family, I was so incredibly wrong.  There aren't any windows, so after my brother and I entered, we were in awe.... and then we wondered if we were going to get kicked out for not wearing better clothes. 

The portions are humongous, you can easily share one meal and leave full, and as for the alcohol... I'm not so sure. I was detoxing and trying to not drink alcohol for a week so I passed, but the people next to us seemed to really enjoy it so I guess they get an A for that. 

I really enjoyed my time here and if I ever wanted to take my friends to a nice dinner in Santa Barbara that was small and intimate, I would take them here. If a guy asked me out on a date and took me here, I'd be really impressed and then I'd wonder what the ulterior motive was.

text: Absolutely beautiful venue and great good and venue. I had the grilled chicken with a tzatziki sauce and roasted pistachios on a bed of saffron rice along with some greens and artichoke hearts. My colleagues had some delicious grilled salmon that had a perfectly crisp skin and flaky and moist body. The portions were big and filling which in addition to their taste made it worth the price tag. Additionally I had a Baby I'm a Star and my colleague had a Lucy in the Sky. Both cocktail drinks were delicious and well balanced. I went on a Friday afternoon during lunch and the service was excellent. The staff were very welcoming and attentive. I definitely would recommend going here on a sunny day in order to make use of their fantastic outdoor seating.

text: My husband and I went to Cafe Stella last night at the spur of the moment.  I hadn't been there in a couple of years.  The bar is nice to get drinks and hang out but we sat in the main dining room for dinner.   We started with the ceviche appetizer and it was  delicious.  The only complaint is the chips that were served with the ceviche were small so it was hard to get a big enough bite onto the chip.  My husband had the Beet Salad which he said was great.  I had the Nioise salad with seared ahi and it was delicious.  The dressing wasn't overpowering and the Ahi was seared perfectly.  For the entree my husband had the Beef Bourguignon with which he had no complaints.  Beef was tender and he liked the brown sauce.  I had the Chicken Cordon Bleu  served with garlic mashed potatoes, sauted spinach and white wine cream sauce. The chicken was crispy and not over cooked.  Mashed potatoes were creamy and the white wine cream sauce was delicious.  The sauce worked with the mashed potatoes and was perfect for dipping my chicken into.  The service was great....we forgot to get the name of our server but she did a fantastic job.  The food all came out  at the right time and she would check on us to see if we needed anything without being annoying.  We enjoyed our dinner and will definitely come back.

text:
Don't walk past this little wine spot! Great place to come in and cool off with a wine tasting. The owner, Marc, chatted and served up some great wines. I'm not usually a fan of white or rose, but their Rockin' Rose was pretty tasty on a summer day. 

The three reds we tried were all so smooth and delicious. My favorite was the 2011 Syrah "Monaco" - so jammy I could eat it with a peanut butter sandwich!

2 little extras: their labels are really cute and well designed (by Marc!) and they are dog friendly!

text:
My boyfriend and I decided to give this place a try since we heard it has one Michelin star. Reservation is $25 deposit per person and the omakase is $145 which consists of 17 courses including dessert.

We arrived on time even though it is recommended to arrive 15 minutes ahead of time. We still end up having to wait for about 10 minutes in the lobby of the Montecito Inn. The hostess asked us if we wanted drinks while we were waiting.

There were no chopsticks. Everyone ate their food with their hands and there was a hot towel to clean your hands. The food was delicious except the rice was a bit mushy. Fish was high quality and fresh. I didn't drink, but everyone else were drinking. As someone here has mentioned, I also felt that their goal was to get people drunk. In the end, the chef asked if anyone wants to try the wagyu or any of the previous nigiris again. 

Overall, the service was great but expect to pay about $200 per person.

text:
I created an account because I NEEDED to write this review.  The food at IV Drip is great (sometimes).  The ice cream is great (sometimes).  However, over the past 3 years they have raised prices to EXORBITANT levels.  It is completely ridiculous and simply cheating the customer to ask $8.50 for a simple milkshake.  When I first started going to IV Drip it was around $5.50 for a milkshake (3 years ago), there is simply no excuse for such an outrageous increase in prices, and as a result, I will never be going back.

McConnell's on State Street (the same ice cream) costs nearly the same, but with higher operating costs, which indicates IV Drip should be able to succeed with their previously lower prices.  For true comparison, a pint of Dutchman's chocolate (16 oz) is $10.00. text:
It was an early (ish) Sunday morning and my friend and I decided to head up to the Santa Ynez Valley for a day of wine tastings.  A little over halfway there we both decided to put some caffeine stimulation in our blood before drinking. After driving up and down State St I pointed out a red awning - in a six block radius there were three Starbucks (WTH?) and well...I wanted local.

Its situated like a living room - couches, a fireplace, small tables,  benches along the wall - and it was pretty packed.  People were also taking advantage of the great weather by sitting on patio. 

The coffee drinks themselves were fine - my friend had a chai and I had a white chocolate mocha -- both were OK, you know when something is perfectly acceptable but not outstanding in any way? Classify our drinks under that.

Although sadly we didn't indulge, the offering of pastries looked quite fresh and tasty.

I did enjoy some good people watching while waiting for our drinks to be made- an very tall preppy man with dark sparkly painted toenails and a woman screaming Haitian or French into her cell phone. 

Ah, a lovely Sunday morning in Santa Barbara.

text: As far as Italian goes, you can't go wrong with Pascucci's. Everything from their dcor to their menu screams old school Italian. With several fire places and red velvet cushioned chairs, you are basically transported to Italy! The food is great as well! There are so many great things to choose from, but I usually go with the "Risotto Carbonaro" - this one isn't on the menu anymore, but they'll still make it if you ask for it! It has pancetta, mushrooms and peas...just delicious!  A must try for all of those Italian enthusiasts out there! Bon Apetit!

text:
I am a big fan of Noodle City.  Delicious noodles, good vegetarian options, YUM Vietnamese iced tea, and quick service.  Saigon In & Out use to be my go-to place in the area for noodles but Noodle City has moved up in the ranks.  This place is super low-key, reasonably priced and really good  (the food at SIO seems to have slide down a few notches over the past few years, maybe they got too big with there 3+ locations or maybe I've hit them on off days).  

As others have noted, Noodle City has a crazy-busy lunch hour which can be somewhat avoided if you call in your order ahead of time.

text: Found this place on Yelp the reviews were good and it's a Sunday half price on burgers and flatbread and a 7 minute drive from our hotel!!! The ambiance is welcoming... We ordered the 1114 burger, pesto flatbread, fries and the Kung pao Brussel sprouts. Every item was delicious!!! The burger was cooked to order and it was juicy and tasty. The Brussel sprouts were Cooked perfectly and they were spicy just how I like them. The pesto flatbread was flavorful and very delicious . We left there full and satisfied... I am so glad we came in and will come back again

text:
Awful place. 
Yes they sell Silvergreens sandwiches and salads. That's nice. 
They probably make great fancy coffee drinks for which you pay too much. 
But 5 months a year in SB, this place is an oven. 
I parked in the lot before my cheap massage at Little Rainbow Spa and got a glass of ice water and a SB power bar. It was 70 and breezy outside. Inside, over 80 with a bunch of comatose individuals on laptops or reading. 
One of the many annoyances of SB is the citywide aversion to a/c. Do SB people think it's a plot of Satan that gives you cancer? 2 million dollar houses have no a/c. Some new fancy houses are plumbed for it, but the owners don't even install central air. 
It's a pretty place which is however uninhabitable for anyone who doesn't like living by the equator (or Phoenix). 
I would never spend more than 2 minutes in this place except during the winter, and even then the whole no a/c thing offends me so much I would boycott and avoid in protest. I hate cheapness and the failure to install a/c is simply obnoxious. 

NO WAY.

text:
Been coming to FP since day 1. Great and consistent coffee and espresso. But their in-house bakery is a disappointment.  

And yet today I fell for their pumpkin, pecan, chocolate bread. (I was starving, ok.)  First, it was small by any standard. Second, it was hard and dry, as if baked yesterday. (At 7am.). 

Lastly, I couldn't believe they charged me $4.25. When I raised the issue with the woman taking orders, she said, "Hey, I don't decide how much to charge."

text:
My coworker recommended this little shop for some fresh seafood, especially uni! Unfortunately when my man and I came here on a Sunday, they were out of uni.
Instead we ordered oysters and tuna, trout, and salmon sashimi. They shuck the oysters and slice the sashimi for you for a small fee. Altogether it cost ~$40 for everything. 
The trout sashimi turned out to be my favorite! We would love to come back here to try their tray of fresh uni next time!

text:
Called for a reservation on this past New Years weekend. The person told me they
only had a 6:30 left. We needed a time after 7:00. They asked me if it was a special occasion and I said yes, in fact it was a birthday. They gave us a 7:00 reservation. When my wife and I arrived the place was packed. The other party was running a little late. They seated my wife and I at a great table immediately.
As usual with Opal, great good and drinks.
Our server Paul was outstanding.
In addition to the great service they had remembered it was a birthday and brought a candle on the dessert we ordered.

text:
Our waiter was Jorge and he was smiling, helpful and laughed at our jokes. But most usefully he helped me pick the braised short ribs, (braised for 12 hours), the beet salad and the (yes, sugar free me fell off the wagon) coconut cake.
The salad was great and healthy. The braised short ribs were tender and the reduction just an explosion of yummy complex flavor. The coconut cake was orgasmic. But, full disclosure I hadn't eaten anything with sugar in it for a while. But everyone who was wily enough to distract me and cadge a bite oohed and ahhed over it.
Jorge and other staff kept us watered and coffee'd swiftly and checked on how we were doing often. This is frequently missing these days.
I get the sense that at Giannfranco's attentive friendly service is a priority and I really appreciate that.
I also liked that it wasn't a noisy restaurant and the ambiance was very nice. Next time we'll go on a warm night and try eating on their beautiful outdoor patio.
Oh and thrill of thrills, the owner came by and made sure we were having a good time. I love that. I'll be back!

text:
We stopped here on our way home to OC from the Bay Area. I was hungry, but not feeling so great as my travelling companion weaved in and out down the twists and turns of the 101. We arrived and I had questions about one of the burgers. Nick was working the counter. He was incredibly helpful and unbelievably hospitable. Watching him it was apparent he was earnest in giving the best customer service to each person who walked in.

Because we were there so late we watched as Nick prepared the dinning room to get mopped. He was thorough as he put the chairs up and swept the rest of the room without making a scene, allowing us to enjoy the rest of our dining experience peacefully.

I hope the location management is aware of what a genuine Super Star Nick is for their location.

I ordered the BFC with a Beyond Meat patty and my friend had the Famous Star with cheese. We both enjoyed our meals.

text:
My boyfriend and and I came to Santa Barbara so he can show me his alma mater (UCSB) and he said it was a must to go to Sambo's. 
Came when there was a ton of people (around 10:00 am) only waited about 10 maybe 15 minutes and was seated. 
Waitress was sweet and explained how there are no chocolate chip pancakes. We can add the chocolate chips but it'll be extra. 
My boyfriends plate came with two pancakes (added chocolate chips) eggs (substantiated that for fruit) & hash browns. 
I got the French toast plate. Four slices of French toast, two eggs. I had a choice of two sausage or two bacon strips (sausage always). 
Everything was great.
One minor detail I should mention was you guys promoted free WiFi but it was password protected. We asked our waitress and she said it should be free but when we showed her she didn't know why it was asking for a password. Just wanted to point that out.

text:
I've been to Hana several times over the past two years and I personally think that this is the best food place in Isla Vista. 
The food overall is pretty good. The bowls (I've only had chicken) are a bit pricey (a dollar less and they'd be perfect, but I know it's unrealistic) and their tacos are good (chicken tacos and $1.50 tacos on Tuesday). They take a while to come out and they often get backed up, but it's usually worth. The veggies that come with the bowl goes well with the spicy mayo sauce and the cucumbers that they have there. 
The boba is meh. Usually it's too sweet for me, and one time (a long time ago, but still noteworthy for me) they made the drink not sweet enough (tasted like there was no sugar whatsoever). Snows are good but sweet and the pearls aren't bad. 
Overall, it's a go to for food, but an afterthought for boba.

text:
Horrible service/delivery and employee knowledge.  

When this place first opened the bowls were better quality and larger portions. Ever since, they have lessened in quality and gotten smaller.

I want go to Hana Kitchen because I like the style of food and it is so convenient.  However, I have been treated poorly by employees and the owner on multiple occasions for asking simple menu and delivery questions.  The employees have no idea how to treat a customer or how to give compensation when due. 

They once took over 90 minutes to deliver, forgot one of my bobas and all the sauce I requested. When I called to tell them, they said they are too busy to bring me the rest of my order and that they would give me 10% off my next boba.  "Thanks so much for that 0.40 off"

DONT GIVE THIS PLACE YOUR BUSINESS

text:
First off, this place is difficult to park near, as the small parking lot nearby doesn't have spots for Dawn Patrol rather the other small businesses in the same building. Make sure you park in the public parking across State street (which is free for 90 minutes) or you'll find yourself driving in circles with all the one-way streets in downtown SB. 

Furthermore, I was super disappointed in this place, and am kicking myself for not have ordered a build-your-own hash!! Instead, I opted for their egg white frittata which comes with a seeded avocado and "fresh" (not so fresh) berries and washed it down with the cold brew. It wasn't at all what I expected, as you would think something that has egg whites would be on the "lighter" side. In fact, the frittata was swimming in cheese and so buttery that I felt best to leave most of the frittata on the plate than to have that gut bomb sit in my stomach. I also didn't quite understand the flavors or the point of the seeded avocado? I think I'll take my avos unseeded in the future. 

I even didn't much care for the cold brew (bland and watery)...mehhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhh

Did I mention this place is PRICEY?! We are talking $20 for my coffee and mostly inedible frittata. Yes, I get it, Santa Barbara but also, it's freaking eggs and potatoes. Don't think I'd return on my own dime.

text:
It was my first time here but had been on my list of places to try for the past 3 years! The restaurant reminded me of a set from Shrek and actually being there aligned with my expectations (minus the ogres). I really appreciated nature's calm for the ambience that really ignited the presence and appreciation of the food and birds fluttering around. Although it was extremely hot outside, there was plenty of shade at the tables and our waiter was always quick to refill our cups. 

The customer service was amazing! My partner and I split one of our entrees and the waiter and staff were so accommodating that they put it on 2 different plates for us :) 

Oh yes-and the food was fresh, the meat wasn't dry, and we finished every last bite! The wonderful mix of environment, customer service, and food is worth every penny spent. I will be this to recommending to all friends passing by or in Santa Barbara. Thanks so much for a great experience !

text:
I was so excited to find this place when my husband and I stopped through Santa Barbara. I love Thai food and was craving it. It looked pretty good from the outside, based on the building and the smell of food coming from the doorway. Most of the really authentic Thai places are not fancy inside, but boast decor from the culture. We were seated soon after we walked in and got water. A few minutes later we had our order taken by a woman who seemed like she was in a hurry or in a bad mood. We brushed it off and continued our conversation. The lady brought our Thai iced tea and started to walk away right as she sat them down. 

Once we got our food, we were pretty excited and hoping it was spicy like we asked. It seems nothing is spicy enough anymore. We have been eating spicy foods for so long. My food was not spicy at all and my husband said his wasn't either. The waitress never came to check on us while we were eating and we never had the opportunity to ask for the spice tray. I had Red Curry with eggplant and tofu. At least 3 big pieces of the eggplant were dark brown instead of the mushy white texture that it usually is. The brown pieces were hard and the little piece I tasted was bitter and gross. I scooped them aside and left it. The red curry was ok, but a bit bland in flavor. Compared to other red curries I have had, it was not up to par. My husband said his was not very flavorful either. The worst part was the service. We were only asked if things were ok when our plates were stacked and we were finished. At that point, what are we to say...no?! 

We were disappointed and the meal was forgettable. I think anyone would expect this place to be better because it is on State St. I won't be eating there next time I pass through Santa Barbara. Oh well, you can't like them all.

text:
It had been a while since I visited the Ultimate Bagel, so I was looking forward to a real treat.  I never had the chance to grab-n-go because apparently there was only one order taker and he was on the phone.  The four other guys standing around behind the counter (not working on making orders) couldn't step-in to help.  By my calculation, I wouldn't make to work on time waiting for one guy to get off the phone and get through the two other waiting customers in front of me to place their orders.

Too bad . . . it may be another long while before I try this place again.

It's not a meal in itself but very tasty.

text: I would go here again but I would stick with a simple chicken taco and nothing that sounds greasy.  The shrimp quesadilla was just too much cheese and greasy.  If that's what you're into then you'll love it.  Probably not the best food choice if you're at all health conscious.  But if you order smart you'll be just fine.  The food is good.  The salsa bar is exceptional.  Fresh everything to suit anyone's needs for whatever plate you order.  You can order a Mexican beer here to go with your meal which is always a plus.  I would recommend, but watch what you order.

text: I ate here for the first time last weekend, and I was super impressed! I had been up in Santa Barbara, and everything was annoyingly crowded up there, so just by chance I happened to stop off here on my way back down to Ventura. The place was cozy, and everyone seemed to know each other, which is always a good sign at an Italian place (regulars equal good food!). I got the avocado sub, which was surprisingly good for a quick little sub. It did have mayonnaise on it, which I wasn't too happy with, because the menu didn't specify it for that sub, while it did for all the other subs, but none the less, it still tasted delicious! It came with a side salad which was good too (just be aware, the side salad comes with salami unless you specify you don't want it!). All in all, I was very happy; good service, great location, yummy food, and all just a quick hop off the freeway!

text:
This place is really special.  Even though I only drove 2 hours from LA, I felt worlds away.  The grounds, views and service provides for an extremely relaxing getaway.  

What is cool about Barcara is how easy they make everything.  You arrive and a bellman takes you and your luggage to your room via golf cart.  When you go to the pool, towels, water, umbrellas are all provided promptly.  The food and drinks are varied enough with many choices for food and bars, most with an amazing views, that you don't need to leave the property.  When it was time to check out, the bellman took our luggage to be stored and we spent the whole day at the pool.  It didn't matter that we checked out of our room since ANY hotel guest can use the amenities at the spa.  So after a day by the pool I took a steam and had an amazing shower with anything I needed right there in the spa.  When we arrived at the bell desk- I simply gave them our last name an our things were placed in our car and away we went.  

The views coupled with the landscaping and architecture are amazing.  The employees make it easy to relax and make you feel as though they are happy to help.  The rooms are very romantic and even though we didn't have an ocean view, we were happy to stay and enjoy as the gardens are lovely.  The spa is one of the largest and nicest I have ever been to and the work out facilities are also top notch.  

I recommend Bacara to anyone looking to spend a romantic weekend away- its not the cheapest place in the world, but there are lots of extras if you have an AMEX Platinum.

text:
La Super Rica is a famous Mexican place in Santa Barbara raved by Julia Child and Katy Perry. 

Lines can be extremely long, usually out the door (although only about three people can fit between the door and cashier anyways). We went on a Monday and we only had to wait behind 2-3 people. Location is slightly far away from downtown state street, about a 3-5 minute drive.

FYI MAJOR PART: they don't take cards. You have to pay in cash. We didn't learn this until we got there, but luckily we had enough cash on us to cover it!

We got #1,#3,#4,#5,#7, and #12. #1 was really good, but not the best steak taco I've ever had. The chorizo taco was actually the best one as the meat was extremely flavorful and cooked quite well! Both #3 and #4 were similar in taste although one of the meats was drier than the other. #12 the cheese quesadilla with chicken was quite basic and I wouldn't get it again because you can do it at home and add more inside the quesadilla. The #7 tritip was really good although it needs more than 3 tacos in my opinion, more like 6 (but we asked for 3 more before cause we didn't realize the tacos were underneath the meat. All that food for about $25!

Now I'm a Lilly's girl. I love their tacos, they're cheaper than La Super Rica and their meats are SOOOO much tastier! I will say La Super Rica wins on salsa for sure, Lilly's doesn't even compare in the salsa department. We even took some home. So I'd say go get Lilly's tacos, but eat them with La Super Rica's salsa! 

There's a good amount of seating behind the kitchen area. They don't have a permanent roof and we went on a windy day and I could see it shaking, so maybe don't come on a rainy day.

Overall: 3.5 stars. Food is good, but doesn't reach height that the fame has given it. Location isn't optimum and interior is underwhelming. Go to Lilly's instead

text:
Made to order, so the empanadas are incredibly fresh in addition to being delicious. I didn't realize this isn't really a dine-in establishment. There are two counters to sit at inside or there's seating outside in a courtyard. Normally, sitting outside would be fine, but we went when it was cold and windy. 

I'd recommend getting 2-3 per person if you're hungry. They're $3.50 each, so super affordable! Yelp check-in gets you a free empanada when you order a half dozen or more.

Bottom Line; This is a great little spot that makes great food.  The people that work there are friendly and the prices aren't bad!    Sometimes it takes courage to wade though the hipsters from Woodland Hills but we must persist as a species....scarves are for wintertime, ladies.... cmon

Ok..... im willing to overlook the fact that this place used to be a Moto Guzzi dealership in which I used to visit frequently as a young man to drool over motorcycles....but now they sell sandwiches and other yummy things which makes another part of my heart jump.

   I ordered.... ummmm crap I forget what I ordered.  A really yum sandwich with Avocado on it.  My wife had - I forget what she had but it was yet another yum sandwich that she loved.  Who cares what was on it?   She loved it is all that matters.
    We had a brownie for dessert and wow - so moist, so good.

 The food came out quickly, everyone was super nice, there are lots of things to look at and consume in here..... Im really glad that we finally checked this place out after walking past it for so long.

text:
Cost Plus is my go to on so many levels! Need discount international wine? Cost Plus. Need a cookie press for grandma that says "Made with Love?" Cost Plus. Need a hipster sweater for your dog and gluten free treats from Cuba? Cost Plus.

Being that this is a huge national chain I don't think i need to say much more about the brand - You can check out their website for details. But this particular store deserves specific recognition. The staff here are very kind, on top of the line game and always have the registers at both ends of the store open for check out. They keep things neat and tidy, know where things are when you ask for help, and are very respectful when dealing with customer issues.

This location has a tiny parking lot, and I mean tiny, that lines up with the backdoor. There is also a massive Public Parking lot right behind the store that is 60 second walking distance away. The store size is big but not overwhelming and very well organized to where you don't feel hopeless and lost like at Macy's.

They have a clearance section in the very center of the store and a secret sale section in the front left corner of the baking/cooking area (if you are facing the store from State St). They also tend to mark random things on the shelf down, all the time. Regular prices are pretty affordable for everything but furniture and big items in home decor. They are amazing to get ideas from, though, if anything.

I love this store, will be back many times (this week), and will continue to highly recommend it to others.

text:
Just keeping it simple, I've had sooo much better Carne Asada. In fact I can literally WALK to Tacos La Costa in Oxnard and get great asada. On top of that, a three minute drive will get me great asada. 

I read a review on another Mexican Food place (might've been one of the over 100 on the Freebird's reviews) that they hate when a place cooks the meat un-seasoned, covers it with salsa and calls it Asada. Unfortunately that's exactly how I feel about this place. 

Last time we went I got the "Meat and Fries" --Carne Asada fries is what I'd rather call them. *shrug. It was good but if the meat was better it wouldve been soooo gooooood. See the difference? 

I got a HUGE CHUNK of veery under ripe Avocado in the guacamole. Come on. How are you going to scoop out guacamole and not even notice this gigantic chunk and not bother to remove it? If it were ripe I'd love it but it was like biting into a watermelon rind. 

I give it an extra star for
- Being open late
- The good Salsa (that saved my food)
- They serve beer
- Food's out Fast 

Other than that, it's in essence a 2-Star review. 

I'll try Freebirds next time I'm in IV.

text:
I have to bump this rating up due to my second visit.  This time I arrived at Something's Fishy I was towards the end of a day-long State Street drinking binge.  As soon as I entered, the sake bombs were calling my name.  There's no telling exactly how many I consumed, but let's suffice it to say that I had enough to not remember anything after they brought me my soup and salad.

Not only was our group extraordinarily loud, messy and drunk but we were buying sake bombs for a group of minors across the restaurant.  So thank you Something's Fishy for putting up with our drunken antics and not kicking us out.  Thank you also for not carding those sweet newlyweds who couldn't have been much past 19.

P.S. I hope I didn't throw up in your bathroom.

text:
I made a reservation at Blush on open table for 12/27 at 6:45pm. It was "promoted" as being a 1000 point reservation and we thought we would try something different. My husband and I arrived at the restaurant and I informed them I had made the reservation on open table. 

We were seated in the patio and asked the server if the fireplaces worked. She told us they did, so we asked to be moved next to it. She tried to turn the fireplace on but wasn't able to. Someone else came by and we asked them to turn it on and we were informed it didn't work. 

The service was extremely slow and we were originally served us someone else's entree. When we eventually got our meal, the food was decent. If we were just reviewing on food alone, we could give them 3 stars. Unfortunately because of the service we can only say the overall experience was a 1 star.

I paid for our dinner with my credit card. The next day I reviewed my open table app and I could not find any record of my reservation. I looked in my email and found that the restaurant had "cancelled" my reservation. I called the reservation desk to inquire and left a message asking that someone return my call. Five days later, I have still not heard back from Blush, nor did I ever get the promised 1000 points!  

A couple days ago I sent another message on the Blush website asking for them to correct the issue and I have still not heard back. It is obvious that this is a failing restaurant that does not care about its customers. It is sad because they have the potential to rival The Lark, which has excellent service, food and atmosphere.

text:
I was REALLY hoping this place would be good...it in such a prime location with so much potential!!! They have a beautiful rooftop lounge/bar/dining area that overlooks the ocean and the Santa Barbara Warf.  The inside of Oku is fairly large with a great outdoor patio and lots of indoor seating.  There is also bar area with open seating. 

My friends and I were really hopeful and excited to check this place out because we 1) LOVE sushi and 2) LOVE the location and ambiance here.  We called at 3pm on a Saturday with hopes there may be a table or wait list and I was rudely told that it is a Saturday on valentines weekend and my only shot to dine here was at 10:15pm...I was very thrown off by the abrupt and rude tone on the phone, but understand when people may be busy or having a bad day...anyway we decided to go anyway and try our hand at a seat at the bar.  We arrived at 8:30 and there were definitely a few available tables, but again we were told there was no way we could get a table for 4 people.  We asked if the bar area was full service and if the patio was reservation only.  The hostess said there was a small bar area upstairs but "it was probably full" so we just stuck to a high top by the indoor bar...there was NO ONE at the indoor bar... so I was very hopeful the service would be quick. 

One thing I have heard from people is that Oku has GREAT cocktails.  So I was really excited about their drink menu.  I ordered the "Red Lily" cocktail, and I will say it was DELICIOUS.  My friend got the "Hidden Dragon" drink and she really liked it as well.  It did feel like we were a bit neglected by the waitresses, it must have been because  we were the only high top in the bar so maybe people were forgetting to check in, but after a little we were able to order.  I got the "Pink Cadillac" roll because my waitress suggested it, I also ordered the salmon "lollipops".  I really enjoyed the lollipop rolls, it is a great roll if you are trying to avoid cards as the fish is wrapped in a thinly sliced cucumber.  It was a super fresh roll and easy to eat because of the lolli stick it came with.  I was a bit disappointed with the Cadillac roll.  It was basically a glorified California roll. I was not impressed at all.  The fish was fairly fresh, but the food didn't blow me away.  I wish I had tried the cauliflower starter because after I went a lot of people said they enjoyed that appetizer.  

Overall I was not impressed with the food and service here, its a really good location and that is what you will be paying for when you come.  I did like the drinks a lot.  I would definitely come back to enjoy a cocktail on the rooftop, but can't foresee myself dining here again.

text:
First of all,  everyone is so nice and friendly.  I ordered the fried chicken sandwich with a side salad . 
  The fried chicken was made from the breast but was moist and crunchy. The spread was tasty.  Underneath the chicken was a crunchy cabbage slaw. The buns were fluffy and soft,  it tasted like they baked it themselves but I don't know. It tasted like layers of buttery goodness. 
     Even the side salad was good.  Just some mixed greens, yellow and red  sweet cherry tomatoes , sunflower seed for texture.

text:
We just ordered 15 meals to be delivered to the beach. We specifically asked for utensils since 12 of them had rice. We're didn't receive the utensils and when we called back the only answer to "uh huh I see it here."  We didn't even get napkins. Mistakes happen but to not believe the order was put in until she pulled it up and act like I was the one lying was a little shocking. Still waiting to see what they will do since the food can't eaten at this point.

Update: the employee we spoke to said she would call back. It's now the next day and we're still waiting. I could give a hint: apologize, deliver necessary utensils, refund and even offer them to be picked up and give something for free. What not to do is NOT- not care, act like the customer did something wrong and Definitely NOT not call back. None of the above happened BUT guest relations replied to my Yelp before the store has even called me. Still waiting... 

I'm sure this happens often; another hint: there should be a standard process that employees follow that includes the above remedies. A bit of free CS consultation.

text:
Went on a Saturday date night here and the whole experience was amazing.

The staff was extremely kind and polite the moment we walked in. The interior design was also very romantic with dimmed lights and candles. Our waitress was eager to serve us, making small talk, and was eager to help when my date asked for a wine recommendation. We arrived a little closer to closing time so the restaurant wasn't very busy as well.

I ordered the shrimp pasta and my date had the chicken with mushrooms. Both of our dishes were amazing. I wished I could have finished mine, but I got too excited and filled up on the free bread.

Desert was by far the best part of our meal. We ordered the chocolate ganache for two, and after the first bites, we both stopped and looked and each other with wide eyes. It was amazing. It was almost a competition now because we both wanted as much of the cake as we could have. The presentation was also very classy and neat with a little drizzled calligraphy on the plate.

All in all, it was an amazing date night and I'll never forget that cake. We plan on coming back again whenever we're both in Santa Barbara again!

text:
This place is a true find. My husband and I came out to Santa Barbara to enjoy a show and wanted a light lunch to hold us over till dinner. 

This place was packed but the downstairs bar had some room. I ordered a Bloody Mary and my husband got the margarita. We also ordered the peel and eat shrimp and fish and chips.

The drinks came quick and strong! I didn't care for my Bloody Mary. Too much horseradish for my taste. 

The peel and et shrimp was very good! I didn't care for mustard seeds(I think that's what they were, because they got all over the place.

The fish and chips were a home run! The fish is fresh. No doubt. 

I wish we lived close to to eat here more but I was very happy with what we got. The servers were quick and courteous. 

If you are in the neighborhood, hit this place up.

text:
Came here on a Saturday afternoon because I had had their wines a couple years ago and remembered they were good at the time. Place was busy but there was a small spot at the tasting bar that we grabbed. People working were very friendly and dos a great job getting everyone there what they wanted which is tough since it's pretty spread out. Also there was a large bachelorette party that came in with like 9 or 10 people but they all seemed pleased. So nice place and good service and good atmosphere, but I just have to say the 3 stars are for the wine, I really didn't dig it at all. 
I had the Pinot tasting and to be honest I didn't think any of the 5 were very good. The 2nd one on the list, the Mesa was the best of the bunch, but it was just mediocre, especially for close to $50 per bottle. I don't mind spending money on good wine, but none of these did it for me at all, and 3 of them tasted so similar it was eerie but yet prices were different. I know it's hard to make 5+ Pinots and then figure out pricing for all of them, but I really didn't care for any of these. Maybe the whites are better but Pinots are not great in my opinion. Could be I'm just spoiled since my family lives in Sonoma county and I've been tasting there for over 10 years and the wines are just better, but still, I just didn't care for it here which is too bad. 
But I still wonder the idea behind making 5+ Pinots which are similar in price range, but hey maybe there's a method to the madness.

text:
I went here for dinner with 8 or 9 girlfriends.  Apparently they lost our reservation, but it wasn't that busy so it was okay.  They sat us all at a corner booth, which was kind of inconvenient (i.e., bathroom runs), but it was spacious enough.

The waiter was very friendly!  I checked-in here, and a got a free calamari appetizer deal for checking in.  Sometimes I feel weird about using those free coupon things, but he was really nice about it!  Too bad the calamari was just okay.  It was too greasy, but the sauce was really tasty!

I asked the waiter if he preferred the salmon or the chicken, and he said the chicken.  GOOD CHOICE!  Three of us had the chicken (and they let one of my friends substitute the couscous for mashed potatoes), and we unanimously agreed it was delicious.  The couscous was flavorful, and the chicken was moist and tender.  Yum.

My friends seemed to be happy with some other dishes - seared ahi, seafood cobb, and cioppino.  I didn't try any, but there were no complaints.  Also, 

Also, this place has free valet parking!  Cool plus.

I would give this place a 3 star, just because it's a little too pricy, however the quantity and quality was good.  The service was nice.  (Our waters were continuously filled.)  And I'll bump it to 4 stars because the chicken was so darn delicious AND they charge you no corkage fee if you bring two bottles of wine or less!

text:
What might seem like a tourist trap is actually a favorite among locals. Posted at the end of the pier overlooking the glorious ocean, on a clear day, it's absolutely the greatest place to soak in SB's cool, casual vibe of coastal sophistication. 

The tastings are affordable and well-rounded. The staff is friendly and has some jokes up their sleeves, as well as some notes on the wines in the event you're interested in that sort of thing. Me? I'm just there to appreciate the view and feel a little finey winey.

They have blankets if there's a nip in the air, so clearly your comfort is their first priority. In addition, you can bring your own food up to the venue. And, don't forget to check-in on Yelp for an extra tasting!

text:
Pre-lockdown review: Jane is one of the best options for fine dining in Goleta. Their brunch, lunch, and dinner menus all offer various standard American entrees with occasional inspiration from other cuisines. For brunch, I highly recommend any of the benedicts. My personal favorite is the slow roasted pulled pork benedict. For lunch and dinner, I recommend their oak burning brick oven pizzas.

The restaurant itself is spacious, with outdoor seating and two different sections of indoor seating. The hosts and waiters are always welcoming, friendly, and responsive.

Watch out for the bread and butter they serve before the meal, it's irresistable!

text: This is my go to lunch spot during the week. The line can get pretty long depending on when you go, but if you show up after 1:00 PM the line is much shorter. In either case, the tacos are worth it and the staff is very friendly. I have tried most of the tacos on the menu and they are all pretty good. My favorite is definitely the carne asada. The salsa bar is well stocked, and I recommend you load up. The green salsa says spicy but is zesty and tangy; it's great with the addition of a squeezed lime. Overall, great food option that does not disappoint.

text: From the stale bread and burnt breadsticks in the bread basket, to the lackluster cioppino, to the burnt tasting & room-temperature-obviously-not-decaf-or-why-am-I-still-awake-at-3:30am-coffee, to the server who spent more time checking out his tips from other tables and obviously trying to upsell and pander for a bigger tip than providing actual service, to the LOUD interior, to the "mousse" that was so thick and heavy that it was practically pudding, this restaurant only earned a couple of stars for two reasons. The cioppino had very good seafood (scallops!) and the tiramisu was light, delicate, and the perfect amount of sweetness.  However, the flavor of the cioppino at Brophy Brothers is far superior. Don't waste your time here - dinner took 2  1/2 hours, or your money. If you're in the mood for Italian, go to Olio e Limone or Ca Dario.

text:
Gotta love YELP!  I checked in on my phone and a FREE Lager beer was offered with check in! What a nice surprise, and my friend's dad was so happy to receive it since it was a "dry" luncheon, with a set of options that didn't include imbibing. We enjoyed  a price fixed lunch in a special private space that was great for 30 people, 15 per table.  

We started with an option of either clam chowder or salad, I opted for salad since we already had bread and butter on the table and dessert was the final course.  Most people tried the chowder and loved it.   I had read the previous Yelps about the honey pie so knew I needed to save some room for that!   My entree was the Mahi Mahi with Macadamia Nuts. AMAZING!  Great flavors! Really well prepared light fish served with rice and crispy onions on top... I ate the whole thing!  (and still had room for dessert, OK I skipped breakfast, don't judge).  My friend had the swordfish and equally pleased and happy to share her steamed broccoli.   All in all the servers were attentive and friendly, they were mindful of our schedule and the whole experience was smooth sailing.

text:
The good stuff :
1. The ambience is great. I would say it is better than the one on Cliff Dr. I am really glad that they opened up a branch in Goleta. 

2. I was reimbursed for my dish as I found chicken in my vegetarian chowmein. The server was very nice to have given us a reimbursement for that. 

The NOT so good stuff:
1. We waited for about 15 mins till we were given a table. The servers had to be reminded that we needed to be seated. All of them saw us standing there, but no one attended. 

2. The waiter paid no attention to the fact that we hadn't even given menus. The next table who came after us was attended to before we were. 

3. The waiter forgot to take our order even after we told him that we had been waiting for a long time for someone to take our order.

4. The food was sub par.

text: I was in Santa Barbara for the last few days on vacation and decided to give this place a shot after reading reviews.  I must say that I was pleased for the most part.  I enjoyed how they had meal options w/A platter that had 3 different items on it(which allowed for tasting multiple entrees).  I feel that this is always a great attraction to the consumer(so we can enjoy different flavors/spices).  Their Chana masala(spicy) was great, the Saag o Paneer was good, and Daal was okay.  The naan was delicious, and samosa tasty.  Fresh Chutneys that went along with that never hurts too.  Compared to other places I would say that this is affordable and good food so I left happy.  Thank you! :)

text: This is truly the best hidden gem in Santa Barbara for Italian Food, as it is off the downtown area. text:
Wow! Hands down my favorite Lure fishhouse. I had an issue with one of my orders one day and when I called in about it, Garrett was extremely personable and offered me and my fiance a complimentary entree on the vip list. So glad I came back, because I tried the ahi tuna and it was hands down the best meal i've had.

They really do care a lot about their customer service and making sure you are satisfied. Thank you to management and whoever hires the employees, great oversight and judgement!

I'll be coming back here for a long time!

text:
of course I agree with everyone else that the location is idyllic.  

I went for a girls' luncheon with two friends and I did find the service a slow,  but friendly.  

I had a Cesar salad which was excellent, and the dungeness crab cake appetizer which was also very tasty. 

the one thing which I was disappointed about would have to be the cocktail I ordered.  It was the blood orange margarita.  The description on the menu was wonderful:  "El Charro 100% Agave Tequila, fresh blood orange juice, fresh lime, Triple Sec and a splash of sweet and sour. Served on the rocks with a salted rim."  but it just tasted like straight tequila... and I do like a strong drink.  I guess I got my money's worth in liquor, but not really because I couldn't even finish it.  Just way too strong.  

I had recently enjoyed amazing drinks at the SB Fishhouse down on Cabrillo which I believe is the same owner, and so my expectations were high for the cocktail.  Oh well.  

I felt like the waitress was just too rushed and I didnt have the heart to send it back.  

beautiful setting.  service was a bit lax.  great food.  i will go back again for a special occasion !

Very worth while dinner outing and we will return to Little Dom's in the future. Give it a try..!

text: Gianfranco is our favorite Italian restaurant, we live in Santa Monica but we don't   generally go to local  SM  Italian restaurants  as they can't compare to Gianfranco,  we go to excellent local  Lebanese,  Turkish,  Armenian , Persian and Indian  restaurant near us.   We've  been   going to  Gianfranco  annually for years for a special   holiday lunch, which we did yesterday, it was  extraordinary, and when we can  during the year. As it's a 3 hour and sometime more  roundtrip journey  we can't go there often, but it's wonderful. Of course , we'll be there as usual    December  2020 for our annual  holiday lunch, in addition we also plan on coming in  May or early June and eating outside on their delightful patio, when the weather should still be mild. We love  this  family owned restaurant with excellent food, charming ambiance and great service.

text: In the mountains high above Santa Barbara, in what seems like the middle of nowhere, is a magical place that serves great food and drinks. An old stage coach stop from the late 1800's is the setting of this magical place. My friends and I were there on a Friday afternoon and there were people waiting outside for a table. Our reservations were for 1:30 pm and it was still croso if possible, I would recommend making reservations. The French dip, tri-tip sandwich, and ribs with onion rings on the side were what my friends ordered. The onion rings looked fabulous and my friends confirmed they were as were the sandwiches and ribs. I had the roasted vegetable salad and it was delicious. We had Cold Spring Tavern's bacon and asparagus quiche for breakfast that morning and it was the best quiche I had ever had. Our server that day was very personable and provided excellent service. My previous visit to the Cold Spring Tavern was about 23 years ago and the food was great then, so I am pretty confident the great quality is consistent.

text:
Just discovered this neat little gem for the first time. Must say, I'm a fan. 

As a local, I'm happy to slowly start seeing this section of the lower east side become gentrified. There are a lot of cool little buildings on this block being restored, and it's a welcome change to the overall dinginess of what it once was. 

Very neat vibe as I walked in. I dig the fun ambient lighting, abundance of lush greenery, and the rustic yet modern decor. When I first heard of this spot, I learned that they are "zero waste", meaning that none of their kitchenware can be thrown away. If you plan on placing your order to-go, it's suggested that you bring a cup of your own as they simply don't provide them. I opted to place my order for-here, though, as the little dining room was simply too cool to walk out of. 

The waitstaff were all very friendly, and the vibe was quite relaxed. I ordered a cold brew (the barista suggested ordering a small as it was pretty caffeine-laden) along with their signature avo toast. Both items were exceptional, and the toast was a work of art - almost too beautiful to consume. Prices are on the higher side, but honestly not all that bad considering we're in Santa Barbara. 

Upon perusing the menu, I noted a host of signature cocktails. I will certainly try one the next time I dine here!

text:
Yelp to the rescue again!  Jetted up the coast with a car full of lady friends to celebrate our Australian friend's visit.  While en route I asked one of them to Yelp on their phones for brunch in Santa Barbara.  They found Jeannine's and we're so glad we stopped in Montecito to take "refreshment" at this little gem instead of in crowded Santa Barbara.

Although it was packed with customers our food was outstanding and so was the service.  Each of us got something different and all were satisfied.  The service was so spectacular that when the hostess saw we were still waiting for a table after 3 attempts to be seated she brought out a free piece of cake to soften the blow.  Watching our figures, none of us had wanted to order dessert but you didn't have to twist our arms to try this super kind chocolate/mocha accommodation.  And the cake did not disappoint.  Rich flavors but still moist and light.

My friends ordered the lobster benedict, banana kahlua french toast and salmon hash.  They all loved their dishes.  I also need to comment on the water, which was flavored with fruit and super delicious.  It was available at a self-serve counter in a large dispenser with pieces of fresh melon packed in a diffuser-sort of compartment.  We each had 3-4 glasses of the refreshing elixir.

Jeannine's is a charming spot, worth the stop before you hit Santa Barbara and I wager provides better service than you're going to find on State Street.
