text:
So, I've been here at least 20 times in the last 15 years.
My kids, nieces and nephews love having " dinner and a show".
However tonight  was an all time low. I'm not sure if it's been since they changed their name from something's fishy to hibachi steak house or if management has changed but the last few times we have gone has been worse and worse. 
Tonight  started well, we all got seated got drinks and ordered but the hostess forgot to turn on the grill.
No big deal,  they offered us free appetizers and drinks on the house. Cool, we'll wait..
But the fact that it takes 15 -20 minutes to heat up the grill ( not the chef's fault entirely) they were back in 5 minutes and started cooking. We had a party of 10 and both chefs have been there for many years. 
They started doing the volcano onion and it was barely hot enough to flame at all, then they gave my sister my wife's rare steak then took it back and re fired it.
My wife's rare steak was given to her cold/ blue. my nephew got my niece's filet mignon and they said it was new York strip,
The vegetables were just boiling in their own juice and became spongy and inedible. 
I get and understand that it was Friday night and it was going to be busy but we all would have been much happier to hang out an chat for 10 minutes more when you are paying over $300.00 for dinner and half of it is inedible 
It's a shame they have a spot on the corner of state and haley that will always have downtown traffic and quality doesn't seem to matter anymore .
That will be the last time I ever go there.

text:
What a fun place.  It's very easy to miss, but trust me, you'll like it.

We ventured over to Live Culture while we were waiting for dinner at Pascucci's.  The staff is so friendly, and helped us choose some wines.  He let us taste four different pinots, and we decided to purchase a bottle of one (slightly pricey, but it's wine, it's not Live Culture's fault) based on their recommendations on the tastings.

Another bartender/waitress was chopping up some olive/cheese combination and topping it on crostini, which she offered to our whole group.  Complimentary!

text: Stella Mare's is our go-to dinner restaurant when visiting Santa Barbara/Montecito on a ladies wine-tasting getaway. To start with, it's easy to get to from our hotel (especially via Lyft, which facilitates enjoyment of the excellent bar). The French country ambience of the indoor dining areas and the spacious glass-covered atrium is at once comfortable and elegant. The service is superb, from the host who greets us upon arrival and gives us the option of seating (including cheerfully letting us change our minds on occasion before settling in), to our server and the bus people, all of whom work together seamlessly, attentively and personably. These qualities are the setting for an extensive and delicious menu of French country classics. Most recently, my friend enjoyed the braised lamb shanks while I indulged in the sole meuniere, accompanied by local California wines that our server suggested we taste before making a decision. For dessert, we shared a slice of lemon cake with cappuccinos and a glass of Calvados cognac to finish. The service is attentive without being rushed, and we always leave feeling that our friendship has been celebrated and nourished by an exceptional dining experience.

text:
This place is a hidden gem. I was recommeded to visit here because the next door coffee shop only served cookies and beverages but nothing savory.
 
It took me a good 5 minutes to reel in the menu because there are a variety of sandwiches/subs etc. I only know that my first thought was whatever sandwich I order must have avocado as an ingredient. I choose the De La Guerra. I remember hearing the chief sandwich artist say to his co-workers as they were trying quickly to prepare the orders

 "ok ,who's next, who's been waiting too long, wait! We've got 3 Ana's all waiting for the same sandwich?" It was hilarious...I dont think they knew I heard them :)

When my sandwich was prepared the server happily bought out my order and whispered to me that he added a cup of special sauce in the bag just in case I wanted to try it :)

Well done customer service!

text: Was driving passed and wanted a good sandwich. Seen this location (they have a few locations as well) and ordered. text: The food here isn't bad.  A standout for me were the regular fries, which were made perfectly!  The sweet potato fries were cut thicker and a little on the soggy side.  The fried fish was a bit oily, but very tender, and the portions were good.  However, overall I was expecting a different atmosphere.  It doesn't feel like a seafood place.  It's more of a sports bar with loud music.  The inside looks very similar to the previous incarnation (Killer Shrimp).  If it weren't for the loud atmosphere, I would have enjoyed our visit more.  The servers are very nice and efficient.

text:
Stopped by on a Thursday night with my boyfriend because we were craving hot pot and this is seriously the ONLY good quality Asian place in the Santa Barbara area. We always come here for a delicious meal whenever we're craving authentic Asian food :)) 

My overall experience: They're taking COVID guidelines very seriously! The tables are separated at a good distance and it's also nicely surrounded by a white fence. They have string lights hanging around and nice music playing so the atmosphere is wonderful for a peaceful dinner. The waiter was also super friendly with helping us pick out our order and recommended us some of their popular items!

Food experience: I ordered the Angus beef hot soup and my boyfriend ordered a Sukiyaki hot soup. It was so perfect for a chilly night and I definitely had that warm feeling you get with the first sip of soup. I absolutely love the sauces too that you can mix around on your own to adjust to your own taste. It's literally a must every time I get hot pot because I love dipping all my hot pot items into their sauces. My boyfriend also loved the Sukiyaki because it came with so many items like fish balls, clams, and udon! I wish we took pics beforehand but we devoured everything before I could even think of taking any pictures :'( 

I definitely recommend coming here especially since nights are getting chilly now and a nice hot pot meal will undoubtedly warm you up! Make sure to waitlist on Yelp beforehand too so you don't need to wait that long :DD Will definitely come back again bc I seriously love this place

50% sweetness was perfect amount of sweetness. Not too sweet but not bland. I wanted more of a roasted flavor to the tea and just a stronger tea flavor overall. The boba was okay. I wanted it to be a bit chewier, but it did have a nice sweet taste.

text:
It has a nice view of the ocean and compared to the restaurants on the Santa Barbara Pier, there's not really a line to eat here. Although I've only eaten here on the weekday so it may get busier on the weekends.

Food wise, the quality and portions are average and the prices are high. My Salmon with fries as a side was lacking. Freshness of the Salmon was good, flavor was OK. But it was tiny, it's 19 bucks for that tiny piece in my picture, the fries were twice its size. If I knew how small it would be I wouldn't have ordered it. Fries were oversalted, I had to wipe the salt off.

Service was good, there are better spots to have a view and dinner with probably higher wait times.

text:
Wonderful service, delicious food, beautiful space. 

We were driving up the coast and wanted to stop at the perfect Santa Barbara spot. This fit the bill. Parking was super easy and we had 10 min until our reservation so we enjoyed walking along the water briefly. 

We sat upstairs and shared the firecracker shrimp, the chowder, the crab cakes and the bouillabaisse. All were exceptional and our server was so warm and welcoming that we felt at home the entire meal. 

Physical space is also quite neat. Take a look at the windy staircase that goes up to the tower.

text: My oldest grandson and I thought the 2014 and 2015 Reserve Cabernet Sauvignon for $80 a bottle was excellent.  They also have a couple of very good red blends for a more reasonable price. Their wine was also a big hit with both of my daughters on an earlier trip after trying it at the SY Kitchen in Santa Ynez.  Tasting fee of $20 is waived with a purchase of three bottles.  Very good service.  Wine tasting room is crowded on the weekend.  Public parking is available within a block or two from El Paseo in downtown Santa Barbara.

text:
To be honest... I run customer service teams and I was completely dumbfounded as to how a simple solution to a customer problem was not addressed. I received a car wash this morning an my way to work (paid for their Works car wash) and when I got to work, I saw that there was still ash all over my car from the recent fires. I was thinking I'd go back at lunch time and see if they would let me pass through the other car wash bay just in case there was something wrong with the one I went through earlier.

At lunch, I went to the station to see if they would look at my truck and come up with a solution (thinking a simple second pass would clean my car). I spoke with the manager (she was nice) and she stated that she needed to talk with the car wash guys. She came back and said that I needed to pay for another wash. There was no way around it. 

Making a happy customer was not on the agenda apparently for something so simple and wouldn't cost hardly anything. I paid full price BTW for the Works wash (and didn't take the discount for getting gas even though I put $75 in during my lunch break when I returned for the additional wash). Sounds like the car wash guys made the decision, but I would think that the Manager would have a say in the situation.

If it were my company, I'd do what it takes to make the customers happy (within reason).

text:
I just want to say the food was AMAZING!!!

However, the service was so crazy slow. AT LUNCH! Once we were sat at a booth, it took 15 minutes for us to be greeted and given drinks. It really wasnt busy at all, I was a server before at a sports bar and I know busy, this wasnt busy at all. 
Our server was Tasha. We ordered 2 sodas and 2 waters. 
I asked for a straw, and im not even kidding you, it took 45 minutes to get the ONE straw! Along with the food. We got the food, before she remembered the straw. 
Once we got finished the food, we were waiting for the desert menu, and then it took ANOTHER 30 minutes to get 2 cheesecake slices and ICE CREAM!!!!  Are you kidding me??!! 

While the food was amazing and the prices was moderate, the service was shit. 
The server came to our table 3x in the 3 HOURS we were there!! While she was tending to the tables that obviously spent more money that us. 

Legit, poor service. Slow food.

text:
As a long-time resident of the area, I have seen many new restaurants open and close in the Camino Real Marketplace, so when I read about Pastavino's arrival, I was excited to see how it compared. After reading numerous other reviews, both online and in the paper, my husband and I decided to try it out last week for ourselves. 

We should have just stayed at home. The decor was good, and the prices were very reasonable, and the bartender we ordered drinks from (I think his name was Matt) was very friendly, and a good mixer. The low rating is solely because of the horrible service we received. It was like our server, a dark-haired, overly made-up Amy Winehouse wanna-be, purposely disregarded our orders. My husband ordered a three-topping pizza, and the one that was delivered to our table had only pepperoni and olive, neither of which he ordered. I ordered the fettucini alfredo without shrimp (i'm allergic) and sure enough, that request was not followed either. I did however catch our waitress gabbing with her co-workers about how many "hot guys" she had met at a party the weekend before. Maybe if she had paid half as much attention to her guests as to her social life, she would have gotten a better tip from us.

Now, I know that I sound like I'm just especially bitter, but the truth is I worked in the restaurant industry for almost six years, and am usually fairly understanding. Everyone makes mistakes, and I know that serving people day in and day out wears down even the most courteous of waiters. Nevertheless, the service I received was beyond abysmal, and I most definitely won't be returning to pastavino for a while, to give them time to weed out the clearly incompetent staff that managed to slip in. I wish I remembered our server's name, to warn the Yelpers out there who ever have the misfortune of sitting with her. Just know if you are greeted by a chubby brunette wearing more eye makeup than a KISS tribute band, kindly excuse yourselves and go sit at the bar. You won't regret it.

text:
Messy and delightful!
Top notch seafood at a reasonable price. Four sauces and levels of spiciness can give you a different experience each time. For a few extra dollars, "Louisiana Style" adds sausage, potatoes, and corn to your meal. 
I'm fond of the snow crab, which is very reasonably priced. I also enjoyed the mussels and the "street corn" but was disappointed with the crab bisque. 

There is a great beer selection, which is all I'm looking for, but there isn't a full bar, so the cocktails may be lacking. 

Very friendly staff, good atmosphere, and spacious, with heated patio seating.

text:
We love Andersen's pastries.  During one of our many wedding planning visits to Santa Barbara, my husband's sister brought me to this place after I told her I was craving chocolate croissants.  One look at their display window and left with not only three chocolate croissants, but an apple strudel, a few eclairs, a napoleon, and other danish pastries (Sarah Bernhardt?  something like that).  Also, marzipan is featured in a lot of their pastries.  I normally hate marzipan, but theirs is really good, so if you're a hater like me, give it a chance.  Everything was SO GOOD and I made sure to visit this place everytime I was in town.  

This includes the weekend of our wedding.  My husband and I decided to treat our immediate families to brunch the morning after our wedding.  We made a reservation for 12 for Sunday.  They gave us our little private area (upstairs).  I can vouch for how good the "real food" is here, too.  Several of us ordered the florentine benedict, while others ordered pulled pork sandwiches, scrambles, pickled herring, and one ordered the eggless breakfast (I think it had pate, some toasty bread, and cheese?).  Everyone went home happy, so that's a good sign to me.

text:
OMGGGGGGG! My new fave spot in Santa Barbara. How have I not found this place until now?? I yelped winetasting options in my area and this came up. First let me talk about the actual place. It has both indoor and outdoor seating. And the view is breathtaking! You were basically over looking The water. You can see a lot of the Santa Barbara city. We came around 7 PM and was able to catch the sunset. really gorgeous!

We wanted the real wine tasting experience so we did two flights and shared it. The wine selection is great! There's so many options and you can even purchase bottles. The staff was probably the most friendly staff I've ever met! They were so  knowledgeable on the wine and really added to our overall experience. They were fun, quirky, and energetic. We stayed and drink longer just because of them!! There were two girls one was alley and if I got the other ones name but she was a sweet blonde girl.I can't wait to come back here again! Btw they  are pet friendly which is a plus.

text:
I am actually on their very nice patio as I write this review as I am a fairly new regular. I just had the smoked meatloaf available in the butcher area which is the item I most often order as it is very good. They have daily specials for ready-to-eat food and pound for pound it's probably a better value than you'd get at any take-out and especially a restaurant -- AND it's way better for you. Even the regular prices aren't too bad, ie said meatloaf 6.00 a pd. 
I love the service and atmosphere though there's a little bit of tweaking that can be done here and there. There is one gal with curly jet black hair in the vitamin/personal care area that is quite indifferent towards me even though I'm a serious shopper. And then the butcher shop guys often cut too much of the meat I want for my lunch and then ask if a half a pound is okay even though I wanted a lunch portion of 1/3 pd. If I say no they look put off by having to put the pieces back-- awkward silence then ensues :( . I got the nerve up to mention this to the manager so hopefully they won't be like that again. I'm really low-maintenance for the most part and generally a nice person so I resist taking it personally. 
And lastly, the internet is really good. If I feel like eating in my car I can still pick it up so long as I'm in the closest parking spaces. 
So overall, I highly recommend Whole Foods because you deserve it! :)

text:
I've lived in the goleta area for a few years now and work across the street. I always saw the nugget and wanted to go check it out but just never got around to it until the other afternoon. 

My bf is a goleta local and he had somehow never even heard of it but I convinced him to check it out with me for lunch. I got the Philly cheesesteak with fries and he got the tri tip dip with onion rings. We were going to split the two meals but we wound up liking what we ordered so much we tried a bite of each others and kept our own sandwiches lol

The decor isn't "Santa Barbara" and is a little cheesy, I'd call it wanna be redneck, but it honestly reminded me of places back home and so I felt very comfortable. Good food, good service for the occasion. 

We will definitely be back for dinner!

text:
I have been eating at Zaytoon for years, and have many decent meals there. However, I had an awful experience there today at lunch. I started to get woozy, and a little nauseous, smelling some really strong scent of gasoline or chemicals. When I asked the waiter what the smell was, he informed me that their patio had been sprayed down with some chemicals days before, and it was still giving off this, what smelled to me like, a very not-safe-to-breathe odor, i.e., TOXIC.

My inner anxiety told me the best option was to get the heck out of there as fast as possible. And, BTW, the chicken kabob tasted very rubbery, on top of it. Probably will never go back. The owner needs to step up and do something.

text:
First and foremost this place is so spacious! Perfect for large crowds or to go on a date. Either way it's a good location and the ambiance is on point. The Institution IPA was my favorite for sure but every beer I tried was fantastic. Customer service was over the top!

Now on too my favorite part of the review... the FOOD!! The pizza there are some of the best I've had specifically the Margarita Pizza and Carne Asada pizza! On top of the pizza the pretzels are phenomenal (this is not an exaggeration) they come with an amazing cheese dip.

Overall an easy 5 star rating. Highly recommended!

text: We stopped by during the holidays and they were having an event with Holidays on Haley. I hope this becomes an annual thing as I loved spending some time at this winery. They have a lovely outdoor fire with plenty of seating and extremely inviting on a cold night. For the event we got to taste three of their wines and I loved them all-cab franc, grenache, and I think a syrah. This is a very relaxed and comfortable wine tasting room where you can relax and enjoy wine without feeling rushed. Great experience and we'll be back soon to get a few bottles.

text: We had a very good happy hour/lunch upon arrival at the Santa Barbara Inn and also took advantage of the (limited) continental breakfast the next morning.  The issue we had was the following night.  After spending the day downtown and at the beach and then at the hotel pool/spa, we decided to have dinner at the hotel.  The restaurant advertised a 10PM closing and upon arriving at 9:15 we were informed that the hotel was no longer serving dinner because it had been a slow night.  The host offered to retrieve the manager at which point she also informed us that they had decided to close early.  I did not know that was an option for legitimate restaurants.  Upon my insisting that we were hotel guests in need of a meal, she begrudgingly offered to have the chef make only a choice of pasta dishes for us.  My husband declined that offer as I believe he felt uncomfortable, although I was willing to accept anything.  We instead walked next door to the Hyatt Hotel where we received a warm greeting, had great steak and salmon dinners, good drinks, and we were even offered dessert.  That totally saved the night.

text:
Pros: The view and the food is decent
Cons: The service is bad. It is partly that they are understaffed & partly that no one there really hustles. The bus boys do one task at a time...very slowly. Go inside, get a towel to clean a table, go back & get water to refill. The last two times (pre & post-COVID) we've been there is been the same bad service. We have had to ask for water, water refills, utensils, etc., and sometimes ask again. And, we asked for the grilled fish sandwich, which was on the menu previously and is on the website. While they have grilled fish & lots of burgers, they said they could no longer make the fish sandwich. There are so many great restaurants in SB, we won't be giving this one another chance.

text:
Opening weekend. Line out the door. I decided to wait. When we got in the door frame we noticed the seating area was rather small. The restaurant does not have large tables to cater to larger parties. 

Just like BBQ joints in Texas, it is like a buffet line.. 

I chose the pork ribs and a side of Mac n cheese. I decided to go with the full rack because half rack was like 3 ribs.  My ribs were cold and they were decent. Mac n cheese was... Rather disappointing.  The had a little biscuit with melted butter. That was tasty. 

Le BF went with the pulled pork sandwich. His portion was tiny! And they added a slice of American cheese...? Rather odd. 

I like the big yellow cups. Reusable. 
They had complimentary ice cream!! 
The napkin dispensers are on the wall. 

Food was ok, but it seems like that's really the only other choice this city has. 
 
I was excited for a new bbq place, really I was. I might be back if my friends want to try this place. I'll try their other selections.

text:
Oh yeah, shellfish heaven! 

We cycled over the uneven wooden surface of Stearns Warf pier (bottles of recently purchased white clinking together in the front of my basket) to find this little gem of a restaurant perch at the farthest corner of the pier. 

I wanted to try everything on the menu but my body failed me. I worked hard to try as much as I could though. (Will have to condition my body for the next time I visit). 

I started with the urchin over scallop and served on top of a slice of lime. Drizzled soy sauce over, was delicious. (That is on their specials board.) Went on to eat a crab sandwich which was also very tasty, with huge crispy onion rings. 
A few crab claws later a foodie smile appeared. 
I then helped finish off my wife's Cioppino dish, which was equally divine. Served in a  hollowed out loaf of bread, the juices get absorbed into the bread and it is yum for the tum.

Fresh local produce. 
Our server was so helpful, bright and enthusiastic. 

Tips
It can be windy at the end of the pier and if you sit outside it maybe a good idea to put an extra layer on.
It is possible you will be queuing up to be seated (it is very popular) be patient, it won't take long and the food is so worth it. Maybe call up to find out how busy they are before.
Be prepared they may have run out of certain things. It is in fact a good sign everything is fresh.

Next visit I am going to eat as many Parmesan encrusted garlic clams as possible - the large steamed crabs - the coconut shrimp and maybe squeeze in the lobster roll.

Why do we not have anything like this on the water in Miami?! There are so few water side restaurants anyway. The ones we have are extortionate. Why could we not offer high quality food at a reasonable price on or over the waters edge?

text:
This is a perfect choice when some in your party are vegetarian and others aren't. There's something for everyone!

When I first reviewed Convivo, the chef refused to make substitutions, so for example, the chef refused to allow us to order the summer peach pizza without the jamn serrano. I can happily report that the chef has now come to his/her senses and we were able to order the same pizza without the meat this time! I'll still hold out hope that the next time, they will allow us to have the jamn we paid for on the side, since this time they would leave it out, but wouldn't bring it on the side for the meat lovers to enjoy.

The lemon thyme cocktail was fabulous and I'll definitely order it next time. The service was great... hats off to Antonio (or was it Arturo?). He was friendly, knowledgeable and attentive.

My favorites were the charcoal avocado app, the charcoal prawns app, and the za'atar flatbread app. All wonderful!

Husband enjoyed the guinzaglio, but I thought my dish of ricotta caramelle was extraordinary and will return just to order it again. 

Convivo features a creative and well-executed menu and wonderful views! We ended the night sitting by the fire, enjoying dessert and the last of our drinks. All in all, a wonderful date night and we will definitely be back.

text:
This place was okay... the best part was by far the patio, the view and the mashed potatoes. We waited for a solid 10 minutes before we were greeted by our server. She was a sweet girl but there were some service issues. We got our salad just fine but after waiting about 30 minutes our server came out and told us there was a mix up in the kitchen and our food would be right out (I'm not sure what kind of mix up there could have been since we didn't have any special instructions to our meals). 

Once our food did come out my boyfriends side dish was wrong. Both his chicken and my salmon were over cooked. The server did go out of her way to take my glass of wine and our desert off the check which we appreciated. 

All in all the restaurant itself was not as nice as we had expected. Butter for the rolls comes out in a plastic ramekin, bussers and food runners look sloppy and unprofessional with their chucks, shorts and shirts not tucked in... just not as classy as we had in mind.

Pretty much think of a red lobster-ish vibe with a pretty patio and view.

text:
I agree with Von G... This place is awful. It's a shame, really, as I was excited to finally have a nice pizzeria in Carp. Or so I thought. 

First off, I have to say the ambiance was nice, and the restaurant was clean. I'll give it that.

We ordered hummus as an appetizer, and it was AWFUL... it was still partially frozen, so the bottom was solid and the top was only somewhat spreadable. Honestly, they could have run over to Vons and bought a tub of hummus and it would have been WAY better. The taste was off as well...tasted very funky, kind of fermented and vinegar-y... Gross.

Next, we got a pizza with sausage and mushrooms. I found the crust to be the sole redeeming quality of our meal. The rest of the pizza was soggy and far too greasy... I'm not usually a "dabber", but I found myself needing to pat down the pizza with a napkin in order to stomach it. Overall, we did not enjoy it, and certainly didn't take the leftovers home in a to-go box.

Last, but certainly not least, it was WAY overpriced for such low quality.. I was very disappointed, and will not be back.

text:
Cup cakes are good (that's why I gave 2 starts) but the service there has consistently been bad. Has happened to me over and over. 

My wife always orders cupcakes for birthday parties there and every once in a while I'll go pick them up. Today was the typical situation where service was just bad and the attendants had a horrible attitude. Like they are doing you a favor in serving you. 

The lady at the counter gave me such bad attitude it made me decide not to give this business another cent of my money. Here is how the conversation went:

Me "I'm here to pick up an order"
Attendant "name?"
Me "Peres"
Attendant "No, First name" (with an attitude)
Me "Fernanda"
Attendant puts her hands up like I am robbing the place and says "I'm still working on it" rolls her eyes. Terible attitude. BTW, we were told the order would be ready at 10:00 and this was 10:40.
Me: "Do you have a non-dairy cupcake"
Attendant "we have vegan"
Me: (I'm not vegetarian so I don't know what "vegan" means)  "Is vegan dairy-free?"
Attendant "Yes, that's what vegan means. No animal byproducts" again with an attitude. 

Why are clients treated with disrespect, I don't know. Seems self-destructive to their business if you ask me.

text:
Well, I have never been more disappointed in service, and that says a lot because I eat at many different restaurants, breweries, etc. I have been here before to sit at the bar and eat a quick lunch. A couple of friends and I decided we wanted to have an actual lunch here and eat at a table - worst mistake we could have made. 

It started off with our server, Ashley, being somewhat rude and off in another land I should say. The entirety of our time spent at this spot she was unhelpful and texting over by their computer.  We continuously would ask for things such as a beer sample, beer pint, water, sauces, which would either come about 10 minutes later or not at all. After we received the food it only got worse as the daily soup I had ordered had to be a can from section 2 or maybe 4 at the nearest grocery store. The only food that seemed to be enjoyed was the Western burger and sweet potato fries (which isn't that difficult to mess up in the first place). 

I am just extremely disappointed that the waitress did not care whatsoever about her service. There are many people who need jobs in SB so her spot could easily be filled - great service is a job so treat it like one!

I really dislike writing terrible reviews, but unfortunately this place just didn't cut it in any fashion. I only give it two stars because it's a neat looking place good for watching sports and usually the bartenders are great, just not on the particular day we came to chow down. Maybe come here for a beer and then walk a few feet for some REAL food and REAL service.

text:
While traveling from Pismo beach we searched for good breakfast places in Santa Barbara and Yelp directed us to Scarlett Begonia. 

A must do breakfast here kinda place! 
Everything I had, tasted Amazing! From the perfectly cooked thick sliced bacon, to the sourdough bread, homemade strawberry jelly, farm fresh over easy eggs,  and  potatoes topped with this like I think it was maybe Maille old style grain mustard! I have just one word Memorable! My husband had the steak and eggs which was equally delicious with a chimichurri sauce worth boasting about! 

I have to say I wasn't expecting great tasting food during times of just order pick up due to COVID but when you still have the craving and memories a few days later, it's worth writing about. 
Also  the place looks super cute inside from what I was able to see from the widow but obvious we can't dine in just yet but worth the drive when they are. But most important they are COVID guidelines to the Tee! 
Lastly! As my foodie friends and I would say "Food  so good makes me wanna cry!" Till we meet again!!!!!

text:
I had dinner here last week, and brunch today!  Just happened that way because friends wanted to go there.  I have to say that both meals were, at best, just average!  The dinner I had was overcooked and had been sitting under lights for a long time.  The pork carnitas were dried out and crispy and had no flavor at all.  I only ate half of the dish and did not take the left-overs home; which should tell you a lot!

For brunch, I understand from my friends that the menu is new.  Nothing looked particularly 'yummy', but the waitress recommended the scrambled eggs with meat, served with beans.  The servings were really quite small for the price, and the eggs were overcooked, and there was a red sauce on top that had no flavor at all.  The beans were ok - but that's not saying a lot for a Mexican restaurant!! No garnish.  No fruit.  Nothing else on the plate, so my rating is very poor.

Their drinks are another matter however.  Had a margarita at dinner and it was wonderful. I had a bloody mary for brunch, and it looked great with a stalk of celery and an olive pinned to it with a toothpick.  Unfortunately, two of my companions ordered their drinks 'without spice'!!!  So, although i ordered mine 'extra spicy', it came very mild.  I will put this down to the bartender thinking all of them should be mild, but ti was disappointing, nonetheless.

Overall, the service was nice (not great) and the food average, at best.  Not a place I will rush back to, that's for sure!

text: Toma. Where do I begin. My family and I where in the Santa Barbara area and were in the mood for Italian food. We saw this spot on yelp and saw it had great reviews. So we drove out and entered the restaurant. We were greeted by a server and he directed us to the bar. He said since we were a party of 12 we needed to wait for tables to be ready. We were waiting and the only positive I have  to say is that while waiting the bartender was being extremely kind and helpful. Now for the bad. While waiting, a man who we later found out was the owner, confronted us saying to quiet our children down. They are only three years old and they were making a little noise, yet Tom came by and rudely told my mom to quiet them down. My parents were very disappointed as we waited for hours. I'm only twelve years old but my parents have been taking us out to fine restaurants since we were toddlers, we have eaten at great restaurants, like Wolfgang puck, and received kind service. This place gets zero stars in my book. If you have children do not go here!!!

text:
The atmosphere alone grants this hideaway three stars. Set in the recesses of a small canyon just  below interstate 154 and  the summit of the Santa Ynez's gaze over the city of Santa Barbara, this biker bar doubles as a steakhouse for those brave enough to parallel park there hybrids next to a row of Harley's. 

This boldness pays off though when you realize you're actually entering a REAL tavern, complete with swinging doors, dark wood furnishings, and a hearth, casting spirals of firelight into dark corners. The food is authentic too, with venison and other game meats proliferating the menu. But as real as the food may be, so are the prices ($8 for a hamburger, uh). 

They've also got a healthy selection of beers and wines to choose from, and while it may not be the Hitching Post in terms of varietals to choose from, they do the Santa Barbara wineries justice.

Only 20 minutes off the 101, it's a great lunch stop if you're in the Santa Barbra area or touring the wine country on the other side of the pass.

text: My boyfriend and I had dinner here on Sunday. I would've given them 5 stars however there was a few things I think could be better. First, I ordered a baked potato and the server completely forgot to bring it out. Second, my BF ordered his steak well done and it was brought out medium so we had to send it back for the chef to cook it some more. Lastly, our server didn't come to our table at all once the food was brought out. We sat there with empty glasses waiting for someone to pass so we could ask for a refill. I would like to say that once they did bring out our food it was AMAZING. The sauteed mushrooms were delicious and the steaks were flavorful. I would definitely come back here again and hopefully we'd get a differen't server.

text:
We met another couple here for a lunch (we thought it'd be a more cost effective meal) to celebrate our anniversary and my friend's birthday.

The first thing I noticed is that they're too cool to have adequate signage :) Oh coolness. Will I ever understand? Once I figured out where they are I was again shocked with this whole "really upscale food, pricey menu items, laid back staff and minimal decor." But whatever. I'm obviously not their demographic. 

All of the drinks were DELICIOUS! Our food was all also very good! I had a crab sandwich and it was yummy. We also ordered a half crab or something like that, a seafood soup, and another sandwich. Everyone was very satisfied with their meals.

I'd recommend going here if you want to spend a pretty penny. I'm not cheap, especially when it comes to quality food. I shop at Whole Foods for God's sake. But spending over a hundred for 4 people for lunch seems silly to me. It was a great celebration and I'd probably stop here for upscale drinks and hors d'oeuvres with friends.

text: This place really has it all if you are a beach person or not.  They have a section for your dog to hang w you while you enjoy their fare.  Varied menu and always specials that really are special.  Friend had the burger special and I had the ono fish tacos.  I am an onion ring fan and theirs do the trick.  Everything tasted fresh, made on the spot.  Speaking of spots, there are a ton of options where to sit including and especially looking out at the ocean.  I'd like to go there at night and enjoy how pretty their grounds are.  Perfect kid spot, they have areas for the kids to play, feels safe, perfect date spot, perfect family and friends spot.  Going for years and never disappointed!

text:
If you want a low key pub to have strong drinks, this is the place to go. The front bar and restaurant is very relaxing and much quieter than other bars around here. We had a few drinks, a Grey Goose lemon drop martini was only $10!!! I have never seen any martini that's cost only $10 anywhere in LA! You'd think one of the richest places in America would charge a lot for a cocktail, but they don't, why is that, not that I am complaining, I love it! 

The other side of the restaurant is a bar and lounge, it's actually quite spacious, they have live band performing sometime so I have heard. We had a few drinks there too, then everything became blurry, drinks were too strong! They serve food till 1am, so if you want late night bar food you can come here too!

text:
Hubby and I came here after a movie and got a corner spot on the street patio. The street patio isn't level, so I found I felt like I was sliding a bit with the booth bench, but it wasn't too bad. Hubby got the shawarma rice bowl at Happy Hour price, which was lucky. I got the kofta (lamb) sliders. We also got the cauliflower bites, french fries, and beet salad. Between the kofta sliders and the shawarma rice bowl, hubby definitely won. The rice bowl came with a beautiful salad and the seasoning was lovely. 

The kofta slider patties were small - about 1/3" tall and too small for the bun and not well formed. I wondered if the lamb was off. They were topped with beautiful cukes and picked turnips, but there was way too much tahini. They were a big mess and poorly seasoned. I asked for salt and pepper, which comes in little disposable packets, like at McDonalds (maybe this is due to COVID - they don't want to put salt/pepp shakers on street?).

The warm beet salad and french fries were fantastic, but no seasoning. The cauliflower was okay. I ordered a manhattan, which was great and they used a homemade walnut bitters in it. Yum!

Highlights were the shawarma rice bowl, the beet salad, the french fries, the Manhattan and the excellent service. Both the bartender and waitress were lovely and helpful.

I've heard so many great things about Foxtail and I would definitely come back for live music and a drink and fries. However, overall, I wasn't that impressed by the food and certainly not by all the plastic containers for sauces and condiments and the packets for salt and pepper. I definitely would choose Zaytoon the next time for dinner.

text:
I've been to Los Arroyos many times, although I've never managed to order anything other than the Burrito Mojado.

I also just ordered a large takeout order (graduation party with 25 people), and I am very happy with the experience.  The food was ready on time and my guests were happy with the food.  The manager was helpful on the phone (she asked if we were going to eat right away so they knew whether to put the cheese and lettuce on the food or on the side).  The only downsides were that I had to call a few times in order to catch the manager when she was there, and the beef tacos were labelled as chicken tacos, which caused a little confusion.  However, I would definitely order party food from Los Arroyos again.

text:
Discovered the Santa Barbara Shellfish company by accident. I saw that the wait was abnormally long, even for a Saturday night. Visually, it's a dive and very casual restaurant. Decided to go for Sunday late lunch after 1:30 p.m. on Sunday instead.
There are no real tables unless you sit outside, you sit on a counter where they do most of the cooking or a ledge by the window. Outside has patio seating.

 My boyfriend and I started with the oyster shooters and the fried scallop and fried oyster plate. Loved both. They use Japanese Panko crumbs instead of batter which is a big plus. Then we decided to splurge and share the Full size lobster! Absolutely delish! Grilled Lobster to be exact... succulent and cooked to perfection and worth every penny! ($39). It's served with a large cup of bisque (lobster or chowder), we had the scrumptious lobster bisque, and also served with a creamy pineapple coleslaw and a few onion rings. 

I had a great experience with the service. I guess we just got lucky. The place gets pretty hectic and people get impatient so they tend to be rude, which then makes the staff defensive. Can't blame them. Always be nice to restaurant staff and they'll be nice to you! Simple...

Long story short... the food is great. Great portions. A little pricey, but hey... it's friggen beautiful Santa Barbara, it's expected. Worth it.... BUT, still cheaper than Moby Dick Sea Food which is next door... horrible, no flavor, over cooked food and more expensive!!! I digress.....

Only gave 4 stars because the place is a bit visually dirty inside and out. They definitely need to "clean" the place up a bit. I like rustic charm and all but not splattered lobster and crab juice on walls and windows. Also, Can barely see out of the windows because they're so dirty, which was a shame since I was facing the ocean and it would have been a glorious view. 

Anyway.... please give this place a try! Food is great. But be patient, you will have to wait. Bring a snack if need be. Sorry, no photos...my hands were full of lobster and butter. :)

text: What a find! Big fan of crispy tacos and they might have the best in town. Was blown away with the quality and size of them. This might be my go to Taco Tuesday place from now on (sorry Los Arroyos).  Super friendly service which is actually what drew me in... One of the owners (I believe it was the husband) was walking in front of me as I was going to Hana Kitchen next door. Apparently he came across an old colleague or someone he knew and offered them a free lunch/burrito which I think was a very nice gesture given the hardships these restaurants have endured. I decided to give them some business and honestly can't wait to go back. They've got great food, friendly service, and hopefully once things open back up they'll be churning out lots of tacos!

text:
And then there was Edomasa.  As in, much, much better than Arigato.  You might stumble across it, tucked aside an unknown area that, *gasp*, you actually have to drive to.  It's worth it.

The outside portends to be this cheesy strip-mall sushi joint. But the inside, and the food, is spot-on.  Very authentic.  A long sushi bar, Japanese traditional, with seasoned sushi chefs. 

Well worth the trip.

We also purchased some soda, black licorice (of course) Black Cherry, Root Beer Float & Green River  (Lime) Very unique store but keep in mind you'll be lugging around a bunch of heavy sodas all day if y ou shop here early. 

Lots of nostalgic candy all the stuff from when I was a kid that you can't find anymore except in specialty stores like this.  So glad they still exisit. It was like bike ride on my schwin with the flowered banana seat, sissy bar and ape hanger handle bars.  Staff really friendly and helpful.

text:
We've been wanting to try Barbareo for years given its reputation. We heard from people that it's amazing, just ok, and not worth it. 

I think the OKAY is where I fall. The dishes highlight solid combinations of simple ingredients. The menu provides a ton of opportunity to be adventurous with this combos. And the entrees really execute for the chef. The BBQ or anything they smoke is their specialty: the tri tip was to die for.

I was a little surprised by the service. Our waiter was lovely, but we had to pour our own bottle of wine we purchased from the restaurant. It took a while to get served in the first place. And restaurant is a lot more rustic/trendy/hipster than nice/date night service. Not inherently bad, just not what I expected.

Would recommend to those interested in an adventurous, locally-sourced meal!

text:
This was my second visit to the Bella Vista (after a really nice first visit). Overall, a nice space but not nearly as nice if you can't sit outside due to the cold. We ordered pickled vegetables to start, and then for mains we ordered the scallops, branzino, vegan lasagna and fish of the day (salmon on risotto). Really appreciated that they have several very strong vegan options for my husband. Most of the table enjoyed their food, but I'm giving 3 stars because the salmon fish of the day was just not a good dish at all-- it was bland and worse of all, the salmon was so dry and tough. I mentioned it to the waitress who offered to have the kitchen re-do it-- I declined because I try hard not to waste food but it was not a good dish at all. I'm surprised the restaurant didn't comp it in some way.

I'm also disappointed because I told them in the reservations that we were there to celebrate two people getting new jobs. I would expect Four Seasons level service to include some sort of congratulations written on their desserts or something (when we came before, it was for a birthday and they did offer a lovely free dessert with candles). It sort of felt like the staff was phoning it in today. I expect more from the Four Seasons.

text:
Casa Blanca has great ambiance with the Spanish inspired decor and tiles. It's a great people watching restaurant in Santa Barbara. Sit outside on the patio and sip on your margarita. 
I highly recommend getting a drink from bartender Dominick. He's a cool cat with a great palate when it comes to making margaritas. 
As for the food, I would skip it. The food is okay, if you're looking for tasty and take you to moon Mexican food this is not where you want to go. The food is a bland and it isn't really remarkable let alone memorable. Even the salsa needs some work. The chips are decent if it's cooked right. So that can be a hit or miss. 
However, they have a great happy hour everyday from 3pm - close. So, overall I gave it a 3 star cause of the ambiance and the drinks.

text:
Nice little hole in the wall. The burgers are made with flatbread rather than the usual buns. I liked it. The OMG burger and the plain cheeseburger were both good. Each burger comes with 2 patties in it. The burgers come with seasoned fries and small side salad. The salad is just fancy lettuce mix. No dressing. They have 4 bottles of condiments. Thousand island, ketchup, garlic aioli (fancy ranch), and spicy (siracha mayo). You can use one of those for your salad. The burgers are good but the star is definitely the seasoned fries.  I wished they gave more with each meal.... you can order a bucket separately.

Didn't try the flatbread or pizzas yet. Will be back to try. The price is decent too.

text:
The fish n chips - fish tasted fresh and the coating was crispy.

But here's where they lost me: 

Not traditional tarter sauce. Way too mayonnaise-ey. Not enough pickle. 

Watered down malt vinegar. Or very old. 

The tables are so sticky, that I found 2 long black hairs stuck to the table top. The staff should have caught that when they wiped it off, not the customer ( some things are hard to get over and hair is just gross - I don't even like to find mine in the sink)

So, not an authentic British fry up, but could make a few changes and get some better reviews.

Cheers!

text: My 2nd visit to Lure in Santa Barbra area. 1st visit was fantastic!  Food, service and prices. This was less than a year ago. Ordered same dish. Was just okay. The Nee England clam chowder that I raved about being the best since I left east coast; wellllll ...... .  It was just as busy as 1st time. Had to ask for hot sauce 3 x. Finally one of the greeters got it for me. Two spoonfuls into my soup and here comes my entree. The server saw the shocked look on my face and asked if she could bring back. I said please. My initial waitress came to check on me and told me to let her know when I was ready for my main course. No sooner than she walked away, another server comes running to my table with my entree. At this point I just said set it there to which he promptly did and ran off. My nice rock fish was a bit dry and overdone. I ate half and requested to bring rest with me. Doubt I'll be back on my next trip to SB. Prices have greatly increased.

text:
I graduated a few years ago from UCSB and come back into town fairly frequently to get my Freebirds fix.  The nachos are perfection and all other nachos that I eat get compared (and never really live up.)  

There are a few things that make these nachos better than all others.  First, the rice.  Most places don't think to put rice on nachos (and yes, it is a slight carb-overload, but so worth it.)  The rice melts into the cheese and really adds something.  The additional toppings are all great quality, romaine lettuce, fresh pico de gallo, newly pickled jalapenos, and great guacamole.  And the icing on the cake are the dried onions.  I've never seen them anywhere else and they're little bits of flavor explosions.  

I just had these nachos yesterday and I'm already salivating over eating them again.

text: Yummm! We go to the location on Milpas. I like Mexican food that's tasty but not too spicy, and my husband likes more kick. There are options for us both. They do a really good business there, but no matter how busy, the staff have always been friendly, and we've never been unable to find a seat or had to wait long for our food. I also love that I can get a side of really good grilled nopales (cactus leaf) there. If you've not had it before, the inside can be an acquired texture (a bit slimy, like okra), but it's so flavorful and Los Agaves prepares them just right, adding a chargrilled touch. Definitely recommend... friendly staff, casual dining, quality ingredients, tasty authentic fare.

We had a few other things that were decent but those were my favorite. The did have a Uni Special that we didn't enjoy to much. We also had a dish I can't remover the name. It had chicken breast and sausage in a rice. We all felt the Chicken was over cooked and dry otherwise it would have been a good dish.

text:
E X C E L L E N T 
Customer Service 
This was my first time making my way to Panino
Twas lunch time and 
Pesto was on my mind..
My friend recommended their pesto sandwich 
With extra pesto

I asked some people in the office I frequent 
About Panino
They all said it's like a gourmet Sandwich place
What they said
Seemed to be in line with what my friend said

While at Panino
They weren't busy
Her name was Holland ( like the country she told me)
The employee I encountered 
I told her this was my first time here
What could she recommend
I made no mention of me being told to order
The pesto sandwich 
Holland was all smiles, and treated me like 
She clocked in with a great cup of coffee 
When I asked if this place has good food
Holland said
"That's the reason why I work here"

She gave me a rundown of the menu
And told me I should start out with the pesto sandwich 
I told her that's what I came for
She stopped what she was doing and said 
"No way!"
The two of us were on the same page
She next told me to choose my bread
Focaccia was a no brainer 
Also "Holland" recommended 

Taste:
Loved the sparkle of pine nuts
Here and there
The darkness of the sun dried tomatoes 
Pesto flavor that sunk my body into
A garden of fresh flavor
This was perfect for my afternoon 
Now panino isnt a restaurant with waitresses 
Somehow, 
Holland still found time to ask me my thoughts 
"I told her, my thoughts are good enough to bring me back

Now, there is one thing 
That would have sent my rating off the charts
The ability to have the sandwich toasted..
They don't have this as an option 
But, what they did present to me
Was good enough to forget about a toaster option 

I recommend this place for your deli needs

text:
Simply the best place for coffee, pastries, and conversation in all of Santa Barbara!!  Locally owned by the lovely couple Julia & Todd.  How nice that a home-grown cafe can succeed in this town of chain stores... Done on their exceptional knowlege of coffee, espresso, and barista-ing!!  This is the real deal -- they know their stuff.  They did so good on State Street that they opened a second AMAZING cafe one block off State, at Anacapa & Cota, with parking and a LARGE outdoor patio.  Come visit them soon -- A MUST!!!

P.S. Free WiFi too!!  If you whine about needing an electrical outlet, charge your damn iPad before coming here, DUH!!

text:
Came in the past & had the short ribs i believe. Was pretty satisfied with them. Husband was less impressed than I. The clam chowder was pretty good but I still suggest the seafood spot around the corner for the best. 
Came again & had the garlic baked clams- BEWARE they come on the half shell & menu does not specify. I was expecting strips of fried/baked clams as they are typically served and as one would expect from the description but I was wrong. They were not tasty, sent them back. (I dont mind seafood on the halfshell but they werent good).
Ordered the fried chicken sandwich instead. Was decent. 

Waitress was super awesome today & service in general has been great each time Ive come.

The patio seating is awesome too so I'll keep coming. 3.5stars

text:
We had a perfect lunch here. Polenta fries, hummus, tacos, tea. Everything was so flavorful yet light and nutritious. Customer service was top notch-- since it was our first time visiting, they offered us samples of their beet/orange/lemon/turmeric juice as well as a dessert on the house. 

The dessert was the star of the meal: a coconut/cashew whipped cream that was probably my favorite thing we had. It was dense yet light and tasted really fresh. The raw cheesecake was tasty too with a honey/turmeric sauce. 

I wish we lived closer to Santa Barbara--I'd be here all the time!

text:
Stopped in last night for a late bite and a beverage.  We were greeted promptly and offered a table in either the upper or lower area.  The staff was very friendly and prompt.  The menu is surprisingly varied and we went with the filet and salmon.

So often salmon isn't cooked correctly, and filet can be a miss.  Not here!  They nailed both entrees in flavor, preparation and presentation.  The entrees were well sized and satisfying.  We ordered the fries as an appetizer.  

Absolutely yum!  Will be back soon...

text:
This review concerns the bakery. 

Even following them from their move to this location our family has been buying bread and pastry from Our Daily Bread for many years. 

Not any more!  

Over the past few weeks, the quality of their products has declined dramatically.  The cases are clearly filled with at least day-old products - choose carefully and look for volume so you can be assured that the breads/pastries were baked recently.  We have found that there are only a few types of bread/pastries in any quantity on the shelves - and if there are only a few left, they are clearly older than a day or two.   Their bread stales quickly so beware.  Shouldn't bakeries clearly label and at least discount day+ old products?

Last week we purchased a few croissant, pastries, breads for a party. The croissants were deformed, oily (where's the butter?), dense, tough and heavy - the baker clearly has no concept of what a real one even looks like, let alone tastes.   Ditto the pastries - Costco does it better!  After a bite or two, we tossed all of them. 

The counter staff is still hard working and charming, but we will be taking our business elsewhere.   

Stand warned.

text:
We were in town for a night of quality civilization before heading into the hills for some hiking and camping. A quick yelp search for seafood told me that Teddy's was our destination. Yelp was completely correct!

We walked to the place and we were feeling really lucky because they sat us immediately in their cozy outdoor, socially distanced seating. They were masked, gloved, and there was plenty of hand sanitizer at the ready. BTW, this was my first time back in a restaurant since this whole Trump catastroph*k shut California down in early March. And what a great return it was!

I started with the margarita flight. My dude got some cocktail he thoroughly enjoyed. And yeah, I got a second round of margarita flight because I wasn't driving - and who are you to judge me? LOL. Yumz.

We agonized over what to order because everything sounded so great. We started w/ the bacon-wrapped dates (aka, "devils on horseback") and the ahi poke nachos. The dates were divine but the nachos were only okay. We picked out all the tuna but the 3 of us agreed that the wasabi cream sauce was pretty much just mayo/crema. It overwhelmed the dish and didn't taste much like wasabi at all. And the crispy fried shallots competed w/ the fried wontons to make the dish too heavy for our tastes. There's room for improvement there.

My main was the seared ahi on coconut rice. Again, although we loved both the ahi and the coconut rice, they didn't pair well together. I would have preferred the cold ahi served w/ a cold side. The "Asian vegetables" were tasty but again, the curry sauce was a hard, "whaah?"

My man got the chorizo shrimp over cheddar grits and he thoroughly enjoyed them.

My daughter got the steamed clams and they were great. There was a minor conflict about just how much of her bread we got to dunk into her broth. I had to reassure her that we could always ask for more bread. 

We finished up w/ the flourless cake (which was very chocolate decadence-esque) and the keylime pie in-a-jar. My husband shamelessly gobbled his decadence down but me and my kid strategically (i.e., we were full) took part of our desserts back to the hotel and had dessert-for-breakfast the next day.

The wait staff were as good as they get. Knowledgable about the menu, eagle-eyed for our needs, very genial, and health-conscious. 

This was our first time in Carpenteria and we really enjoyed our time here. And despite my husband's scorn when I pronounced it "carpent-EER-ee-AH," like "cafeteria," we definitely look forward to being back and getting back to Teddy's By the Sea.

text:
As the legendary Elmer Dills once stated, BBQ is like sex and religion - everyone has an opinion on what's good... 

I like it sweet, tangy, and I want to taste the smoke when I bite into the ribs.   

I've eaten as some outstanding BBQ places in my travel.  This isn't one of them, but it is VERY respectable.  Pork ribs are a 4, the duck is a 4, and the chicken is a 3 .  I can't speak for the rest of the menu.  

I wouldn't go out of my way to go here, but I always know that I can get a satisfying meal in a casual funky atmosphere.  Very reliable and consistent and the best I've had in the area.

text:
When I was a UCSB student in the early 2000s I used to come here frequently to buy Middle Eastern food. Now the year is 2020 and I'm back in the SB area for a few months and I was overjoyed to find that European Deli Market is still in business! 

For those who are looking to buy Middle Eastern food to cook at home, they have almost all the essentials. This is what I have bought so far:

Freekeh
Moghrabiye 
Couscous
Pomegranate molasses 
Labne 
Stuffed grape leaves (fresh) and cabbage leaves
Zaytoun
Halloum
Ashqawan cheese 
Pita bread (the Lebanese kind)
Tabbouli 
Fresh baba ghannuj from the deli 
Spices such as Aleppo pepper, sumac, dried mint
Pickled radishes
Falafel
Lebanese beers

They also sell products from other Mediterranean countries and Eastern Europe.

text: Ah, Sama Sama. It's a crime that you're not at five stars overall. To call the menu inventive is a gross understatement. Fusing Indonedian with Mexican is risky and I'm sure hard as heck, but they pull it off flawlessly. The Mie Goreng was as good as any I've had, and I'm including Indonesia! Then the lemongrass chicken tacos arrived and I knew the ish got real! The pepes Ikan fish tamale with coconut rice was the revelation, though. Each individually were delicious, but together they were transcendent. Each ingredient in the dishes were deeply thought out to interact with each other exponentially. By the time the grilled broccolini arrived, we were combining everything to see how it blended. It was like a pile of delicious foodie Legos that created awesome new toys. Needless to say, I recommend.

When questioned, she claimed she told us. She had not. Then she proceeds to say "oops we ran out so we gave it to you instead." If you don't have an item, please offer or tell me the alternative, I would have chosen something else--a garden salad didn't really satisfy my craving for "Mexican food." Would not come back.

text: This place is such a hidden gem!! We were lucky enough to find ourself there when the owner was present. She was super kind, gave us background on the company and their little family business, and gave us a sample of wine with the Yelp check in. She even let me go behind the counter for a second to pet their absolutely adorable puppy dog. My family was in town so we all did the flight sampler of the wines. My dad is a huge wino, and there was a special wine that was for members only. Lucky for him - a bottle happened to be opened for tasting from a member that had come before him, and the owner offered to let him taste it! She said it rarely happened, but since it was opened and he was there, he could have a glass. We all loved every wine we tried, but he raved about that glass for the rest of the afternoon haha. We drove up to visit Santa Barbara from the Inland Empire... and this place did not disappoint! I have a feeling we will definitely be going back :)

text:
Bouchon is good, but I wish that I could have marked 4 1/2 stars instead of 5.   I made reservations at Bouchon based on these Yelp reviews, and for the most part, my experience was similar.  That said, I felt that the portions were very slightly under-sized, even for a nouvelle cuisine plate.  Of course, I'm a bit of a pig, and the 3 others at the table didn't complain. 

The Roasted Wild Mushrooms appetizer was very meaty and tasty. They were not over-oiled or over-salted so the subtle flavors of mushrooms could come forth. The House-smoked Local Albacore Carpaccio melts in your mouth and has just enough zest to compliment the fish. As a note, Carpaccio was ordered by a friend who is an L.A. westside sushi snob, and he loved it. He never loves anything. His way-too-good-for-him girlfriend ordered Chilled Santa Barbara Red Rock Crab and that was ridiculous. Delicious, that is.  I had Tom Shepard's Mixed Organic Greens. The salad was not over-dressed, the leafy greens were tender, and the colors were vibrant, even in their dimly lit arena. No random stem chunks here.  It was evident that Bouchon simply spent time sourcing great ingredients and preparing them in a way that lets them sing their own culinary song.  Smart.  This always allows chefs to take credit for what nature provides. 

Up to this point, our service had been great. A few tiny glitches here and there, such as not having cranberry juice or lemonade for our non-alcohol drinking friend.  A Coke was ordered by this person (who orders Coke at a place like this?) and he complained that it was a bit low on the syrup ratio, and high on the carbonation.  I tasted it and unfortunately, he was right. I kind of expected it to be extra rich in flavor.  But, this didn't dampen his mood for the main course. My glass of '04 Three Saints Pinot Noir, Santa Maria, as a matter of fact, helped. For main dishes, our table had 2 orders of Skin-on Local White Sea Bass, a Pomegranate-Marinated Char-grilled Rack of Lamb, and Pan-Roasted Chicken. The Bass was fantastic, but the root of my 1/2 star reduction. O.K. Maybe only a 1/4 star.  That is, the portion was smaller-than-average for California Cuisine.  Maybe the local sea bass is smaller and perhaps I'm jaded by the no-longer-endangered gargantuan Chilean Sea Bass. But the crispy skin and the slightly flaky, but moist meat was perfectly balanced.  The Complainer had the Rack of Lamb and he raved.  Unusual. I was wondering if he was O.K. and not delirious from the sun.  But the real focus of the evening came when my wife, a 20 year vegetarian, came out of her veggie closet and ordered the chicken. She had eaten tons of meat as a kid (all Koreans are raised on meat), then much to her parents demise, turned veggie in her last year of high school.  We mentioned this to our waiter and jokingly asked him to let the chef know that this has to be the chicken of all finger licking good chickens. One that will turn a vegetarian into an omnivore. Well, at least for one meal.  And, bravo!  Chef Josh Brown delivered. Poor Jane. We all dug into her chicken medallions with anticipation, leaving her with less than what had arrived, but we unanimously rolled our eyes in enjoyment. Frankly, the chicken is always the least exciting item on a nouvelle menu, but the chicken here should be featured. The flavor didn't come from the salt or heavy herbs. Everything was subtle and you are reminded of what perfectly cooked chicken is supposed to taste like, along with its texture. 

I have to give credit to Bouchon. The burning reviews for higher end restaurants hold hotter candles than for mainstream eateries.  In that light, it's amazing to have gained so many good reviews. Cheers to Bouchon!

text:
State & Fig is a great place for lunch, tucked in a small walkway of different shops/restaurants. I came for a late lunch on a Monday around 3pm and pretty much had the whole place to myself. I had a portebello mushroom panini and couple bites of the fig burger. 

The portebello mushroom panini included a generous amount of red bell peppers. The bread had a touch of pesto sauce and it all melted nicely together with provolone cheese. This also came with a side of arugula salad. I loved how they put the vinaigrette dressing on the side.

I had a few bites of the burger and it was just ok. I did enjoy the fries that came with, lightly crunchy and not overly salty. 

Service was ok, can't complain, prices were fair. I'd come back to State & Fig in the future.

text:
Alright, so, another yelp find.. When we were up in Santa B. we were hungry and tired from walking and bikeing up awesome hills all day long. We wanted some italian food, some nice  quality carb overload time. 

This place is in a shopping mall (litteraly) it's an outside mall  and this place is tucked away in it... This should have been the first sign. 

The service was horrid, H-O-R-R-I-D the waitress was MIA, always, there were not even that many people either, it was later on a sunday night... 

The food was eh, edible? kinda. The pizza, was a dough ball with chef boyarde sauce, the pasta was a little soupy, how do you mess up penne with olive oil spinach and tomatoes? It was edible like I said, but the service was so horrendous, I think it is a for sure pass next time. Thank you and good night...

text:
Stopped by here after a trip to Santa Barbara since a good friend recommended it. I got the Super Deluxe Melt with pesto and it was delicious! My sister got the Super Emma but agreed mine was better. 
Took one star off since the place was packed with college kids (it is by the UC though so understandable) and the spot is not big at all. It was hard to get your food too since it was so packed! They def should get a speaker for outside so we could at least hear the numbers outside since there's no room to wait indoors. We kept having to go in and out to check if they said our order. 
Very satisfying bagel melt though! Half was filling enough so you could honestly share with someone if you usually get full fast or you could save the other half for later like what we did and it was still good!

text: Came in with the family for a Sunday brunch. Food was good, can't complain. We did have to wait 13-15 minutes for a waitress to finally come by to ask if we want anything to drink. After taking our order she brought us cold coffee and water with ice when we specifically asked not put ice in the water. 10 more minutes and she took our order finally. Place was not packed at all, there was entire section of empty tables and 3 tables right around us were empty as well, so there was no reason to say that the waitress was swamped with tables. We had lobster bisque and fried seafood platter. Both were good, not exceptional. We did like re puff pastry on top of the lobster bisque. It was a nice touch. We probably won't come back here since there are plenty of restaurants with great service just down the street.

text:
Came here during a trip to SB that I had planned to celebrate the boyfriend's birthday.

This spot is located on the pier. We had a little difficulty navigating to it because there weren't any signs directing us to this place. It's located on the second floor of one of the buildings to the right. Google Maps had pointed us to another building further down the pier.

I'm not a huge wine buff, since I just recently started to enjoy wine, so I can't really speak to the wines. But we checked in on Yelp to get the yelp deal - I think it was a free tasting of the chardonnay, and also opted for one of their tasting menus. It was $20 for the both of us and 5 wines.

It's a cute little place and the view is amazing. It was a little cold when we went but not too bad considering it was January and we were wine tasting right on the ocean. Great place to sip some wine and enjoy the view! I just wish there was more seating. All the seats were taken in the outdoor area, and there wasn't really any seating indoors.

Very good value and a nice atmosphere, but all things considered I'd rather go to Persona.

text:
Stopped in about 5:00 pm on Saturday and was sitting at a table within 5 minutes with my daughter on the front patio. They had us spaced out well to adhere to social distancing and have even opened up an extended seating area in the large parking lot. Plenty of umbrellas for shade with these longer and warmer sunny days!

The masked staff were friendly and attentive and the service was prompt.  It was fun being able to be safely downtown in the hustle and bustle of Cabrillo Boulevard on a Saturday and enjoyed the ocean view from our seats!

I ordered the Blackberry Mojito, which was delicious, and would have had a second one if I didn't have to drive. I appreciated the compostable straws they offered too. 

The Fish Tacos were yummy. Definitely large enough for a full meal, a little messy if you have small hands.  Would have liked to have seen more butter and seasoning on the corn on the side and it needed to be warmer, but the tacos stole the show anyway. 

The Fishouse Burger presentation was beautiful and dramatic. Definitely made a you want to sink your teeth into the stack.  It was flavorful and juicy, and a perfectly cooked temperature. The French fries that came with it were cooked to perfection and had great seasoning. 

I was pleasantly surprised by tonight's meal. It's easy to assume it's just another mediocre tourist trap given its location, but it wasn't at all. We are looking forward to our next meal and can't wait to try more items on the menu and snag another Mojito! Make sure to bring a jacket for when the sun goes down, the patio can get a little chilly!

text:
My best friend used to work at SB Outfitters and I met him here for lunch a couple of times and I totally dig this place. I've had the burritos and tacos and I have not been disappointed with any of those dishes. What I enjoy about this place is the great flavors from the food without the greasy, heavy feeling after the meal. The food tastes fresh and comes out of the kitchen quickly.

Los Arroyos reminds me of Chipotle but with a more extensive menu. The prices are very fair and the efficiency of how they operate makes this place a great option for people on a short lunch. I dig this location too because is far enough up State Street that it's not too overly crowded but close enough to the action of downtown.

So if you're looking for good quality, good tasting Mexican food for a decent price Los Arroyos is a great choice. If you happen to over eat and the weather is nice, you can walk it off window shopping on State Street.

text:
The most flavorful and tender venison I've ever eaten!  Ask for the Cabernet Sauvignon that they pair with the venison.  You will not be disappointed.  The venison was built with a bread based stuffing that absorbed the juices from the venison.  It all went together very well.

The pan seared foie gras was creamy and full of the rich flavor that one expects when enjoying this delicacy.  It is served with a delightful fried cornmeal paddy that soaks up the juices from the foie gras.  Delicious.

A special of the day was escargot.  These gastropods were  flavored with butter, garlic and parsley.  Simple and flavorful.

Sofie enjoyed the Sea Bass.  It was very nicely cooked and tasted fresh.

The cutlery at Bouchon is Laguiole by flyingcolors.  I enjoy nice things.  As the proper frame for a work of art, the plates, cutlery and wine glasses added to the enjoyment of our meal.

I asked our server which individual was the chef when I looked into the kitchen area.  (The kitchen is visible from the dining room.)  

"Chef is on vacation this week.", he said.  
"Well, the guys back there are making great food!", I said.  "What do you need the chef for?"  

He smiled.  

A well run restaurant is one that makes quality food when Chef is not around.  When I was in school, I was a dishwasher in a Chinese restaurant in Fresno.  The manager lamented, "I got to be around here all the time!  Otherwise these clowns will burn the food."    Bouchon is well managed.  (I moved on from my very successful job of dishwasher to find a position that matched my level of incompetence.  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_principle )

This restaurant is located just off of State Street.  Walking West on State Street one finds a tasteful assortment of shops, restaurants and bars.  Should you be looking for an outstanding meal and a tour of State Street, Bouchon is a great choice!

text: My husband and I decided to try arigato based on his sis and bro-in-laws' raves.  The place is pretty popular. So don't be surprised If there is a long wait. But the good thing is, they ask for your cell number so you can walk around State st while you wait.  The rolls were small, but very tasty...with the exception of the yellow submarine roll (tiger shrimp).  The seared toro was buttery and had just a little kick. The stAnding room only app (imagine a dynamite roll with avacado replacing the mayo....yum!) was amazing! And the oyster shooter with quail egg (Hot Shot) was very Delish.  My only regret was not eating any raw dishes... We didn't realize it until we left...oh well, next time.   OH, and sit at the sushi bar.  We had an awesome sushi chef, Bryan. He was very quick, personable, and never left us waiting too long for our dishes. Overall a nice dining experience.

text:
Two Words: Stale Bread 

I have been here three times, every time I get stale bread. I remember one time,  I got the clam chowder and I ate all the chowder. The bowl was inedible and still pretty hard like a rock. I probably could have used it as a paperweight.

The quality is mediocre,  and the ingredients aren't fresh. I know that there is a Campus Special deal, but I recommend heading somewhere elsewhere to eat. They have lovely decor, but they are not clean. They do not wipe or clear their tables. It makes me wonder if they even clean their kitchen. 

As for service, I feel like they do not want my business, I get bad vibes there. Okay, I will just eat somewhere else then.

text: We've been looking for a good pizza place for a year since I moved here from the East Coast. We've tried a bunch of different places with no luck, but we were hopeful with this place from pictures we saw randomly on instagram. Finally we found a good pizza place! We had the margherita and the one with truffles, fontina, and thyme. Both were delicious, wood fired and fresh mozzarella! Aside from the pizza, the interior is cute and the people are very friendly, great service, oh yeah complimentary sparkling water yum.

text:
I find myself coming here again and again. Although it's a bit pricier than I normally like to spend on a normal evening, Sama Sama does an excellent job of persuading you to stay and enjoy a long luxurious dinner with delicious drinks.
The exquisite and creative cocktails are my favorite part about this place. Casey is an outstanding bartender with a friendly (but never nosy) demeanor.

The ambience is intimate, the service is kind, and the ingredients are fresh. What more can you want?
