text: I've come to have a bit of a love/hate relationship with Rudy's for several reasons. First off not all the Rudys locations in town are the same. Both the service and food can vary quite a bit and at worst is just a bad value. Secondly, I've come to realize that the reason my wife and I come here is really only because they make a decent indulgent burrito. I say indulgent because quality is not what they or their patrons are after. They use average quality meat, decent rice and beans and packaged tortillas but it all makes for a 'just-fat-and-flavorful-enough-to-feel-extra-satisfied' sort of visit. Often the amount of grease we get is surprising but even that varies as well. Recently we ordered some burritos and a crunchy taco for my daughter with no cheese (she's allergic to dairy). I verified that the receipt noted the 'no cheese' request and we waited. Out came the food and not only was the taco bursting with shredded lettuce but with cheese as well. We complained and got another taco. We soon realized that they had actually just taken the taco and haphazardly scraped the inside and re-stuffed it without cheese. We checked it and sure enough it was still lined with cheese inside. We were worried about our daughters allergy and they seemed to think we were some vain a-holes who were worried about the extra fat (although even the cheese is packaged garbage). Finally we complained again and the young kid at the counter had no idea how to handle it so an older woman intervened, apologized sincerely and refunded our money. The more I thought about it, the more I realized that we'd actually seen the 'stuff it with lettuce' trick on other dishes as well including one where tacos are laid around  a bed of lettuce to make the dish appear more plentiful. I've realized that while the place does a decent job with most things here, they really have nothing to offer in terms of quality and their attitude leaves nearly everything to be desired. They really have no interest in long term patronage. No interest in accommodating you. It's great for an indulgent burrito, but there are businesses I prefer to give my money to and ever since the last time I spend almost $20 for 2 burritos and a soda, I think my visits here will become less and less frequent.

text: My best friend and I were walking around S.B. and we got hungry, so we started reading menus on State St. Cadiz caught our attention because their menu was placed on a nicely lit table next to the host, and we appreciated the light! Italian and Spanish menu, and everything sounded appealing so we asked for a table and were seated immediately. The restaurant has a Mediterranean ambiance that is really pleasant. I had the Paella, which was nicely presented and very satisfying. My friend had the Fettuccini pomodoro, which she said was good quality, and tasted fresh. Our server, Justin, was a very nice young man who attended to our every whim, just as we girls like! Thanks for a great experience!

Please get some better sound equipment I really want to love this place

text:
This restaurant seemed so full of 70s kitsch and promise that I was eager to try it. The bar looked more lively than the dining room so we settled in there. The cocktail waitress, unfortunately, was not on her game. 

There was a party of about 15 celebrating a birthday in the bar which means we were forgotten. It seemed the cocktail gal was a bit Too Laid Back. I watched her bring them one drink at a time.  It took forever to get her attention and put in a dinner order even though the place is tiny.

Hub loved his strong Mai Tai. Salad bar was small but everything in it was fresh. The entrees came but we didn't receive a set up (silverware). I had to steal that from a table in the dining room because said cocktail gal was enjoying social time. I asked for salt but, after watching her plod her single servings around, I stole that from the dining room, too. I had to get up and get my own glass of water from the bar. 

If entrees are $30, you'd better get it right. Hub's medium rare filet was raw. He tried to eat around the edges because he was so hungry. I had a bite and was shocked at its blandness. Season Your Steaks! My salmon was decent, however. 

Chuck's seemed to have the right vibe but the service and the food ruined it for us. Thank goodness there are other local steak houses that hit the mark.

text: This is great Indian cousin in Santa Barbara. It's located on state street right by all the shopping. This was my second time here and I was just as pleased as the first. It was me, my brother, and my boy and we ordered some vegetable samosas to start, garlic naan, butter chicken, lamb vindaloo, and one of their specials with chicken and coconut. Everything was delicious. I can't really say much more. For dessert we ordered milk balls in sweet cardamon water. I don't remember the name because it was in hindu but they were little doughnut holes soaked in sugar water and served warm. Quite tasty!

text:
Excellent date spot for delicious food and flawless service in a beautiful setting.

Waited just a few minutes for brunch at a beautiful table outside on a Saturday afternoon. The service was stellar. Our waitress recommended the dirty fries, shrimp and grits, and a few other things. I took her advice on the dirty fries and the shrimp and grits, and loved them both. I stole a piece of bacon from my date's plate, and it was some of the best bacon we've both ever had. The house-made ketchup was unbelievable. Everything was nearly perfect.

The only minor thing I'd have to say is that my grits were underseasoned (I'm from Atlanta and know great grits), but this was easily remedied by a sprinkle of the delicious flaked salt on the table.

The prices might seem a tad bit high, but I would attribute them to not only to the fact that the restaurant is in such a fantastic location, but also because the menu is almost entirely comprised of local, organic, and house-made ingredients.

text: THIS. PLACE.  I dream about this place.  First ate here in Feb when I helped my SIL move up to Goleta.  I was in heaven and could not stop thinking about the baker's basket.  It's everything I want in a breakfast.  So when my hubby and I decided to take a camping trip to Carpinteria, we of course had to swing by Renaud's.  Well, we ended up eating at this location twice and the other one on State Street once.  I can't get enough - even had to get some pastries to go and enjoy at home.  We've tried the Fried Egg Sandwich (delicious!), the bacon, egg and cheese croissant with potatoes and of course the Bakers' Basket (OJ, Coffee/Tea, toasted baguette, croissant and delicious home made jam).  The OJ is divine, and I've never had a better croissant.  Fruit was fresh, ripe and juicy.  We also ordered the french onion soup once, which was good but not as amazing as everything else they have.  Already thinking we need to plan another trip just so we can have this breakfast again.

text: in town for a kids hockey game.  rolled in late and walked in.  I've been all over, and this has to be one of the best meals I have ever had.  started with the flatbreads and a cocktail.  once seated, had the beet salad and grilled& octopus appetizers.  salad had multiple ingredients, fresh and tasty.  grilled octopus prepared perfectly, a little crispy, and not too chewy.  for main course we had the salmon and the burger.  salmon seared on outside, perfectly done inside.  served on a bed of greens.  son had the burger, very solid, fried were very top notch.  chef came over to talk repeatedly, great guy.  Highly, highly recommended.

text:
This place is so special.  

The food is really good, the drinks are amazing (try the blood orange marg!), the ambiance is incredibly romantic, and the service is OVER THE TOP! 

We loved the seasonal soup, salad, and halibut, the steak diane was just okay.  But don't skip the souffles- both delicious but the Grand Marnier with the passion fruit sauce was my fav!

Lisa is so charming, down to earth, and accommodating- she takes the place from really good to extremely memorable.

Atmosphere friendly both staff and patrons. There is a nice back patio available but it had just rained when I went to meet friends so everything was wet. 
Inside decor a little interesting, if taxidermy on walls bothers you; this is not the place for you. It is not my favorite but quite interesting to look around. There are some creative signs as well to enjoy.

text: I have been coming here for years and the atmosphere never ceases to amaze me! The food is delicious and the drinks are amazing. If you are going with a group get the vegetarian feast as appetizers to share. Highly recommend that you make reservations ahead of time as they get busy and rare to get a table for walk ins or long wait. As for the service it is usually hit or miss depending on the waiter or waitress that you get. Some are highly attentive and others have you chasing down someone to order more drinks or anything in general. The Kebob combo is the best to get when you cannot decide on the protein ( it contains lamb, chicken and beef) and the sides are generous portions which are a salad and rice. Order the garlic sauce and have it on the bread or anything else. The flavor is not too potent so you will not be smelling too much of it. Yes they have fries here as well and recommend that you get them! You cannot leave without having the baklava and the flourless chocolate cake with either tea or wine! This place is great for a special occasion group outing or date night! Great to have appetizers and drinks and or entrees.

text:
Used a Groupon for my most recent visit, I could always save some money when I have expensive tastes! Coming for lunch on a weekday is a big difference from the weekend you can find seating immediately, I prefer inside to outside you don't get stared down by seagulls and you have the excitement of the kitchen. 

The rock crab special or local crab is what to order, it takes time to eat but you don't even need the accompanying butter and cocktail sauces. Steamed fresh, the sweet crab flavor and tender meat is very nice. People in Vegas pay the price they charge here for a whole hot steaming crab, for just a couple of cold claws. I was a bit sad when I asked my crab to not be cleaned so I can get the delicious crab fat and they brought me put a squeaky clean shell anyways. The onion rings included in the special was just two large rings, just enough to be plural but what the hey better than nothing... 

The Calamari was okay, comes a good portion of coleslaw if that's your thing. We ordered with a side a fries and they brought it with onion rings. I guess the kitchen was a little off today. 

The steamed mussels are comfort food, reminds me of meals in Europe. Served in a big bowl of broth with white white, shallots and herbs that's best soaked up with the thick slice of toasted sourdough bread on the side. It's doesn't need anything else but a spritz of lemon or lime.  If you want a more filling meal I suggest going with the pasta version. 

The uni was fresh, spines still wiggling! They apparently get their shipments from the local fishermen 2-3 times a week. Jumbo sized pieces are mild in flavor, draped over slices of scallop and lime wheels atop crushed ice. The plating is pretty to look at but negatively impacts the flavor. The lime wheels impart a bitterness due to the oils in the rind and the melting ice dilutes the flavor of the already mild uni. Ice works with oysters since they are still on the half-shell. With uni this fresh you don't need the ice, for plating purposes sushi places have it figured out they use ice to stabilize the shell as a bowl and place the uni on a neutral filler medium. Eh, still the price is on point and Santa Barbara is famous for the quality of their uni.

text: Used to love to eat here almost twice a week back when it was Pokemee. Since it became Choppa Poke and got new management and staff, I have seen a sharp decline in this restaurant. Service is slow, workers mumble and seem to not care about their jobs (makes me feel like they are annoyed just to serve me). There have also been numerous times where employees either charge me the wrong price or just simply don't know how to work their own cashier equipment, needing to call a supervisor over to actually complete my simple purchase. The quality of fish has greatly decreased and portions are a fraction of what they were before. Coupled with the rising prices, it's getting ludicrous. Their doordash prices are $4 more than in store (what a scam! Almost $20 for a large!). I've noticed less and less people eating here every time I come in and it's no mystery why. Hopefully this place can get its act together soon

text: Worst restaurant experience ever. My wife and I used to come here years ago, always enjoyed the food and the great view. We finally had a chance to get out for a date night and decided to go to Moby Dicks. To start, we were seated and took the waitress 10 minutes to come over and take our drink order or for that matter even acknowledge we were there. My wife ordered the Caribbean lobster and I ordered a Alaskan rock fish dish. It took 30 minutes to get our food, the lobster was so overcooked and had the texture of a rubber ball. Waitress finally came back to our table to ask us how our food was my wife told her the lobster was very overcooked. The waitress apologized, took the lobster away and said she would bring a new one out. A few minutes later someone who identified himself as the  manager came to our table and said  he had heard we had a problem with the lobster dinner , he said the  new one would be out shortly. Not sure if this was his attempt at apologizing but he was definitely lacking in any customer service skills. About 10-15 minutes later the waitress brought out the 2nd lobster dish, this time it was so undercooked the meat was raw. My wife and I actually laughed about the experience, trying to keep our date night from being tainted by a bad experience. This time my wife told the waitress let's forget the lobster and just get the salmon. Again, about 10 minutes later the waitress came to our table and said the cook wants to know "what temperature did she want her salmon"  by this time I was so irritated by the incompetent cook, waitress and manager, I told her tell your cook she wants her fish 142 degree's (sarcastically). The fish finally came out and was about as bland as can be. We just wanted to get out of this dive and requested the check, the check came with no adjustments to the tab at all. I asked the waitress if the manager was going to make any adjustments, she replied "I will ask" she came back a few minutes later and said the manager took off 20%. 2 hours later start to finish, 3 bad dishes in a row , horrible service and 20% off and no real apology was the best they could do.... I paid the bill and we left , I have honestly never had such poor service in all my years, stay away from this place it is the definition of a Bad restaurant.

text: Disapointed to say the least.. I really try to find the good in every place and really give valid reason for why something may have not worked out. However, in this case well I have nothing! The fish in the tacos was so bland and soggy I could barely finish one. Im glad I did not order more food. The food lacked a energy and love to it that I could taste the frustration LOL. My fiance and step son liked their meals but again couldn't rave about it. I was in town as a makeup artist for a wedding and it had been long day on my feet so here is where I gave it two stars instead 1 because I'll take responsibility for my hangry attitude!! I did love my blood orange drink so much I had two. Imagine being so hungry the food isn't good and so you just get drunk!! HAHA... anyway we don't live near this restaurant but if we are in the area I won't be going again. It's a cute place great location but the food was a miss for me.

text:
Love love love! 
I came to visit Santa Barbara for 1 day and decided to have dinner here. We came in, didn't expect too much, thinking that it would just be another seafood restaurant. Boy were we wrong!
Decoration: elegant and upscale, malibu vibe (we sat indoors because it was too cold outside at around 6pm in Feb)
Staffs: nice and attentive
Food: we ordered oyster shooters, calamari, chowder (a must), seabass and seafood pasta. Oh my god. So good! (So much seafood within the pasta, great mashed potato and the price is very affordable)
Leaving feeling stuffed and satisfied. Will definitely come back again the next time I'm in SB. Thanks guys!

text: I I had a 45 minute layover at the Santa Barbara Amtrak station and I was hungry so I yelped local restaurants and was thrilled with my choice of Mony's. text:
When you enter the building, you see a long table. You order first and then find yourself a seat. Going upstairs, you can chose some seats inside or on the patio over looking the street..

I had the Brat that is a lot like a hot dog because I am not really a brat fan. With my stomach being sensitive with what I eat, I got something more on the simple side. Though, it is still yummy, I had mine with caramelized onions.  

The pretzel is very good as well. A nice golden color, the inside is very soft and tasty. You can also have a various sides to dip it in as well.  

I found the people there very nice and friendly. 

The whole place looks like a very popular place, like a place the in crowd would go to.  The inside of the building was a very I guess you can say classy place.

text:
I went here for lunch and disagree with the bad reviews.  

It was later in the afternoon  so not busy.  I had very good service.  Maybe things would have been different had I been at peak lunch time.  They had a lunch special for 9.95 where I got mango iced tea, salad, and 1/2 lasagna.  I enjoyed everything..  And as someone mentioned the garlic bread they give you before the meal is great.

I would definitely go back the next time I'm in Santa Barbara and try some of the other menu items.

text: Thought I ought to support local and use this company rather than going with a big Sparkletts or Arrowhead type outfit. Man do I regret that decision. Water itself was fine and delivery service was relatively reliable, and that's about where things end. Customer service and billing is embarrassingly poor. I had several negative interactions while under subscription to their services. At one point there was a delivery that was accidentally left at my neighbors and I was informed that I was liable for said bottles and that it was my responsibility to go retrieve them. If I didn't then they would charge me for the bottles themselves along with the water. More times than I can count on one hand I was charged late payment fees even though I never received a bill prior to the "late" one. Now, nearly two years after moving homes and ending my relationship with this company, I wake up to a collections notice in the mail. Apparently I owe them $125! First of all, if you believe I have a debt with your company (which makes no sense, but I digress), give me a call, send me an email, reach out to me and let's figure it out. You have my contact information, I've had the same phone and email for the last 20 years. Friggin debt collections, over bottled water for a household of two -- what? Seriously?? And second of all, how about dealing with this in a timely fashion and not waiting for years to pass, avoiding me all together, and then sending me to someone else to do your bidding. You all are a very sorry example of a local business. I strongly suggest anyone seeking water delivery look elsewhere. Even if it means supporting one of the big guys...as much as I hate to say that.

text:
The food is fine just don't use Santa Barbara Menu. The order took an hour and they got it wrong. I would advise to go in person to get the order correct. This is more about Santa Barbara Menus than Silvergreens. 

I had the chicken club and it was ok and the tortilla soup was good. The fries were also good. Salad looked fresh and abundant. Just don't get it delivered By Santa Barbara Menus.

Update: After thinking about it more I think giving 2 stars to Silvergreens was unfair. I'm upgrading to 4 stars as their quality of food is very good and worthy of a more positive rating. My disappointment was with Santa Barbara Menus for their inability to get the order correct and deliver in a timely manner.

text:
My review is from my visit back in April 2020.
At the time of quarantine, I was so stressed out from work that I needed to get away. 

My stay was an absolutely dream, it was only at 12% occupancy so I had the most attentive service I've ever had. It was quiet, peaceful, and a beautiful view at every corner! It was also half-off, so that was great. 

My room, of course, was gorgeous, clean, and bed was very comfy.

Because business was so slow for them at the time, I was able to rent an electric-bicycle for free. 

I know this will never happen again & this was an once in a lifetime chance, but I'm glad I got to experience at this location regardless!
Thank you for the amazing experience.

text: I have to say how disappointing I am with my experienced at this Location. I've been in and around the Restaurant business for over 30 years and Clearly the Sanitation and Customer service procedures are Very Subpar! You would think during this Pandemic that there would be some better protocols in place. So I'l make it brief, once you make it to the counter your greeted with attitude. The employees were short with me and Super inpatient. They preferred to sell me a can beer vs just pouring one from the draft as if they were just too Lazy to do so, Due to Covid there obviously is no interior seating and everyone is waiting to get a seat outside. NOT Once did I see anyone that represents the company come out to Clean and Sanitize a Table let alone clear the dirty dishes? The Trash cans were overflowing and once I got a table I knew that Clearly I would have to clean it myself. I proceeded to the counter to ask for a wet towel w/sanitizer and the girl just Gave me a Dry Towel? I personally had to use my Sanitizer Hand Spray to clean the table! The people next to us had to move the previous customers dishes aside while they ate? So to make matters worst I Contacted the company through their website to let them know there is a Serious Lack of performance from this location and they never responded. I will say this, the pizza was pretty good but there's no excuse for this lack of Service to ensure everyone's safety. Management its time to show your presence.

text:
This is my favorite place to eat in the Santa Barbara area.
It's definitely a breath of fresh air in a town that looks a bit rundown. But nevertheless, the food is fantastic, the service is great, and the scenery is very tropical. Definitely recommend if you want healthy, quality food anytime between breakfast and dinner. The teas and coffees are also great.

text: A bit of a long line to order, but the gentleman at the counter was incredibly charming and entertaining, and took our order with a great deal of panache. The quesadillas are very unusual, and quite delicious with a lot of flavor. The adobo was juicy. The shrimp quesadilla didn't need the shrimp, actually. They got a bit lost in roasted corn, salsa crudo, poblanos and more. Very tasty. Order chips and guacamole too - very crispy chips and the pepitas on the guacamole is a fresh take. Presentation is beautiful, and while we were eating, we watched the line quintuple, so best to get there early!

text: I was in town visiting family and needed to have my daughters' meds refilled so I transferred to this location. They informed me over the phone that it would be 6 hours at the earliest that my request would be filled as they were very busy. I arrived an hour before closing I arrived to pick up the prescription. The Pharmacist asked the purpose of my giving this particular medication to my 7 year old daughter, I explained the reason to which he replied "Umm yeah that is not what this medication is supposed to be used for so I am afraid I cannot give this to you." I explained that my daughter is living with Rett syndrome and that her Neurologist had prescribed this for her months ago and we had been filling our 'scrips at CVS in Sherman Oaks for months. He attempted to correct me "I believe you mean Tourette's, ma'am." I then explained that no, I did not mean TOURett's and my daughter had been in fact diagnosed with RETT syndrome - he began "correct" me over and over again that because he had never heard of Rett syndrome I was mistaken and obviously I meant TOURett's and there was no way he would be giving me the medication because HE did not believe it was being used properly. EXCUSE ME, but since when do Pharmacists argue with parents over their child/ren's diagnosis?? And SINCE WHEN do they question and refuse to fill a prescription that was ordered by a Medical DOCTOR!?!?!?! Needless to say this turned in to a screaming match. Once he looked up Rett Syndrome on his "smartphone" and looked up how this medication was used for children living with Rett syndrome he "decided" to go ahead and give me the medication. It took me nearly an HOUR of fighting and arguing while my child was at home desperately needing her medication. Pharmacist Hameed (not sure of the spelling of his name but that is his name) was awful and perhaps needs better training! The Store Manager was not interested in hearing how awful I was treated in his store. I am NOT a competitor. I am a mother of a severly disabled child that desperately needed her medication and was subjected to verbal abuse by this person

text:
3 lbs of local Rock Crab with Lobster Bisque and a Caesar Salad for $23.00 dollars . . . What's not to love? Firestone DBA on draft to go with the crab . . . even better. Fried calamari, shrimp and scallops to go with the beer . . . Sold!

We had to wait 20 minutes or so for one of the few (4) tables outside, but we ordered our food as soon as we were sat, and it was served to us less than 10 minutes later.

We enjoyed the crabs, laughed, told a few life stories and watched a beautiful sunset from the edge of the pier. We watched as sailboats continued to slip past us on into the early evening, and after enjoying a perfectly warm (74-76) January afternoon, the server turned on the overhead heaters to fend off an evening chill.

Absolutely Classic.

text: Let me start by saying the food was excellent, HOWEVER four reasons why our evening wasn't.  My husband absolutely can't eat onions.  Server said no problem.  First course salad with onions.  I offered to trade for my tart...more onions.  Server said you only said no raw onions. Strike one:  don't argue with the customer.  Server offered to bring a substitute dish.  Strike two:  we were charged for the substitute as well as the other two.  Strike three:  we waited forever for the check to be brought...restaurant half empty, near closing.  Strike four:  the leftovers that we were told would be wrapped were never brought to us.  Yes, we could have argued about the check, the leftovers, but where's the fun in that.  So while the food is really good, there are lots of other good choices in town.  Oh, and for the record, my husband was up all night with a reaction to the onions.

text: We've been members of Community Seafood for over a month now and have been delighted with the assortment of seafood sent our way.  Each week we get an email with details about that week's catch, the local fishermen who haul it in, along with a variety of tasty recipes to try.  There have been several times when we've gotten a selection we've never tried or cooked before!  This program a great way to open yourself up to try something new or unfamiliar.  Here's the best part:  I do my pickup at the Sunday (Santa Monica) Farmer's Market and all I have to do is call ahead of time and they have my order ready for me AND they bring it right out to my car!  How easy is that?!

text: We went to Carpinteria on a whim for Italian food and ended up at Sly's.  Great atmosphere.  The food was very good - we had the steaks.  My filet mignon was a slight disappointment because it was tough.  I've never had a tough filet mignon, so I was surprised.  Luckily the bernaise sauce helped with the flavor experience.  The veggie sides dishes tasted fresh and were cooked perfect.  The coconut cake was to die for and worth the extra calories!  The menu items were on the pricey side and ala carte so watch what you are ordering or you will fall off your chair when the bill hits your table.  All in all, a dining experience worthy of another visit.

text: Nice ambience to take friends from out of town - Overpriced though. The Pozole is so good, yet The last time I ordered it there were teeny, choke-worthy fragments of bones. text:
On a particularly hot day in Los Angeles, I packed up my family (husband + dog) for an afternoon of cool ocean breezes in Santa Barbara. When lunch time came around, we were having trouble finding a dog-friendly, vegan-friendly, shady patio along State St. until we crossed Patxi's. Pizza! Vegan cheese! Shady, dog-friendly patio! Organic wine options! We were sold.

We were seated immediately. Our waitress was so friendly and accommodating, bringing a water bowl for Marty and walking us through the menu. We each ordered our own 10" thin crust pizzas, which we completely devoured. A light breakfast and lots of walking definitely made us hungry, but the crust was also perfectly thin, so we never felt overly stuffed. I'd ordered a make-your-own pizza with daiya, basil, roasted garlic, and kalamata olives. They'd forgotten the olives, which was honestly fine, the pizza was still delicious without them, and our waitress made sure they weren't on our final bill, which I really appreciate.

I love that they have a vegan deep dish pizza on the menu, that is so cool! We were too hungry to wait for deep dish this time (it takes about 40 minutes), but I'd definitely return to try it. I also loved my glass of Horse & Plow wine, which is Californian, vegan, and organic, a triple threat!

I'd come back here even if I didn't have Marty in tow. The patio was great for people watching and there's lots of shade to escape the hot sun. I'm a fan!

I would not recommend them to anyone as their philosophy is about The Almighty Buck.

text:
Goleta, California is simply gorgeous.   I've visited one time before and had a blissful lunch at the Natural Cafe and did Laundry at the Lucky Coin Mat not too far.  This shopping center is HUGE!!  There's Costco, Lowe's or Home Depot. Can't remember which one. A slew of restaurants and then it ends but does it?

It doesn't unofficially. Just past the McDonalds on the other side is the Lucky Coin Mat, The French Press, Chipotle and Rusty's Pizza and if you blinked you would have missed Lilly's Taqueria. 

YOU SHOULD NOT BLINK. 

Go find Lilly's and get there before noon or get ready to wait in line. I walked in 8 minutes to noon and was the only patron waiting in line.  Ten minutes later and the line was 20 deep with locals. 

I usually have a set of rules when dinning out

 1. Menu better be small 
2. If locals eat there, it's good enough for me 
3. Got to have vegetarian and vegan options or the ability to customize. 

Lily's has all three. 

It's a simple taqueria, so don't over think it.  Get your tacos and get them with the works.  Each taco has two little corn tortillas that are made right on site.  There's all the meat choices and veggies tacos.  For the vegans like me, double check the rice, beans, and oil.  

They'll ask you if you want onions and cilantro. For heavens sake say yes.  Why ?  They don't dump a dump truck amount of onions and cilantro like some place.  It's like the Taco Gods gently sprinkled the right amount.  Then head over the salsa bar.  Not sure which one you may like, ask. Lilly's Team is there to help you.  The Green  is good. Like really good but the Orange is down right devilish.  

I wish we had a Lilly's Taqueria here because of its legit factor.  

Just remember don't blink and get there before noon, you'll thank me later

text: The best Japanese food I've ever had (and I used to live in the Bay Area)!  If you appreciate refined flavors, beautiful and tasteful dishes, and want a dinner experience, this place is it.  Not many places do food like this (kaiseki  style; 7-course meals), so SB is fortunate to have this place here near downtown.  While pricey ($85/person) it's worth it, particularly for a special occasion.   I plan to go again as the menu changes each month.

text: Wow. I'm not sure where to start. Have not had service this bad ever. Made me want to write a review and usually my reviews are good. I feel bad for the server because I think the server actually knew how bad the service was.  The server forgot to take drink order  and then forgot our drinks. The server forgot our quacamole, forgot our silverware My brother in-law sat with his enchiladas getting cold because he had no fork. The server forgot my sisters beans, forgot our soups. I think he forgot almost everything. Once the food came out it was so good we actually could only joke about the bad service and enjoyed the great view of the beach. Until the server knocked my sisters cocktail all over her and class shattered all over the floor. Maybe it was an off day for the server, or maybe the server really was that bad at waiting tables. We felt so bad for the server we still decided to tip. I still gave 3 stars because the food really was decent and we were seated quickly but I would prefer a different server next time.

text:
First time here, and I'm very happy to find a great cafe in Old Town! I'm in the SF Bay Area, so when I visit family in Goleta I normally head to Handlebar in SB. Very different places but this place holds its own against that SB favorite. 

First, nailed the coffee. Only one selection of pour over,  it it came in its own Hario Coffee Server and hit the spot. A couple options would be an improvement, especially when jonesing for a particular bean/region. 

They have lots of food selections, mostly local and fresh. I had a carne empanadas. Yum. I want another and I want to try all their others! Also have pastries and vegan options, as well as fresh fruit. 

Ambiance is modern/hip with lots of photos of old town that give it a sense of place. Gender neutral restrooms, a take/leave book station, cornhole & pong, as well as plentiful and comfy indoor & outdoor seating hits all the marks for families, adults, couples and solo visitors (which I was on this day). 

Overall a strong 4 or 4.5 for me, but they hit the 5-star mark with avocado based straws (a real thing), reusable mugs & glassware, as well as reusable plates & trays. Sustainability is critical and important to me as a consumer, so given the fact that I was ready to walk out and skip coffee is they couldn't give me a reusable mug (cuz I forgot mine like an idiot), I was pleasantly surprised to see them hit so many sustainability marks!

text:
If you love the kind of place where the owner flirts subtly with you, everyone knows you by name and even has the order down to memorization, D'vine is simply divine. Granted, I did order the same thing everytime, sometimes multiple times a week, so it's logical they would take note. 

I remember to review this place today as I am strongly craving a for my former mainstay:! A quick walk from my former Nordstrom squallor, D'vine became my weekly lunch spot for one thing alone: THE CHICKEN SALAD SANDWICH. I'm sorry, but I have not had a single one that comes close to smokin' this location's. Made from scratch every morning, they throw in an additional spice (that I have yet to discover exactly what it is) and will serve it with all the toppings you want. My suggestion: mustard, sprouts, onion, lettuce, and havarti cheese on sourdough. Creamy goodness with a slight crisp. 

I've tried the items there, and they're all good. But nothing compares to my signature sandwich. I hate getting cravings for it now that I live so far away. 

Plus: They sell IT's-IT, which I haven't really been able to find anywhere else in SB as it's too much of a Bay Area thing.

Fun fact: the name of the place comes from the cross street, De La Vina, or so I've been told by the staff.

text: My daughter decided to have her graduation dinner at Sama Kitchen, we got there a bit late for our reservation and there was no problem. Our server explained how the food would come as it was ready and not necessarily at the same time or together. When the plates started to come, the presentation, the taste was all on point. It encouraged us to keep ordering more & more. The noodle bowl appetizer was very so delicious, and although I'm not a fan of chicken wings usually they were the best thing I have ever tasted that we ordered another order right after! Although the steak was a little bit expensive for the amount you get it was great. A great part of their service was they allowed us to bring our own cake. Overall, it was an excellent first experience for all seven of us with who all held different expectations!

text:
Possibly the worst customer service I've experienced at a hotel. We requested a room with a crib and toddler bed, checked in at 5, four phone calls, 4 1/2 hrs and exhausted screaming kids later it was finally brought to our room. Ordered room service and it came missing an order twice. Called for someone to pick up our bags and it took 45 minutes. The other two parties we were with had similar experiences. 

Property is beautiful, employees are very nice and proximity to Santa Barbara are all pluses, too bad they can't seem to get their act together or it would be a fantastic place to stay.

text:
I really wanted to give this place 4 stars if not only for the name of the menu items but also the types of food they serve. A normal person may give it 4 stars, but for me the verdict is 3. 

I ordered the YOLO with poached egg. I expected amazing. I mean, who can turn down poached egg, buttermilk biscuit, fried chicken and gravy?

The idea is great. Execution not so much. 

Chicken was more of a thin cutlet, instead of savory chicken breast you'd expect. Biscuit tasted absolutely perfect and egg was cooked right. I could have dealt with the chicken but the gravy was overwhelming. I'm from the south, and trust me, I'm used to gravy. 

However, it was almost like they threw the meal into a full bowl of gravy. The gravy was okay in taste but when the gravy takes up more of the bowl than all the other ingredients you have a problem. 

Id give this place another shot. After all, their Benedict (tugboat) looked amazing as they were prepping it for another customer. I'd have ordered that but I was already mentally and physically committed to the YOLO. 

TIP: if weather is not great, very limited seating (and no ambience) inside. It has the feel of a large storage locker. Outside area looks nice, so go when it's nice out.

text: Walked into Savoy on a Friday afternoon and it was quite busy. I got in line for the turkey pozole rojo, scooped a spoon of soup and got a huge surprise - a long black hair inside my soup and it was also hanging outside of my cup. I walked to the front counter and handed the cup to an employee, told them that I found a long hair inside the pozole. I told the employee that they need to move the pozole soup immediately from the soup station because it's disgusting and contaminated. The employee said yes and walked to the back of the kitchen, came out a couple seconds later and carried on with the customers. I waited for 3 minutes to see if any they were going to remove the soup, nope. Will not be eating here anymore, super disappointed.

text:
I had high hopes, left sad.  Not sure how it's 4 stars, maybe Sushi Terry staff & family get bonuses to post reviews.

I got a 1/2 dozen oysters and asked for the sauce on the side, in case I didn't like the "Asian sauce & hot sauce" they told me it came with, I requested cocktail sauce and horseradish on the side.  I was told no problem.  The oysters came with what I believe was ponzu and a chili paste on them, I asked why it wasn't on the side and where's the cocktail sauce, the food runner told me they don't have cocktail sauce.  What seafood place doesn't have cocktail sauce??  What's even stranger was the raw oysters were warm, I pray I don't get sick.

The clam chowder came in a thick, small, coffee cup, with a plastic spoon.  WTF?  It was thick and so so, not delicious like the Crocodile, Brophys and Lure.  How much were the warm oysters no where close to prepared the way I ordered and the worlds smallest cup of clam chowder with a plastic spoon??  22.00, lol.

Do not waste your money if going for clam chowder and oysters.  The other food may be great, the items I got suck.  I only give it 2 stars because some of the other items I saw people eating looked good.

text:
Great happy hour choice!  It gets very packed, so best to come early.  It's right by the urban wine tasting trail, so if you're looking for something to do you can always do a couple tastings and then time it so that you make happy hour at Enterprise!

I came with two friends after a tasting at LaFond across the street.  We sat in the bar area for happy hour and ordered off the happy hour menu and had a very good experience!  The oysters were great at $1.50 each and the house wine was only $4.50 a glass and the pours were generous.  We also ordered oyster shooters, which I wouldn't recommend - stick to the oysters.  They just had too much cheese on the top and made it difficult to eat.  My favorite item we ordered were the shishito peppers and the steamed mussels.  Ask for extra bread to dip in the broth the mussles comes with!

We will definitely return.

text: Arigato is by far my favorite Sushi Restaurant in Santa Barbara. While it is a little pricey (what good restaurant in SB isn't?), their sushi is fresh and their rolls are deliciously creative. text:
This place is adorable! I came here for breakfast with my friends while visiting UCSB. I ordered the turkey chili and tuna melt. Oh my goodness was it delicious. I don't eat beef so I was really happy to see a chili i could eat. It was so flavorful but not too salty. I still crave it to this day! I love love love tuna melts and CrushCafe's tuna melt definitely met my expectations!

We also shared the red velvet pancakes. Now, I've never had red velvet pancakes so I don't know if I'm qualified to rate red velvet pancakes BUT they were delicious nonetheless. They weren't soggy, perfectly round and delicious! 

If i'm ever back in Santa Barbara, I will definitely be back to try more of the menu :)

text:
My fianc and I stopped in here on our way up north. It's a really cute coffee shop off of the main road. We found parking on the street right in front of the shop. 

They have a big variety of baked goods - savory and sweet. They also have your typical coffee shop drink options. 

I got a chai tea latte and the beef empanada. The beef empanada was delicious! I would definitely get that again. The chai tea latte was not that great. It tasted very watered down. 

My fianc got a tea with the prosciutto cheese empanada and the croissant cinnamon roll. Both of these were delicious as well!

I would be back for the empanadas but would probably try another drink next time.

text:
Welcome to Goleta, Sp & Js! I have been waiting anxiously for Kyle's Kitchen's new annex to open for business. Like myself, the owner was in awe of Barcelona's Mercat de la Boqueria and was apparently inspired to create a local "Grab N Go Market". Besides the colorful image of la Boqueria on the wall, it cannot even compare. The closest thing within the US would be the Pike Place Market in Seattle. Nonetheless, it is nice to have a somewhere to stop to/from work or during errands for a quick snack or meal. They offer several things:
-Homemade Soups: Beef Chili with Beans, New England Clam Chowder, Lasagna Soup with Turkey Sausage, Chicken Enchilada Soup, Chicken & Wild Rice Soup, Organic Ancient Grain Minestone, Thai Chicken Soup, Roasted Red Pepper with Smoked Gouda and Tomato Basil Soup. 
Keep in mind that only 6 are offered hot, while more recipes are only available in the refrigerator and by the pint.
-Salads, Sandwiches, Sides & Pastries: Since they had just opened, there was only a Ceasar Salad and a few sides available including mashed sweet potatoes, cauliflower, and mac n cheese. They only had an area for sweet pastries including cookies, brownie's and morning items.
-Juice: All the juices are made the same day of fresh fruit and vegetables. They have a deal of buy 5, get the 6th for free. Plus, there's a little to-go carrier that holds multiple bottles.
-Hot Beverages: They serve Handlebar Coffee and Steep Tea by Bigelow.

I'm a big fan of soups so having another option besides Natural Cafe and Panera is a plus. While the Chicken and Wild Rice Soup was a bit bland, the Lasagna Soup made up for it with plenty of flavor. I paired the soups with a Hot Brisket sandwich which was decent but would have been better with a sauce or aioli. I had to add my own horseradish sauce from home.

A few things to note:
-S&J is connected to Kyle's Kitchen. They're open 10AM-8PM daily.
-You can order online in advance and have the food ready to pick up. This is ideal since they only have one sandwich grill to warm them up and it can take some time.
-I was hoping for a baguette or bread bowl to pair with the soups. Idea for the future perhaps?

text:
I was thoroughly impressed with Due Lune. 
I went for lunch today for the first time and right when I walked in I noticed that they take care of their restaurant, making sure all the details are just right. The atmosphere feels classy and clean, but also cozy and warm at the same time. 

The location is prime, I chose to sit right next to the window overlooking the wharf, the street, the palm trees, and the beach. Great view for a lunch, I must say. 

First of all, the service is outstanding. The staff were so friendly and consistently made sure I was taken care of. My coffee was re-filled 4 times over the course of the hour I was there without me ever asking, and I was never left without a full glass of water. 

Now for the food: 
The bread basket gets its own mention considering it's very fresh and comes with olive oil and vinegar, a spinach spread, and olives. I didn't try the olives because I don't like olives in general, but the spinach spread was AMAZING. I didn't even know what it was when I first tried it, and was very surprised to find out it was spinach! But it was delicious. I'm pretty sure I ate the whole thing. 

I ordered the Penne All'Arrabbiata which is penne pasta with a spicy tomato sauce and roasted garlic. YUM. The spice was just right (If you order this, I suggest peppering it up which enhances the pasta even more) and the roasted garlic was roasted to perfection. They also brought out my very own PARMESAN CHEESE BOWL so I could add MY OWN CHEESE TO MY LIKING. 
Even the portion was more than enough (although that might have been the bread baskets fault), but usually with nicer Italian restaurants like this, the portions are super tiny in a tiny pasta bowl and it's disappointing. But nope! Not this one! I brought home the leftovers and I cannot wait to eat them. 

Any way, long story short, I'll definitely be coming back, and can't wait to try more entrees, and also all of the happy hour menu.

text:
I have long been a fan of Cioppino.  This was the best I've ever had by far.  Great sauce with abundant shellfish.  The sauce is not the usual thin fish broth served with Cioppino.  It's a tomatoey masterpiece.  

Lots of tourists here, but the quality is still great.  This place is quite informal; not a place for a romantic dinner, but a fun place for a good meal.  Try to get a seat at one of the stools facing the kitchen.  It's really quite a sight to see the "maestro" keeping up with the dinner rush. This place was busy, but worth the wait.  I'll be back soon.

text: Mesa Verde's number one yelp rating in Santa Barbara is well deserved! The menu is full of delicious and affordable vegetarian options. We had the BLTA and potato latkes which were both great. They also have a large selection of interesting drink options like teas, smoothies and kombucha. Our food came our super fast but our tea was a little behind it; our server gave us a free dessert though for our trouble (the baklava was maybe the best I've had!) the only negative is the small parking lot, but there is plenty of parking around the corner.

In order to not further be an inconvenience we opted go elsewhere.

text:
Usually when I'm with friends and have a great time, I'm generous with the stars.  Nikka Fish Market and Grill is not one of those places.

We all had crab salads.  I don't eat a lot of crab salads.  I probably haven't eaten a crab salad in 20 years!  I was disappointed.  The crab was tasteless.  There salad part was iceberg lettuce.  They included the large bitter spines of the iceberg lettuce head in the salad.  It wasn't a cheap salad monetarily - but certainly as to quality.

Later one of my companions who has a fetish for seafood commented on the salad:  "They used canned crab on that salad!"  Eh?  Yes they did!  When I looked at the salad I had the suspicion:  "How come the crab is all the same appearance and the pieces are the same size on each of the four plates?"  Answer:  Because they used canned crab.

Nikka's has several businesses in that area.  I live in Sonoma County, so the loss of my patronage will mean nothing to the Nikka family; but I'm done with Nikka restaurants.

text:
On the spur of the moment, we signed up for this tour.
Two of the venues were on Stern's Wharf.
The others (like 6-8 others!) were in The Funk Zone, an eclectic mix of architecture styles, characters, businesses, and  FOODS.
Our tour was led by the company's owner, Terra, and she was extremely knowledgeable and friendly. She knows a lot about Sta. Barbara's history.
We sampled wines at 2 places; sparkly at another; and spirits (vodka, gin - wow! - bourbon, and apple pie whiskey) at yet another site; ceviche; chorizo/potato/egg pizza; beer and ice cream 'milk'shakes; toffee; chicken and waffles...and I'm sure I'm missing a few.
I would say the photography information was minimal and would not advise those looking for professional tips to expect professional advice.
But would I recommend this tour to others?
Yes. An unqualified YES.
Don't plan on eating much more than a small cookie for dinner; you'll be full.

He said it was fine with a bad attitude. When I picked up my food, someone else wanted to order and he gave her the same bad experience. She also was confused and asked if they were closed because he made it so obvious that he was annoyed she was wanting to order. Lock the doors and/or tell people KINDLY that you are closed. Easy. This type of blah attitude has been my experience every time.

text:
I love Via Vai's. We order to go all the time. They can have a pizza ready for me by the time I get there and we live 5 minutes away. They are fast and delicious. Their pizzas are the best traditional pizzas you can ask for. When my stomach is acting up one of the few foods I can still eat and enjoy is their margarita pizza. it has enough flavor to be delicious but is so easy on my stomach. I almost always order a pizza even if its not what I order for dinner because their pizzas are even amazing when cold a few hours later and make great snacks. 

The restaurant is also nice and very authentic, we don't each in much but when we do the experience is great.

Their outdoor seating area is heated and just as comfortable as inside. On a nice day eating outside at Via Vais really lets you take in the view of the mountains and its just a wonderful experience all around.

text:
Rori's, I love you! And yes, I must say, after much deliberation, you ARE my favorite creamery in Santa Barbara County! I'm sorry McConnells, Rori's has stolen my heart! 

This location is dangerously located just down the road from our home, so I have a feeling they'll be seeing much more of us in the days and weeks to come. 

Most recently, I opted for my favorite Biscoff Ice Cream, atop a freshly baked, warmed brownie, drizzled with house made caramel sauce. It was heavenly! Can you feel your mouth watering as you read about it? I can, just like Pavlov's dog! Yes, it's that good! 

I also love the Brown Sugar Banana ice cream! Pair it will the brownie and caramel sauce that I mentioned earlier and you'll have yourself an incredible dessert that rivals the flavors of even the most decadent bananas foster you've very tried. 

They also make ice cream cookie sandwiches with freshly baked cookies and have multiple gluten free baked options to choose from as well. 

Not in Montecito? No problem! There is a downtown location located inside the Public Market at Chapala Street and Victoria Ave, so go check them out!

text:
This restaurant is located across the beach.  Even pre Covid, we always asked to sit outdoors.  The ambiance is nice as you can see the beach across the street and the tall palm trees.  When it gets a little chilly, you can ask them to turn on heaters.  Our waiter was attentive.  He made sure that we had what we needed.

We came here for dinner.  My husband and I ordered their home made pasta and we were not disappointed:  
~Guinzaglio | 7 hour veal bolognese & Parmigiano   
~Bucatini | pancetta, chile, crushed tomato, pecorino
 
We ended our sinner with Lemon Sorbet.  So refreshing!

text: Just spent 4 nights here.  Great location next to the beach.  Nice pool area.  Rooms are ok - decent size, decent aesthetics but seems expensive for what you get.  I did not do a full comparison to other hotels in the area but at $279/night weekdays and $369/night weekends, it seems overpriced for the quality of the place.  One major disappointment was that the sink smelled horrible every time we put the water on.  Smelled like a sewer.  Very frustrating that when I checked out and explained this to the front desk, there was no comment other than "sorry" nor any attempt to make good.  Overall, a nice place but a bit pricey for what they offer.

text:
This place by far has the best almond croissants!!! Flaky buttery goodness! Also ordered their fried egg sandwich, egg, ham and cheese croissant, and omelette. All were standard but the croissant itself from the sandwich was also amazing. 

Was disappointed with the fried egg sandwich though. For some reason, the pain de mie it came on was covered in lint so was too grossed out to eat it. Ended up eating just the tomato, egg, and bacon. 

Would be back for their croissants/pastries.

text:
This is the mecca of ice cream parlors. The ice cream itself is the best in the world. The best flavors to try are classics like Golden State Vanilla, Mint Chip, Santa Barbara Strawberry, Coconut Cream, Sweet Cream, and Salted Caramel Chip. Fun foodie flavors are also worth trying. Unlimited samples, so go ahead and try a bunch.  

People go mad for the house made Sea Salt Chocolate Chip Cookies, perfect, and literally made for an ice cream sandwich.  

The sundaes are awesome. I recommend the Apple Compote, Banana Split, Churros con Sundae, and the Cold Brew Mockiato shake. I wish I could go here everyday of my life. That good..

text:
This is just a fun place to go and a great overall experience.  The line out the door is actually somewhat welcome, because there was a live band outside (probably just some local guys playing instruments and having fun) and they have random instruments (tambourine, moraccas? a washboard and a spoon?) that they pass out to the people in line.  On the inside, once every hour or hour and a half they play the song "It's a Wonderful World" and everybody is supposed to sing along and toast, including the staff.  Good times.

The only reason I'm not rating it a full 5 stars is the food.  The assortment of muffins was cool and most of them were pretty tasty, but the entrees weren't that great.  The Chicken Tchoupitoulas has a really really thick sauce, almost like a gravy, and tastes almost like cheese, mustard, and wine.  It's not bad, but it is different and not really outstanding.  The Jambalaya pasta was ok, but I probably should have gone with the traditional Jamabalaya over rice.  Of course, we needed to finish it off with the souffle, which was pretty tasty, but not overly sweet.

text: Pretty disappointing. I've been wanting to eat here for several years based on what I thought was a great reputation in town.  I don't get over to the Mesa much but when I saw a coupon in a mailed flyer a couple months ago, I clipped it.  It offered a free entree with purchase of one entree and two drinks. Even with a discount of $12, the bill was $53 for lunch (before tip) -- I can eat a great dinner out for less than this -- so I was expecting a very delicious meal.  Both my companion and I felt the food was vastly overpriced for the quality, flavor and even presentation. The quantity was generous enough but the items we ordered (empanadas and the mushroom burger) were both rather bland.  The "burger" was served on a doughy, barely cooked pita-like bread rather than on an appropriate item to hold a messy burger in place like a brioche bun.  It was completely falling apart after a few bites... which would have been okay to eat with a fork except it was just not flavorful or complex given the list of ingredients. The most interesting item was the ketchup made from beets.  Also the side fries weren't thoroughly cooked except for the smallest ones.  Definitely not a $24 item! The empanadas were somewhat better but again, not a 'wow' and not even a 'hey, really tasty.' Just bland and again, not worth $24.  The half-off discount didn't even cover the $13 cost of a chai tea and lemonade (that was mostly ice of course).  All in all, very disappointing food and therefore completely overpriced.  We took the food to go so I cannot really comment on the service. When I read another lengthy review (12/5/21), I now see that the prices have been jacked and the quality has been wavering. I totally understand the precarious state of the restaurant business right now during covid but I cannot recommend this restaurant at this time.

text:
We are 3 days into our 7 day stay, and I've had better experiences at Holiday Inn Express. To start with, we requested a double queen room and upon check-in, were told that we would have to switch rooms the next day because only a king room was available. Okay. The next day, they told us all the double queen rooms were booked for the next 6 days, so we were SOL. 

Please, if I'm going to spend my "vacation" sharing a bed with my wiggly 4 year old, I need some serious advanced notice to prepare. We also requested a crib ahead of time for the baby, but it wasn't there when we checked in, and took over an hour to arrive. Which meant bedtime was delayed even further after a long day of travel. 

Service is also horrible. No one seems to be happy to be working here, and no one listens. One afternoon, I requested clean towels and a bathroom cleanup. They said someone would be right there. 12 hours later, and we still hadn't seen anyone. Meanwhile I'm cleaning the bathroom floor with baby wipes, and the filth that came up made me doubt that it ever got mopped. 

I verified beforehand that the restaurants had gluten-free options (I have celiac disease), but then got to the Bistro only to see the gluten-free label on items that obviously contained gluten like farro and orzo. I've been terrified to eat on-site ever since. 

We were given a trail map when we arrived, but upon trying to go for a walk, found that trail heads weren't marked and it was hard to tell a service road from a hiking trail. 

I could go on, but I won't. I've never stayed at a Ritz before, and likely won't again. The Fairmont chain blows you guys out of the water.

text:
This is a good classic pizza parlor spot without the classic dank. It has a nice large salad bar, beer on tap, and arcade games.  I thought the pizza was good, not stellar but pretty good. 

The place is very bright and has a whole lot of TVs. The televisions were a bit overwhelming for the family. We were there with the kids and half of the 10 large screen televisions surrounding the small room were showing news or several with some stories of abductions. The other half were sports. We did ask to switch the channels to something more kid friendly (since there were no other patrons facing the way we were) and they switched it to more news (more sports would have been preferable or maybe cartoons or something). Anyway, the food was good enough that I would go back, but for take-out next time.

The food was good - but pricey. It was a special occasion so we gave it a shot. I'm not anticipating we'll be running back anytime soon.

text:
No need to park on the street since parking on the Pier is free for the first 90 minutes then $2.50 for the first 30 min or 1hr afterwards.  Parking can be hard to find though since the pier is small. We had a table of 3 and had to wait around 45min to get seated at the bar.  Although the line was long, a lot of people were not there when they called out names.  There is a take out window on the side of the building and people can eat at the tables nearby. In addition to the regular menu, theres a specials menu inside the restaurant

With so much time to look at the menu while we waited we were ready to order when we got seated.  We first started with the clam chowder which had a spice that was overpowering of the soup but they do give a generous amount of ingredients.  

Jonny, our server, recommended the shrimp and scallop pasta over the crab sandwich.  They give a decent portion of pasta, shrimp and scallops but the dish lacked flavor even with the side of cheese.

Lobster roll - not like the lobster rolls I've had in LA or the E. coast with the large pieces of lobster.  

Cioppino - great that it comes with the half portion of crab but I wish there was more soup in the inside of the bread bowl and soup could have been better.

Live uni with scallop and lime - Best dish of the meal.  Didn't think the lime was needed but it was cool to watch the juice make the sea urchin move around when you put the juice on it.

text:
I was beyond excited when this place opened up. The location is perfect as I dreaded driving to IV to try the other hot pot place AND there is a parking lot. 

I went here with a friend and we both got their popular spicy broth, it was listed as the spiciest one but it really isn't that spicy. We got the beef version and it was delicious! They give you tons of meat and tons of cabbage which I love. The only con I have is that the soup for some reason has this very strong vinegar/tart after taste in your mouth. I'm not sure if it's from the broth or from one of the dipping sauces but that was the only thing I really didn't like. 

We also ordered a rose milk tea and a Hokkaido milk tea. Both were good but just a tad bit too sweet. They do however use a reusable like cup which is awesome. I'm not sure if you bring it back they will give you a discount on your next drink order, that would be really smart to help decrease plastic waste. 

All in all it was a really great experience and we will definitely be coming back. If you plan on coming here plan for at least an hour as we tried to do it on our lunch break and that was definitely not enough time. Once their servers get up to speed on the menu, I'm sure the customer service will be better.

text:
Andersens is a fascinating place on State street. Cute decor makes it very different than any other bakery in SB. The pastry cases are lined with generous and beautiful looking delicacies. 

For dinner we had salmon risotto and the Hoekeboeuf (spelling?). It was basically an in-housed ground beef patty. Good beef and yummy veggies. 

We also had the strawberry fields forever cake. Delicious!
Great outdoor seating and friendly staff.

text: This place really wouldn't be so horrible if the staff wasn't so RUDE. My boyfriend and I came here because we are new in town and wanted to try out some barbecue, not to mention the "fried Mac and cheese" listed on the menu drew quick to my eye. Anyways, our waiter comes to us and takes our order. We order the fried okra as an appetizer, when 10 minutes later, our waiter comes to the table--"here's your order of hushpuppies"..."no," I told him "we ordered the fried okra." The waiter proceeded to ARGUE back and forth with me, trying to tell me that I didn't order fried okra. This got to the point where my boyfriend had to raise his voice at the man because he was being so disrespectful to me. After he rudely took the food back to kitchen, we were asked what we'd like as an entree. Immediately I asked the waiter if I could have the fried Mac and cheese (my absolute favorite, and part of the reason we went to the BBQ company) he told me that they didn't have the fried Mac and cheese available anymore, and he just HAD to tell me that even if they did, I wouldn't be able to get it because it was a kids menu item. Ugh. I had just about had it with this ignorant prick. We ended up leaving early considering this waiter had literally ruined our night. The food was not horrible but not great at all. Definitely not worth it to suffer through the poor service. We will NEVER be coming here again.

text: Have been to The Lark twice in the last several months.  The first time I would have given it 4 stars. Second time 2.75 to be exact :) I can't recall what we had the first visit but I do remember almost everything being pretty tasty. Maybe one item of 5 I would not order again. Second visit the only 2 of the 6 items I can recommend.. The really moist and just barely sweet cornbread with honey chile butter. More butter than needed so it was pretty hard not to just spoon it up at the end.  Also I can recommend the pineapple upside down dessert. Tart berry sauce, dense cake and pineapples and what seemed like a minty cream,  all so good and balanced portion. Now for the bad news... Crab risotto.  I really went out on a limb order this because I love crab just all alone and risotto is often so heavy but, I thought, it's almost ways delicious how could it go wrong. Well,  rename it "saltless long grain rice porridge with  mushrooms of little flavor' and you now have an accurate description. There was no visible crab and no crab flavor. Only mushrooms. No flavor of the Sea at all.  Odd. We only ate about 1/3 of the dish. I have noticed that the crab, in general, in California doesn't have as much flavor as the gulf coast or the Northwest. Then we had duck confit, it was ok,  a little dry.  Have had much better. Bibb salad... Enormous, could feed 5,there were only two of us,  just prep accordingly, too much guilt leaving so much on the plate.  Leaving on a positive note,  the atmosphere is just wonderful, especially the patio,servers were friendly and attentive.  Will go again but just for drink, app and atmosphere.

text:
This place has one thing going for it that the other Pho places in Goleta do not:

Delivery.

The downsides to delivery: 
You need to order $15 minimum. 
_Do not_ expect the driver to have change.  
It takes a while because the delivery sometimes requires them to pull staff from the store.

The upsides:
The beef is stored in the broth that entire time.  Unless you want your meat rare and bloody, it tasted really, really good that way.

For the actual menu, the Vietnamese and Korean menus are pretty good.  Some of the veggies/fungi in the Bibimbap are a little too chewy though.  

I have not tried the Chinese menu other than the appetizers--nothing there I can't get somewhere else.

text:
I don't review chains.   I would always give them a three,   McDonalds; 3, Subway; 3, Taco Bell; 3, In ' Out; 3 (ok, 4).  Anyway, you get the picture.    But this Starbucks is different and while every other Starbucks in the world would probably get a three this one gets a four.  Let me explain:

It's not for the service, in fact the girl who gave me my coffee was kind of rude.  The coffee and the pastries look like any other Starbucks so no extra points there.   It is the people watching!   Wow!   The place is packed and it is full of a very diverse and amazingly entertaining group of people.  Think people who are staying at the Biltmore for a bachelorette party having their coffee before they jump on a fancy wine tasting bus.  A few Westmont students, some CEO of some company, an old guy who is always there, a few assorted crazy people and maybe a celebrity or two.  Some think that they are privileged and seem to be annoyed to be waiting for their coffee with all the common folks.

So if you are REALLY reading Yelp to find out if Starbucks is a good place to go for a cup of coffee, go there (or come here since I am sitting here now.)  You will certainly be amused.  

Wow, and as I sit here, some old guy just asked me if I would mind moving, he told me I am in his seat!!!!   Can you believe it?    I LOVE this place!

text:
One of the recent reviews said this place ruined Mexican food for me, and i couldn't agree more. This place was so delicious that is has become the new measuring stick for other mexican places. Its seriously so good that as i write this im eating the leftovers of my room temperature burrito because my hotel room has no microwave, and its STILL DELICIOUS. 

I got the fajita burrito, and it was amazing. Some people prefer more steak in theres, (my girlfriend thought it had too much beans/cheese) but i still had steak in every bite. The freshness of the veggies, guac, sour cream and steak was amazing. You could literally taste the freshness. My girlfriend got the mojito burrito with green sauce on top, and that was also delicious. 

The only things I did not like about this place is the rice (it was mediocore) and the prices. The prices are intimidating at first for  aplace thats not a sit down place but the food is well worth it!

text: We tried this for dinner during Restaurant Week, and were entirely pleased.  The dining room is not very nice -- looks more like a cafeteria or diner, but the outside dining area was lovely, so we chose that. It was well heated with overhead gas heaters for a chilly February night, and gas lamps made it very atmospheric.  Our server was friendly and enthusiastic, and checked on us as often as we would have wanted. the only complaint about the service is that we asked for salt several times, and never got it.  The food was terrific.  Lamb meatballs and Stinco (braised pork shank) were divine, and the artichokes and the sausage and fennel pizza were delish, too.  A single glass of Babcock Pinot Noir, at $12, was a nice deep pour, and went well with all the dishes, so we ordered a carafe to continue.  And the Lemon Tart for dessert was to die for:  flaky crust, light and lemony custard, with a pretty meringue topping.  The menu prices were fair for the size of portions, quality of food, and presentation.  We will return!

text:
Great view, decent food, cute waitresses

I came here for lunch, ordered some lobster mac & cheese and some seared ahi. For the price i could have gotten more ahi, but it didnt really matter because the view on the roof deck was amazing and the cute waitresses were very nice to watch.

Im definitely coming back here on saturday night and drinking alittle :o)

text: Everything is better here . Coffee is better , butter is better , iced tea is better , and that's the little things you just hope are nice. I have been her several time and have watched everyone around me eating with enthusiasm. Personally I LOVED the Blacked Salmon omelette with home potatoes and a side of sourdough toast. It's great with a few forkfuls of my husbands chilaquiles and a small piece of my friend Tri tip and a slice of my Papas extra crispy bacon ;)   There's no wrong choice here. Everyone loves this place. Plan on a wait if you're going at a normal time. It's well worth it !
